</PRE>
<P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>I. Overview</H2>
<HR>
<BR>
<H3>Research</H3>
The current aim of the research at the Nobel Institute for Neurophysiology
is to explore how the nervous system generates vertebrate behaviour in
molecular, cellular and neuronal network terms. The roles of <STRONG>ion
channels</STRONG> in different neurones (El Manira, Hill, Wall&eacute;n and
&Aring;rhem) and of <STRONG>synaptic transmission</STRONG> (Brodin,
Christenson and Wall&eacute;n) have been explored.  Behaviour is produced
by <STRONG>networks of nerve cells. Locomotion</STRONG>, including the
vestibular control of body orientation (Grillner, Orlovski, Deliagina, El
Manira and Wall&eacute;n) and <STRONG>respiration</STRONG> (Yamamoto) is
studied. To understand the basic principles of these neural networks, the
<STRONG>patterns of interaction between identified nerve cells</STRONG>
have been mapped and <STRONG>realistic computer simulations</STRONG> are
used to reveal the mode of operation of vertebrate neuronal networks. The
respiratory analysis has focused on the<STRONG> ontogeny of the respiratory
control</STRONG> system (Lagercrantz and Yamamoto). <STRONG>The development
of voluntary and postural motor control </STRONG>in normal infants is also
investigated as well as that of prematurely born or brain damaged children
(Forssberg). The human brain was investigated at the system's level with
<STRONG>positron emission tomography</STRONG>, magnetic resonance
tomography and at the microscopical level (Roland and Guly&aacute;s)<P>

<BR>
<H3>Techniques and Collaboration</H3>
With the broad problems addressed by the different research groups a
variety of techniques  is required.<STRONG> Intra- and extracellular
neurophysiological techniques </STRONG>are used including <STRONG>patch and
voltage clamp</STRONG>, combined with <STRONG>pharmacological</STRONG>
tools for analysis of ion channels, synaptic release mechanisms, single
neurones and systems of neurones, and morphological analysis on the light
and ultrastructural level. Extensive <STRONG>computer simulation</STRONG>
<STRONG>of single neurones and neuronal networks</STRONG> are developed in
collaboration with the <STRONG>laboratory of A. Lansner</STRONG> at the
computer science department at the Royal Institute of Technology.
<STRONG>Positron emission tomography (PET)</STRONG> and <STRONG>nuclear
magnetic resonance tomography (NMR)</STRONG> is also used, also in
collaboration with Southwestern University, Texas.  Tools for 3D
statistical analysis of data sets are developed in collaboration with the
Department of Mathematical Statistics of the Royal Institute of Technology
(Holst, Raab). Advanced mathematical image analysis is developed by the
group of Roland et al. and in collaboration with NADA at the Royal
Institute of Technology.  Longstanding collaboration with other research
groups extend our technical repertoire to
<STRONG>immunihistochemistry</STRONG> (H&ouml;kfelt), <STRONG>molecular
biology</STRONG> (Larhammar), <STRONG>ultrastructure</STRONG> (Cullheim). A
close <STRONG>interaction between basic and clinical research</STRONG> is
taking place. Two senior investigators (doc. Forssberg and prof.
Lagercrantz) hold clinical positions with the Pediatric department
(Karolinska Hospital) and some collaborative projects have a clear clinical
relevance (intensive care unit, Lindahl; pediatrics, Lagercrantz;
neurovirology, Kristensson; geriatrics, Winblad).<P>

<H4>International collaborations</H4>
Collaborations also occur with the departments of Anatomy and Brain
Research, Heinrich Heine University, D&uuml;sseldorf; the department of
Physiology, University of Tokyo, the department of Experimental Psychology,
University of Oxford; the department of Anatomy, University of Lausanne,
Division of Neuroscience, CNRS, Marseille (F. Clarac), Howard Hughes
Institute, USCD, San Diego (R. Tsien); MRC Unit of Neuroscience, University
of Montreal (S. Rossignol, R. Dubuc); Molecular Neurobiology, Rockefeller
University, New York (P. Greengard); University of Toronto (H. Atwood);
Molecular Neurobiology, Univ. Calif., Irvine (R. Miledi); Southwestern
Medical School, The University of Texas (L. Friberg).  <P>

<BR>
<H3>Funding</H3>
The research is funded by grants from the Medical (MFR) and Science (NFR)
Research Councils, the board of the research councils (FRN) and the board
of Technical Development (NUTEK), the Science program of the European
Commission, Human Frontier Program, Human Capital and Mobility, and other
foundations.<P>

<BR>
<H3>Department of Neuroscience</H3>
Since July 1 1993 the Neuroscience department of the Karolinska Institute
comprises of the researchers of the Nobel Institute (professor S. Grillner
and P. Roland) and it also contains professor K. Fuxe, T. H&ouml;kfelt and
L. Olson (previously department of Histology and Neurobiology), professor
L.-G. Elfvin and G. Grant (previously department of Anatomy) and  professor
K. Kristensson (previously section of neuropathology at Huddinge Hospital).
<P>

<BR>
<H3>Premises of the Department</H3>
The space allocated to the Nobel Institute for Neurophysiology is too
small, which prevents us from accepting new visiting scientists, graduate
students and associated neuroscience groups. The new Neuroscience
department is initially housed in three different locations (the previous
Anatomy, Neurophysiology and Berzelius laboratory buildings). It was
planned that Neurophysiology should move into new space in the Berzelius
laboratory before July 1993, but this did not occur. The new plans are now
detailed by architect M. Dunge, and it is planned to occur before July
1995. <P>

<BR>
<H3>Conferences, Seminars and Courses</H3>
The interdisciplinary <STRONG>"Neuroclub"</STRONG> is coordinated from the
department, which in addition organizes weekly lunch seminars.<P>
An integrated course in Neuroscience (10 weeks) is given annually for
undergraduates with a non-medical background (ie. physics, engineering,
biology, etc.). This course is required for students to be accepted into
the graduate student program in Neuroscience.<P>
A course (5p) for graduate students in Neuroscience and computer science
has been given in collaboration with A. Lansner, Computer Science
Department, Royal Institute of Technology.<P>

<BR>
<H2>II. Research Groups of S. Grillner, L. Brodin, T. Deliagina, A. El
Mantra, R. Hill, G. Orlovski, and P. Well&eacute;n, Including Visiting and
Doctoral Students</H2>
<HR><BR>
<STRONG>Grillner</STRONG> has been a member of the editorial boards of Acta
Physiol. Scand., Brain Research, Behavioural Brain Research, Behavioural
Brain Sciences, Current Neurobiology, European Journal of Neuroscience,
Network - Computational Neuroscience, Int. Journal of Neural Systems and
Neuron. He is a member of Academia Europeaea, Royal Swedish Academy of
Science, associate of the Neuroscience Institute (New York) and the board
for the European Neuroscience Program, Councils for the International Union
of Physiology, and International Brain Research Organisation. During 1994
he has been deputy chairman of the Nobel committee. He has lectured on
different occasions in Kyoto, San Diego, Nijmegen, Milan, Rennes, Boca
Raton.<P>
<STRONG>Wall&eacute;n</STRONG> has lectured in G&ouml;teborg, Doorwerth,
Holland.<P>
<STRONG>Orlovski</STRONG> has lectured in Marseille, Paris, San Diego,
Hawaii.<P>
<STRONG>Brodin</STRONG> has lectured in New York.<P>
<H3>Research Framework</H3>
The brain consists of interacting neural networks, which generate the
different aspects of our behavioural repertoire. To understand the brain,
these networks must be understood at at cellular level. In vertebrates this
has turned out to be an almost elusive problem due to the complex neural
organisation. An experimentally amenable in vitro preparation of a lower
vertebrate (lamprey) has therefore been developed. It has comparatively few
neurones and the synapses are accessible for analysis. These studies can be
divided into two parts, a <STRONG>cellular and molecular</STRONG>, and a
<STRONG>network part </STRONG>both of which are of fundamental importance.
The lamprey locomotor network is now better understood than that of any
other vertebrate. <P>

<BR>
<H3>A. Synaptic Transmission, Postsynaptic Receptors and Ion Channels</H3>

<H4>1. Analysis of presynaptic mechanisms (Brodin, Shupliakov, Pieribone) </H4>
In collaboration with P. Greengards laboratory presynaptic microinjection
experiments in the lamprey giant reticulo spinal synapse have been
performed, which have demonstrated the existence of biochemically and
functionally distinct pools of synaptic vesicles (submitted to Nature).
Injection of synapsin antibodies was found to cause a marked disruption of
the major portion of synaptic vesicle clusters, while only a small pool of
vesicles remained tethered to the active zones. Immunogold labelling showed
that the distribution of synapsin correlated with the distribution of
vesicles that were disrupted after antibody injections. Paired recording
experiments between injected axons and target cells showed that the
synaptic response during low-frequency stimulation was unaltered, while
during high-frequency stimulation a marked depression of the release
occurred. Thus, a large synapsin-dependent pool of vesicles is required
during sustained release, while a small synapsin-independent pool is
sufficient to support release at low frequency.<P>
Injection of synaptotagmin antibodies had a distinctly different effect
than that of synapsin antibodies. In this case the synapses showed
ultrastructural changes indicating a strong increase of the spontaneous
release. These included an increased number of fusing vesicles ("omega
profiles"), an expansion of plasma membrane and an increased number of
coated (endocytic) structures. A clustered "reserve pool" was still
present. Structural changes similar to these occur in normal axons
subjected to intense action potential stimulation. These data strongly
support the hypothesis that synaptotagmin has an inhibitory regulatory role
in the synapse.<P>
In a collaborative study with J. Storm-Mathisen and O.P. Ottersen,
D-aspartate, which is taken up by plasma membrane transporters but not
vesicular transporters, was used as a marker at the ultrastructural level
to localize and quantifythe excitatory amino acid uptake into different
synaptic compartments. After incubation in D-aspartate-containing solution
glutamatergic axons were found to show only a limited uptake, while a
prominent uptake occurred in adjacent glial processes. Three-dimensional
reconstruction showed that these glial processes formed a "collar" around
the individual synapses. Taken together with our previous data, these data
show that the synaptic cleft in glutamatergic synapses is isolated from the
surrounding extracellular space by a glial "collar" with a high uptake
activity. This appears to be of critical importance for the integrity of
the synaptic transmission, as it prevents synaptically released glutamate
to diffuse out from the cleft to activate receptors in adjacent synapses,
and it also protects the postsynaptic receptors from being activated during
general elevations of the extracellular excitatory amino acid levels (e.g.
during pathological conditions).<P>

<H4>2. Complementary action of DA-5-HT on synaptic transmission in the
spinal cord (Brodin, El Manira, Grillner, Schotland, Shupliakov,
Wikstr&ouml;m, Zhang)</H4>
5-HT cells located in the spinal cord have been found to co-store dopamine
(DA). The different 5-HT systems in the brainstem-spinal cord release 5-HT
in a paracrine fashion without forming point-to-point synapses. 5-HT acts
in a nonconventional way by modifying the frequency regulation of the
target neurones (spinal and reticulospinal neurones) by influencing the
afterhyperpolarization (AHP) mediated by Ca dependent K+ channels. The
5-<BR>
HT system modulates the segmental and intersegmental locomotor circuitry
through these effects on the AHP. DA acts on Ca2+ channels reducing the
Ca2+ entry during the action potential. This effect complements that of
5-HT on Ca2+ dependent K+ channels. 5-HT and DA are co-released and their
action is complementary and additive (Nature in press). The distribution of
the 5-HT-DA system in a rostrocaudal fashion in brainstem-spinal cord has
been analysed and the effects of 5-HT-DA on different parts of the spinal
cord network for locomotion. 5-HT exerts its action on  5-HT1A like
receptors, while DA acts preferentially on D2 receptors. Both 5-HT and DA
also cause a depression of glutamatergic synaptic transmission from certain
types of neurones. <P>

<H4>3. Real-time measurements of calcium influx in lamprey spinal cord
neurones. (Wall&eacute;n, Grillner, in collaboration with R.Y. Tsien, B.J.
Bacskai, Howard Hughes Medical Institute, UCSD, La Jolla)</H4>
The analysis of the calcium dynamics in different types of neurons in the
lamprey CNS, a collaborative project with prof. Roger Y. Tsien"'"s
laboratory in La Jolla, has continued with regard to spinal motoneurons,
and the results have been compiled into a report which has now been
published (Bacskai et al., Neuron, 14:19-28, 1995). In these studies we
have utilized a video-rate laser scanning confocal microscope system,
developed by prof. Tsien, in combination with Ca2+-sensitive fluorescent
probes which can be intracellularly injected into the recorded cell from
the microelectrode. This allows measurement of Ca2+ fluctuations at
adequately high temporal (30 images/s) and spatial resolution, in
conjunction with simultaneous electrophysiological recordings from the same
neuron.<P>

<H4>4. Sensory touch and pressure cells and afferents, and modulation of
their sensory transmission to different types of neurones (El Manira,
Tegn&eacute;r,)</H4>
Sensory dorsal cells are modulated to a varying degree during fictive
locomotion, providing a phasic gating of the sensory input. This
presynaptic inhibition acts by modulating the excitatory synaptic
transmission in phase with the locomotor activity. The amplitude after
monosynaptic EPSPs  is gated phasically. Both activation of GABAB receptors
and 5-HT causes a depression of the synaptic transmission, it appears
however that the locomotor related modulator of sensory afferents is not
through GABA receptors.<P>

<H4>5. Monosynaptic input from skin afferents to fin motoneurones (El Manira, Shupliakov)</H4>
Touch and pressure dorsal cells do not have monosynaptic input to somatic
motoneurones, but to fin motoneurones. Dorsal cells provide monosynaptic
feedback to fin motoneurones, whereas the corresponding feedback system to
somatic motoneurones is provided by intraspinal stretch receptor neurones
sensing the laterally directed locomotor movements. <P>

<H4>6. Dorsal cells and post tetanic hyperpolarisation (Parker)</H4>
After a higher frequency burst, sensory dorsal cells exhibit a long lasting
hyperpolarisation. This hyperpolarisation blocks the transmission of
impulses from the afferent axon to the central terminals, and acts
therefore as a gating mechanism. This hyperpolarisation is due to a
combined action of a novel type (in lamprey) of calcium dependent K+
channel (not apamin sensitive), and an activation of Na-K+ pump. This is a
new control mechanism. The action of 5-HT and peptides (substance P) is
analysed.<P>

<H4>7. The action of somatostatin and neurotensin on neurones and the
locomotor network (Barthe) </H4>
GABA and somatostatin-ir and GABA and neurotensin-ir containing cells
located at the central canal form a dense plexus around the lateral
dendritic ramifications of edge cells. GABA and somatostatin both have
inhibitory effects, the former via Cl-channels activated by GABAA receptors
and the latter via a so far unidentified K+ channels mechanism. GABAB
receptors also exert effects on edge cells including gating of Ca2+
channels. Neurotensin, on the other hand, depolarizes target cells, an
effect not mediated by a conductance increase and not being dependent on
voltage dependent Na+ or Ca2+ channels.  Somatostatin and neurotensin both
act in the locomotor network.<P>

<H4>8.Peptide neurons - analysis by immunohistochemistry, molecular cloning
and in situ hybridization (Brodin, S&ouml;derberg, Dahlstrand, Pieribone,
Rawitch and Larhammar) </H4>
The amino acid sequences of two NPY-related peptides in lamprey have been
determined from cDNA clones. Sequence comparisons have shown that they
correspond to NPY and PYY, respectively. The two types of mRNA have been
localized in distinct neuron systems including a reticulospinal system
(PYY) and dorsal horn interneurons (NPY), using in situ hybridization. The
peptides deduced from the cDNA sequences have been synthesized and will be
used for electrophysiological analysis.<P>

<H4>9. Dissociation of identifiable spinal cord neurones - cell culture -
Ca2+ channels (El Manira, Bussi&egrave;res)</H4>
To be able to study the properties of identified cell types with regard to
single types of ion channels, particularly different types of Ca2+ channels
(single channel, whole cell) techniques for reliable dissociation of
identified cells have been developed. Cultures of transmitter identified
cells (glutamate, glycine, Ach) are being developed - and their formation
of synapses.<P>

<BR>
<H3>B. Network Analyses - Cellular Bases of Locomotion</H3>
One overall goal of the study of the lamprey CNS-model is to elucidate how
individual brainstem and spinal cord interneurones interact in the neural
networks that generate the basic locomotor synergy. The basic principles of
operation have been analyzed by a variety of techniques including
intracellular paired recordings and computer simulation in collaboration
with Anders Lansner's research group at the Royal College of Technology.
Intersegmental and segmental neuronal mechanisms in the locomotor network
have been described to the extent that many basic mechanisms can now be
said to be understood. The neuronal systems underlying the control of body
equilibrium during movements and for steering are now becoming in focus.<P>

<H4>1. The neural mechanisms of intersegmental coordination (Hellgren,
Wadden, Tegn&eacute;r, El Manira, Grillner)</H4>
The work to establish the mechanisms underlying the constant phase lag
between consecutive segments were continued. Very extensive simulations
have shown that the known segmental and intersegmental connectivity can
produce a phase lag. The new model is continuous, without discrete
segmental oscillators, ie. in a strict sense not a coupled oscillator
model. The model in its largest form has 2000 realistic neurones, and
700,000 synapses. <P>

<H4>2. Efference copy information from spinal networks to brainstem
reticulospinal neurones and back - significance (Vinay)</H4>
The spinal locomotor network signals back to the brainstem information
about its activity. Extensive physiological and anatomical studies of the
spinoreticular axonal pathway have been performed. The system projects in
the lateral part of the spinal cord and continues into the medial
lemniscus. The different neurones inform about ongoing motor activity on
both sides as well as about the transition between the different phases of
the motor program. The effect of braking this loop on the brainstem level
has been investigated under conditions when the spinal CPG is active. The
significance of this circuit is being analysed by simulation. <P>

<H4>3. Local spinal interneurone with crossed axons (Fagerstedt,
Wall&eacute;n) </H4>
A new class of interneurones have been identified, which is currently under
investigation with paired intracellular recordings. They are small and have
crossed axons that extend over a limited number of segments. Some of these
neurones are inhibitory and probably glycinergic. During the experiment the
neurones can be identified by previous staining with retrograde tracers.<P>

<H4>4. Mathematical modelling of the lamprey locomotor system (Grillner,
Lansner, Wall&eacute;n, Ekeberg, Wadden, Hellgren, Tegn&eacute;r,
Wikstr&ouml;m)</H4>
The detailed synaptic interaction between the different types of neurones
has been established as well as the properties of the individual neurones
with their blend of different types of ion-<BR>
channels. With this knowledge, often biological, at hand we have continued
to simulate the neurones in the network in a biologically realistic way in
the form of coupled differential equations. New software has been developed
for a work station or a parallell super computer (CH), which allows
simulation of a number of neurones, each of which with its specific
properties. The analyses of populations of neurones have been very
illuminating, combined with different cellular properties of the spinal
cord and brainstem neurones. Ekeberg has developed a new neuromechanical
lamprey model, which actually swims through "simulated" walls. A new
network configuration has been introduced which allows steering control in
3D. This model is based on the resent neuronal network. <P>

<H4>5. Selection of behaviour - basal ganglia (Pombal, El Manira)</H4>
The basal ganglia are fairly large structures in the lamprey CNS and can be
assumed to take part in the overall regulation and selection of behaviour.
We have started by describing the basic circuitry. Striatum in lamprey has
a similar innervation to that of mammals (DA, 5-HT, histamin, NT) and the
DA projections from the brainstem to striatum have been detailed. Moreover
a pathway with monosynaptic connections from "ventral thalamus" to
reticulospinal cells has been identified, which can initiate locomotor
activity, and displays synaptic potentiation. <P>

<BR>
<H3>C. Nervous Mechanisms for Spatial Orientation and Postural Control
(Orlovsky, Deliagina, Ull&eacute;n, Gonzalez, Grillner)</H3>
A comparative study of the systems responsible for spatial orientation and
postural control was carried out on a few, remotely related species of
animals - the lamprey, the rat and a mollusc (<CITE>Clione lomacina</CITE>)
- to reveal common basic principles in the organization and operation of
these systems.<P>

<H4>1. Postural and steering control systems in the lamprey.</H4>
In behavioral experiments, the motor patterns used by an animal for
changing and correcting its body orientation in space, and for selecting
and maintaining a certain swimming direction were studied. Vestibular
sensory input was found to play a crucial role for the control of body
orientation in the vertical plane, while visual input could strongly affect
the direction of swimming. In addition, dermal photoreceptors were shown to
be responsible for activation of the locomotor system during the
light-avoidance reaction.<P>
On the bases of these behavioral studies, as well as of earlier
electrophysiological studies on the isolated brainstem preparation, a
conceptual model of the roll control system, which is responsible for
stabilization of the dorsal side-up orientation, has been formulated. The
model can explain a number of phenomena related to postural control, such
as the dorsal light response and the continuous rolling seen after a lesion
to the vestibular organ. The model also allowed certain predictions that
later could be confirmed experimentally. In particular, lesion experiments,
where the vestibular and visual sensory organs were removed in different
combinations, showed that the lacking vestibular input could be substituted
by contralateral visual input. This finding is a basis for further studies
of plastic changes after lesions in the CNS. 	<BR>
The analysis of the neuronal networks responsible for the light-avoidance
reaction which represents a very simple form of steering control, was
carried out in electrophysiological experiments, with the main attention
given to the analysis of the transformation of an asymmetrical (unilateral)
sensory input into symmetrical (bilateral) one in the motor centres
responsible for rectilinear swimming.<P>

<H4>2. Postural control in the rat.</H4>
This study was carried out in collaboration with G. Grant, L. Popova and B.
Ragnarsson. Removal of the vestibular sensory organ on one side in the rat
results in numerous motor disorders which severely disturb the postural
control. It was found that all these disorders could be considerably
reduced and even completely abolished by electrical stimulation of the
vestibular nerve on the lesioned side. This finding clearly demonstrated
that tonic input from the labyrinth plays a crucial role for the normal
function of the postural control mechanisms. In addition to the immediate
restoration of the postural control, stimulation of the vestibular nerve
also had long-lasting effects, and promoted the compensation of the
vestibular deficit.<P>
Integration of sensory inputs of different modalities is an essential
feature of the postural control system. One site for the integration is the
central cervical nucleus. In electrophysiological experiments it was shown
that neurons of this nucleus respond both to natural vestibular stimuli
(tilting the animal) and to natural proprioceptive stimuli (stretching the
neck muscles). The output of these neurons thus signals about the head
orientation both in space and in relation to the trunk.<P>

<H4>3. Postural control in molluscs.</H4>
The mollusc <CITE>Clione limacina </CITE>has been used as a simple model
system for studying postural control mechanisms at the network and cellular
levels. In collaboration with the Moscow group headed by Y. Arshavsky, the
gravistatic response has been characterized in different identified
neurons, which constitute the system responsible for the maintenance of the
vertical body orientation. These include: (i) sensory cells of the gravity
sensory organ (statocyst), (ii) different type of interneurons in the
cerebro-pedal command system, and (iii) motoneurons controlling a postural
effector organ, the tail. These experimental results allowed the
formulation of a conceptual model of the postural control system, as well
as a characterization of the corresponding neuronal networks. <P>
Vestibular input affects not only the postural control mechanisms. In the
rat, the lamprey and <CITE>Clione</CITE>, it also affects the locomotor
system and some other systems. In another mollusc, <CITE>Planorbis
corneus</CITE>, input from the statocysts is responsible not only for
postural control, but it can also evoke a defensive behavior. This
phenomenon was analyzed at the network level.<P>

<BR>
<H2>III. Research Group of P. &Aring;rhem</H2>
<HR><BR>
&Aring;rhem has lectured at an international workshop on information
science in Madrid (June). He has coedited a workshop volume on the
cognitive activity of mind and a thematic issue of Journal of Theoretical
Biology on the mind-matter problem. <P>
A graduate course (3p) in theoretical  biology and philosophy of science
has been given in  collaboration with H. Liljenstr&ouml;m, Royal Institute
of Technology. <P>
Fredrik Elinder has defended his thesis "Surface charges of voltage-gated
ion channels".<P>

<BR>
<H3>Research Framework</H3>
To understand the brain it is necessary, as pointed out at other places in
this report, to study nerve activity at all levels. The basis for the
electrical activity of the brain is the activity of ion channels in the
nerve membrane.  It is necessary to complement the increased amount of
structural data on ion channels at a molecular level with functional,
biophysical and pharmacological data at a corresponding level. Important
problems to solve, are for instance the role of charges and the kinetics of
the channels. Such problems are studied experimentally with voltage and
patch clamp techniques on different preparations, and theoretically with
channel model computations. <P>
During the year the group has started voltage clamp studies on cloned
channels expressed in oocytes of <CITE>Xenopus laevis</CITE>. This powerful
technique makes it possible to analyze the channel kinetics in molecular
detail.  The experiments were made in collaboration with Dr Madeja at
University of M&uuml;nster. Several types of mammalian K channels were used
to test a hypothesis developed from voltage clamp studies on the effect of
metal ions. The patch clamp studies of hippocampal slices under visual
control with the technique developed by the Sakmann group in Heidelberg and
recently introduced at the laboratory have continued. This technique is
essential for analyzing neurons in relative intact tissue, and have been
used to test hypotheses based on studies of primary cultures of hippocampal
neurons. Further, the patch clamp technique has also been used extensively
to analyze cell lines (rhabdomyoma cells) and primary cultures of
hippocampal neurons in collaboration with other groups at and outside the
Department. The voltage clamp method developed for myelinated nerve fibres
has been used for studies of statistical and pharmacological properties of
voltage gated Na and K channels. It is, as pointed out in earlier reports,
well suited for high-resolution measurements of these channels. The reason
is that the preparation is well characterized, probably quantitively better
than any other membrane preparation, and that the membrane sites of action
are easily accessible for many blocking and gating modifying substances.
During the year it has mainly been used to study current fluctuations in
order to develop a kinetic model of the Na channel, and the metal binding
to Na and K channels in order to understand the functional role of the
charge profile of the channel molecule. It has also been used in
preliminary experiments with certain local anaesthetics, suggested to
selectively block channels responsible for the resting potential. The
origin of the resting potential is still unsatisfactorily known.  <P>

<H4>1. Metal ion binding to Na and K channels and the role of surface
charges (Elinder, &Aring;rhem)</H4>
In previous studies on the trivalent gadolinium ion it was shown that the
effect on the Na and K channels in the nodal membrane could be described by
three separate mechanisms, mediated by separate sites of action. Further,
quantitative models for the gadolinium ion binding, based on the assumed
molecular structure of the channels, were developed. The models include
metal ion binding to a modulatory site and the modification of a surface
potential due to neutralization of fixed surface charges according to the
Gouy-Chapman theory. The models made it possible to estimate the charge
density of the nodal Na and K channels more exactly than previously. The
models also suggest the location of the modulatory sites as well as the
location of charges on the channels. This makes it possible to predict the
effect of other metal ions on other channel types from data on the primary
structure of the channel.<P>
In order to test these predictions it is necessary to use channels whose
molecular identity is known in detail. Unfortunately this is not the case
for the channels in the nodal membrane of <CITE>Xenopus laevis</CITE>.
Furthermore, the populations are not homogenous. To circumvent these
problems the technique to express identified cloned channels in
<CITE>Xenopus</CITE> oocytes was used. In collaboration with Dr Madeja at
the University of M&uuml;nster experiments on the effect of the divalent
strontium ion on five types of mammalian K channels were performed. The
cRNA used for the expression was obtained from Prof. Pongs at Hamburg
University. The choice of strontium for the analysis was based on the fact
that strontium seems to bind less to the channels than other available
metal ions (with the exception of magnesium that was excluded of other
reasons), and thus is assumed to mainly neutralize the charges by
screening. The results showed that the previously presented hypothesis that
certain functional properties of the channel can be predicted from the
primary structure was valid. The effective charge density of the studied K
channels seems to be mainly determined by a segment close to the
poreforming segment. <P>

<H4>2. The kinetics of the Na channel: Fluctuation analysis (Elinder,
Frankenhaeuser, &Aring;rhem)</H4>
The analysis of Na channel kinetics by fluctuation analysis of
non-stationary Na-currents in the myelinated axon under voltage clamp
conditions has led to the development of a detailed kinetic model. A large
number of models suggested in the literature could be excluded. The most
unexpected feature of the developed model is that it includes two open
states, suggesting channel properties that are experimentally testable. In
collaboration with Prof. Richard Keynes at Cambridge University, Elinder
has analyzed other aspects of Na channel models, based on the studies by
Keynes on the Na channel gating current. These aspects will be included in
the presented model. <BR>

<H4>3. Electrophysiology of hippocampal neurons: Graded impulses and
spontaneous activity (&Aring;rhem,  Englund, Nerg&aring;rdh)</H4>
Earlier patch clamp studies of cultured hippocampal neurons have
unexpectedly shown that certain small-sized neurons generate impulses that
vary in amplitude with stimulus strength. This behaviour deviates from the
generally accepted all-or-nothing law. Further, these small-<BR>
sized neurons show spontaneous activity, that can be shown to be triggered
by single channel events. Both these findings may have consequences for the
information processing of the brain. The latter finding suggests that
random gating of ion channel molecules may be used as a mechanism for
stochastic triggering of spontaneous impulses in mammalian central neurons.
<P>
In order to study these phenomena under more "intact" conditions the
recently introduced hippocampal slice preparation was used. Mainly
spontaneously active neurons of a type corresponding to those earlier
investigated, i.e. small round neurons, were analyzed. The results suggest
that the earlier observations also are valid for neurons in hippocampal
tissue.<P>

<H4>4. Theoretical studies (&Aring;rhem, Lindahl)</H4>
&Aring;rhem has with B.I.B. Lindahl at Stockholm University and in
collaboration with Karl Popper continued the analysis of the proposal by
Popper that certain mental states can be described in terms of force fields
of classical physics. Attempts have been made to understand the role of
spontaneous activity in this context.

<BR>
<H2>IV. Research Group of H.Lagercrantz,Y.Yamamoto, and M.Runold</H2>
<HR><BR>
H.Lagercrantz, professor in neonatology at the Karolinska Hospital together
with drs Y.Yamamoto and M.Runold has studied further functional role of
various neuroactive substances during development.<P>
<STRONG>Michael Runold and Shi-zend Yuan</STRONG> have continued the study
of the mechanisms of the autoresuscitation. They have found that bilateral
adrenalectomy reduced the ability to tolerate anoxia in the newborn rats as
indicated by the significantly shorted gasping duration. The
autoresuscitation mechanism was impaired after adrenalectomy, especially in
the 8-day old rat group. The ability of autoresuscitation was abolished
following phentolamine administration. Propranol did not affect the ability
to autoresuscitate after asphyxia. Glucose supplementation was found to
prolong the duration of hypoxic gasping in 8-day old rats, while the
survival after glucose was reduced in both 1-day and 8 day old rats,
particulary in 8-day old rats. The results indicate that hyperglycemia
might jeopardize the autoresuscitation mechanism in newborn rats during
anoxia. Recovery from apnea was reduced when oxygen was given after the
last gasp. However, a conciderable number of rats survived spontaneously.
This suggests that autoresuscitation is still active even after gasping
period.<P>
<STRONG>Yuji Yamamoto and Hiroshi Otsuka</STRONG> have studied further the
central mechanisms for the integration and the modulation of the
ventilatory "drive"-factors and the respiratory rhythmgeneration in in
vitro preparation from newborn rats. We examined the effects of <BR>
NMDA antagonists, APV and non-NMDA antagonists, CNQX on inspiratory neurons
in the medulla oblongata and C4 and C5 ventral root activity in the
<CITE>in vitro</CITE> brainstem-spinal cord preparation of newborn rats.
Application of APV induced increased rate of inspiratory neuron bursts, and
decreased burst duration. The C4 burst activity was almost abolished by
application of CNQX, whereas inspiratory neurons continued to discharge
rhythmically. The results suggest that non-NMDA receptors are not crucially
involved in the medullary respiratory rhythmogenesis. We have also examined
the effects of halothane on the central respiratory activity. Halothane
decreased respiratory burst frequency, inspiratory duration, ventral C4
activity and respiratory minute activity in a concentration-dependent
fashion. Bicuculline counteracted the depressive effect of halothane on
respiratory burst frequency, C4 activity, and respiratory minute activity.
Inspiratory neuronal activity corresponded to these changes. Activities of
Pre-Inspiratory (Pre-I) neurons and expiratory neurons in the RVL were also
inhibited by halothane. The C4 activity failed to correspond to the
discharge of Pre-I neurons. <P>
These results suggest that modification of GABAA receptor-mediated
neurotransmission is in part responsible for respiratory depression by
halothane, especially the effect on respiratory frequency, peak C4
activity, and minute activity. There seems to be a desynchronization
between Pre-I neurons and C4 discharge during halothane anaesthesia. <P>
<STRONG>Yuji Yamamoto and Eric Herlenius</STRONG> have studied the central
adenosine effects on respiratory activity during postnatal period by using
the isolated rat brainstem-spinal cord preparation. <P>
Endogeneneous adenosine caused a depressing effect on respiratory activity
by a direct action on medullary respiration-related neurons. Adenosine
antagonist theophylline abolished this effect, by blocking central
adenosine receptors. Furthermore, the effect of adenosine was age
dependent, younger animals hade more pronounced effect compaired to more
than 2 day-old rats. In neonatal rats (less than 48h) adenosine play a role
in the irregular type of breathing. <P>

<BR>
<H2>V. Research Group of Curt von Euler</H2>
<HR><BR>

Curt von Euler has written a chapter on Neural Organization and Rhythm
Generation Rhythm in Respiration for a two-volume book entitled "The Lung:
Scientific Foundations" to be published by Raven Press, New York.<P>
Curt von Euler is president of the international dyslexia research
organization "Academia Rodinensis Pro Remediatione". In this capacity he
has taken part in the program committee and gave the opening speech for the
international symposia on "Eye Movements and Reading with Special Reference
to Dyslexia". This symposium, which was a Wenner-Gren Center Symposium held
in January 1994, was organized by professor Gunnar Lennerstrand and docent
Jan Ygge.<P>
Euler has taken part in the planning and led the 23rd international
symposium of the Rodin Renediation Academy. This symposium was held on
Malta, September 20-24. The theme was "Diagnostic Methods, Crusial Markers
and Genetics for Dyslexia". The main part of the scientific program
consisted of 16 plenary lectures given by leading scientists in the fields
of psychology, neuropsychology, cognitive science, linguistics, neurology
and genetics. In addition, there was a rich menu of poster
presentations.<P>
Euler is also chairman of the Sweidsh Dyslexia Foundation and the Swedish
Dyslexia Association, which <CITE>inter alia</CITE> has been in charge of
two different research projects. One of these is aimed at determining the
occurrance of developmental dyslexia among young (18-25 yr. old) unemployed
people. The other project was a study of developmental dyslexia among
criminals in a Swedish prison. These studies are in progress. Preliminary
results have shown a large over-representaion of dyslexia in both of these
populations.<P>
The longitudinal multicenter research project on developmental dyslexia
described in last years"'"s annual report has proceeded as planned. The
results of this project, which now is in its sixth year, are now on the way
to be published in a series of papers as well as in the form of a book.<P>
In an extension of this project Euler together with prof. Lennerstrand of
the Ophtalmology at the Karolinska Institute and Huddinge Hospital, prof.
Ingvar Lundberg, Dept. of Psychology, University of Ume&aring;, and a group
of reserach workers at the Dept. of Practical Pedagogics at the University
of V&auml;xj&ouml;, have undertaken to investigate the genetics of
developmental dyslexia. The object is to find some 100 families in which
dyslexia can be well documented in two or more generations, and to describe
the pedigress of these family members. Blood samples of the family members
are collected and sent to our collaborators at the laboratory of molecular
biology at the Institute of Deafness and other Communication Disorders,
NIH, Bethesda, USA. So far about 40 families have been well documented in
this way and blood samples from them have been received by the laboratory
at NIH.<P>
The study on adult dyslexic individuals with MRI and PET techniques during
different linguistic tasks, mentioned in last year"'"s report, is no being
prepared for publication. The project is running at the department of
Neuroradiology and clinical neurophysiology at the Karolinska Hospital
jointly by prof. T. Greitz, prof. L. Eriksson and assoc. prof. Martin
Ingvar, and assoc. prof. P. af Trampe, Dept of Linguistics, Stockholm
University. The results, which have been presented at several meetings and
conferences are of great interest, especially with rrespect to the
unexpected differences in activation of Broca"'"s area between dyslexics
and non-dyslexics.<P>

<BR>
<H2>VI. Research Group of Per Roland, Balazs Gulyas, Ivanka Savic. Visiting
Scientists and Doctoral Students</H2>
<HR><BR>
Roland has served on the editorial boards of Cerebral Cortex, Cognitive
Brain Research, Human Brain Mapping and Neuroimage. Roland has lectured at
the University of Lausanne and has been a co-organiser of the following two
international symposia "Neuromechanism of learning and memory" and a
"Wennergren Conference on the Somethesis and the Neurobiology of
Somatosensory Cortex". Guly&aacute;s has lectured at the Hungarian
Neuroscience Meeting. Roland and Guly&aacute;s are the members of the
advisory board of the Human Brain Map Project.<P>

<BR>
<H3>Research Framework</H3>
To understand the functioning of the brain, one must understand how the
brain works at all levels: Membrane level, cellular level, small neuronal
network level as well as the macro-<BR>
network level. One of the more recent level-bridging techniques is positron
emission tomography by which one can study membrane and receptor events as
well as the behaviour of macro-networks. Most often, as in our laboratory,
the regional cerebral blood flow is used as aparameter of regional
synaptic metabolism.<P>
Based on the relationship between changes in synaptic metabolism and
changes in synaptic activity and the relationship between synaptic
metabolism and regional cerebral blood flow, this technique is used
together with magnetic resonance tomographic techniques and neuroanatomical
techniques to understand the principles for brain work in terms of
macro-<BR>
network organisation. The results of such investigations are 3D pictures of
the brain, often representing more than a million measurement points each.
The manipulation and statistical analysis of such data require advanced
software, development of algorithms and statistical procedures, which are
therefore also substantial part of the activities. Specific programs
include:<P>

<H4>1. The functional organization of the motor cortices in man (Kinomura,
Roland and Ledberg)</H4>
Within the three major motor cortical zones: the premotor zone, the
supplementary motor zone and the primary motor zone, we have now found
several independent areas functionally and anatomically in man. These are
the rostral and caudal cingulate motor areas, the area 4a, the area 4p
(formally the primary motor area) the supplementary motor area and the
pre-SMA. The pre-motor areas seem difficult to parcel at the present.
Several representations of the hand and arm exist here.<P>

<H4>2. The somatosensory cortices in man (Ledberg, O'Sullivan and Roland)</H4>
The recent research has concentrated upon finding several somatosensory
areas in the parietal operculum of man. Here at least three independent
areas of which one might be the so-called secondary somatosensory area have
been discovered.<P>

<H4>3. Functional parcellation of the visual cortices in man
(Guly&aacute;s, Larsson, Roland in collaboration with Cowey and Heywood,
University of Oxford)</H4>
In humans, V1 and V4 (MT) are relatively well characterised
cytoarchitectonically and myeloarchitectonically as well as functionally.
From studies by our own group and others, we now know that the visual
cortical areas extent into the parietal lobe rather far rostrally and into
the inferior temporal gyrus. Traditionally, one has the view that the
visual perception follows a dorsal or parietal route for spatial
information and the information about movement in the field of view, and a
temporal route for analysis of objects and the details (Ungerleider and
Mishikin 1982). We have shown that stereoscopical vision activates
occipital and parietal cortical fields (Guly&aacute;s and Roland 1994a):
However, form perception activates both parietal and temporal lobe areas.
Similarly, colour perception also activates parietal and temporal lobe
areas (Guly&aacute;s and Roland 1994b). Furthermore, a single visual
submodality is always activated by multiple cortical fields and not as
proposed by Zeki by only one cortical field. Finally, in the discrimination
of form attributes a parallel  organisation is apparent (Guly&aacute;s et
al. 1994), Thus form provided by colour cues and form provided by disparity
cues activate non-overlapping visual cortical fields. More rostral parts of
the visual association areas, that is posterior part of the inferior
temporal gyrus and the fusiform gyri, the angular gyrus and the superior
parietal lobule as well as precuneus are potential storage sites for
complex visual information (Roland and Guly&aacute;s 1994; Roland and
Guly&aacute;s 1995).<P>

<H4>4. Visual memories (Klingberg, Kinomura, Roland)</H4>
The entorrhinal cortex in man seems to have a special role for establishing
and maintaining intramodal associations. Working memory representations as
well as long-term memory representations of visual patterns which are
stationary are located both in the temporal cortex (fusiform gyrus) and
posterior inferior temporal cortex as well as in the parietal cortex.<P>

<H4>5. Development of advanced tools for analysis of 3D pictures of the
brain (Graufelds, &Aring;kerman, Lindeberg and Roland)</H4>
The new computerized atlas, at present the most accurate in re-formatting
3D images of the brain into a standard format has been further developed.
Tools for unfolding the cerebral cortex of man have been implemented which
permits a preliminary multiple area unfolded map with moderate area
distortion. Finally a new statistical model for the estimate of overlapping
functional field has been developed in collaboration with Mikael Raab and
Lars Holst at the KTH.<P>

<BR>
<H2>VII. Research group of H. Forssberg</H2>
<HR>
<BR>
<H4>Development of human control.</H4>
During the spring Forssberg was a Fulbright Scholar at the Department of
Neurology, Childrens Hospital and Harvard Medical School, Boston,
Massachusetts. Forssberg organized, in collaboration with Francois Clarac,
a Jaques Monod Conference on "Locomotion - from neural networks to
cognition" in Aussois, France. He has on invitation lectured in Boston,
Cambridge, Missuola, Philadelphia, New York, Portland, Quebec, Ohlstadt and
Groningen.<P>
The development of postural control and fine motor skill is studied
experimentally in healthy children with perinatal brain injuries. The
postural control is studied together with Hirschfeld, Eriksson and Brogren
by means of a movable platform perturbing a sitting or standing child while
EMG is recorded by surface electrodes and kinematics by an automatized
movement analyzing system (ELIT). A backward perturbation of a sitting
subject elicits an instant backward rotation of the pelvis, which triggers
central pattern generators for postural adjustments. However, before the
muscles are activated, the pattern is modified by a multi-<BR>
sensorial input including information from the vestibular system. The basic
pattern, triggered by the pelvic rotation, seems to mature before a child
is able to sit up without support. The capability to modify the disorder,
spastic diplegia, only activate the basic pattern seen in young children.
The pattern is stereotyped with only minor modifications. The neural
control of the precision grip is studied together with Eliasson, Iwasaki
and Ingvarsson by a special instrument, which monitor the isometric forces
applied to the grip surfaces. During this year the tactile regulation of
the grip force depending on the friction of the grip surface has been
studied in healthy children and in children with cerebral palsy. The
capability to adapt during an ongoing lift develops normally during the
second year but it is not until the third year children can store the
tactile information into an internal representation of the object and scale
the isometric force pulse during the succeeding lift. Small children need
several lifts to form the representation and only exhibit minor influence
on the force development. The anticipatory capacity is improved with
increasing age and is getting adult like at about 6 years. Children with
cerebral palsy have an impaired feed back regulation as well as weak
anticipation.<P>
Clinical follow up studies are performed on preterm infants, infants with
plexus brachialis paresis, and children with spastic diplegia. Preterm
infants and infants subjected to perinatal asphyxia are followed during the
neonatal period and during subsequent motor and cognitive development
(together with Lagercrantz, Katz-Salamon, Gerner). Special efforts are made
to describe the pathogenesis and the location of brain lesions. Children
with defined perinatal brain lesion are later studied regarding their
postural control and fine manipulative skill. Since several years the
recovery of arm function and manipulation are followed in children with
plexus brachialis palsy, operated on with a nerve graft at the damage
location of the plexus, providing possibility for neurones to regenerate to
the nerves of the arm. Finally, a clinical investigation comparing three
different methods to treat children with spastic diplegia has started, i.e.
selective dorsal rhizotomy, orthopedic surgery and intensified physical
therapy.<P>
<BR><BR>
Stockholm, March 1, 1995<P>
<STRONG>The Nobel Institute for Neurophysiology</STRONG><P>
Sten Grillner<BR>
professor, director<P>
