<HEAD>

<TITLE>1997 Mining Engineering Editorial Calendar</TITLE>

<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><A HREF="index.html">
<IMG SRC="art/smelogo.GIF" ALIGN=left height=65 width=68 HSPACE=12 BORDER=0></A>

<IMG SRC="art/melogo.GIF" ALIGN=right HSPACE=12></H1><BR CLEAR=all>

<P><CITE><FONT SIZE=5>1997 Mining Engineering Editorial Calendar</FONT><HR>

</CITE></P>


<BR CLEAR=all>

<!-- Document Body Text -->

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><H3>January</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>ShowGuide Issue.</B></FONT><BR>
The January issue of <CITE>MINING ENGINEERING</CITE> highlights products and services to be found at the 1997 SME Annual Meeting and Exhibit, February 24-27, in Denver, Colorado.  Exhibitors' advertisements in the January issue will be discounted 20% from established rates.

<DT><H3>February</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Recent Developments in Industrial Minerals.</B></FONT><BR>
The world outlook for industrial minerals will be examined in this issue, as well as new processing technologies. Coverage includes processing innovations.

<DT><H3>March</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Exploration Geology in Southeast Asia.</B></FONT><BR>
Exploration for potential mining sites throughout the world finds no exception in Southeast Asia. The March issue reports on exploration activity in the region.
 
<DT><H3>April</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Plant Design and Practice-Comminution Techniques.</B></FONT><BR>
Advances in mill design, process control and instrumentation, and crushing and grinding are featured in this issue.

<DT><H3>May</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Annual Review of Mining in the US.</B></FONT><BR>
Investigates recent mining and exploration activities throughout much of the United States. Includes reports of the domestic hard-rock and coal-mining industries.

<DT><H3>June</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Industrial Minerals.</B></FONT><BR>
Domestic and world industrial minerals activities and recent developments are examined in this issue.

<DT><H3>July</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Coal Prep-Technology Update.</B></FONT><BR>
Current issues in coal utilization, innovative plant design and economic recovery of low-grade coals are the focuses of the July issue.

<DT><H3>August</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Resurgence of Underground Mining.</B></FONT><BR>
After suffering some decline in recent years, underground mining is staging a rebirth. The August issue investigates whether any major leaps in underground mining techniques are left.
 
<DT><H3>September</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Mineral Economics and Financing.</B></FONT><BR>
Always important to mining activities, the economics and financing aspects of the modern-day minerals industry will be investigated in this issue, with emphasis on financing risk management.

<DT><H3>October</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Surface Mining-Coal and Metals.</B></FONT><BR>
Not to be outdone by the resurgence of underground mining, surface-mining workers have developed new techniques in coal and metals mining. The October issue reports on these new developments.

<DT><H3>November</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Exploration in Latin America.</B></FONT><BR>
The blush is still not off the bloom in Latin America mining. <CITE>MINING ENGINEERING</CITE> looks at Latin American copper developments in particular.

<DT><H3>December</H3>
<DD><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" SIZE=4><B>Environmental Control/Minerals Toxicity.</B></FONT><BR>
Plans to mitigate the environmental impact of mining are investigated, as well as reclamation and remediation efforts. Examined also is the toxicological effect of some minerals.
</DL>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>
<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to Customer Service</STRONG>.</P>
<P><CITE>me-editorial.stml</CITE><BR>Version 1.0</P>
<P>You are visitor number
317.</P>

