<HEAD>

<TITLE>

APCOM: 

Home Page

</TITLE>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#a6a6a6">

<TABLE WIDTH=100%>

<TR>

<TD><IMG SRC="apcom-logo.gif" ALT="APCOM:" ALIGN=left WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=180 HSPACE=12></TD>

<TH VALIGN=bottom><FONT FACE="Arial,Helvetica">

<H1>Application of Computers and Operations Research in the Mineral Industry

<HR SIZE=6>

</FONT></H1></TH></TR></TABLE>



<!-- Body of page goes here! -->



<P>We are in the Information Age!  Computer methods have become an

integral part of mineral exploration, mining, mineral processing

and management.  These methods were essentially unknown to

minerals professionals before 1960.  They have developed as

computer hardware and software have evolved over the last several

decades.  The constantly increasing portfolio of computer

applications includes analyzing and mapping exploration data,

estimating ore reserves, designing mines, planning production,

controlling processes, maintaining equipment, and managing human

resources, supplies inventories and all types of financial

information.</P>



<P>APCOM has been the major forum for discussion of the application of

computer methods in the mineral industry for nearly four decades. 

As information system technology has advanced from mainframes to

minicomputers to PCs to the World Wide Web, the APCOM Symposia

continue to be a highly effective mechanism for communicating

the advancements in minerals computer application

development worldwide.</P>



<P>It all started in 1961 as a series of workshops at University of

Arizona.  During the 1960s, new sponsors joined in at Stanford,

Colorado School of Mines and Penn State.  SME became a sponsor,

celebrating <I>A Decade of Digital Computing</I> at its 1969 fall

meeting.</P>



<P>APCOM went international in the 1970s with symposia sponsored by

the Canadian Institute of Mining and Metallurgy, the South

African Institute of Mining and Metallurgy, the University of

Clausthal, the Australasian Institute of Mining and Metallurgy

and the Technical University of Berlin, as well as by the US

sponsors.  To date, 26 APCOM international symposia have been

held.</P>



<P>In an effort to meet the needs of emerging groups of computer

users, regional APCOM symposia were started in 1995 with the

first one being held in Ljubljana, Slovenia.



<H2>Proceedings Volumes</H2>



<P>The evolution of minerals computer applications is documented in

the <I>APCOM Proceedings</I> produced for the symposia.  These volumes

are useful references for application developers and users. 

Several recent <I>APCOM Proceedings</I> are currently available.  Earlier

volumes may be found in mineral reference libraries around the

world.

<UL>

<LI><STRONG><I>26th Proceedings of the Application of Computers and Operations Research in the Mineral Industry</I></STRONG>, September 16-20, 1996, University Park, Pennsylvania, R. V. Ramani, Editor.  Sponsored by the Pennsylvania State University.  View the <A HREF="toc26.html">Table of Contents</A> or you may  <A HREF="apcom26.html">order from SME</A>.

<LI>25th Proceedings, <STRONG><I>APCOM XXV 1995: Application of Computers and Operations Research in the Minerals Industries</I></STRONG>, July 9-14, 1995, Brisbane Australia.  Sponsored by The Australasian Institute of Mining and Metallurgy.  <A HREF="apcom25.html">Order from AusIMM.</A>

<LI>24th Proceedings, <STRONG><I>24th Application of Computers and Operations Research in the Mineral Industry</I></STRONG>, October 31-Nov. 3, 1993, Montreal, Quebec, Canada.  Sponsored by the Canadian Institute of Mining, Metallurgy, and Petroleum.  (out-of-print)

<LI>23rd Proceedings, <STRONG><I>23rd Application of Computers and Operations Research in the Mineral Industry</I></STRONG>, April 7-11, 1992, Tucson, Arizona, Y. C. Kim, Editor.  Sponsored by the University of Arizona.  (out-of-print)

<LI>22nd Proceedings, <STRONG><I>XXII International Symposium APCOM</I></STRONG>, September 17-21, 1990, Berlin, Germany. Sponsored by the Technical University of Berlin.  <A HREF="apcom22.html">Order from T U Berlin.</A></UL>



<H2>Future APCOM International Symposia</H2>



<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.imm.org.uk/apcom.html" TARGET="_top">27th APCOM International Symposium</A>, London, United Kingdom Royal School of Mines, April 19-23, 1998.  Sponsored by the Institution of Mining and Metallurgy.

<LI>28th APCOM International Symposium, Golden, CO, USA.  Sponsored by the Colorado School of Mines.

<LI>29th APCOM International Symposium, Beijing, People's Republic of China.  Sponsored by the China Institute of Mining.

<LI>30th APCOM International Symposium, Phoenix, AZ, USA.  Sponsored by the Society for Mining, Metallurgy and Exploration (SME).</UL>



<H2>Future APCOM Regional Symposia</H2>



<UL>

<LI>2nd Regional APCOM Symposium, Moscow, Russia, August 24-28, 1997.  Sponsored by the Moscow State Mining University.

<LI>3rd Regional APCOM Symposium, Perth, Australia, December 7-9, 1998.  Sponsored by The Australasian Institute of Mining and Metallurgy and the Western Australian School of Mines.</UL>



<H2>APCOM International Council</H2>



<P>The APCOM symposia are organized by the APCOM International Council.  The council is composed of <A HREF="council.html"> representatives of the sponsoring organizations</A>.  It operates on a largely informal basis.  Its success is due to the personal commitment of a number of dedicated individuals, both council members and those working behind the scenes of the symposia.



<H2>Other Computer Resources for SME Members</H2>



<P><STRONG>COGSnet</STRONG>  is the computer bulletin board system sponsored by the Denver, Colorado-based Computer Oriented Geological Society (COGS) and SME.  It contains an extensive library of geology, mining and related software which can be downloaded.  COGSnet can be reached via the World Wide Web at <A HREF="ftp://ftp.csn.net/cogs" TARGET="_top">ftp://ftp.csn.net/COGS/</A>.  You can also connect directly by dialing 303-526-1617.  Set your modem for 1200 bps or greater, 8 data bits, 1 stop bit, and no parity.

<P><STRONG>MINSIM'96 - First International Symposium on Mine Simulation via the Internet.</STRONG>  The University of Idaho (USA) and the National Technical University of Athens (Greece) have hosted, completely via the Internet, a symposium on mining system simulation and related topics.  The symposium was held for two weeks beginning December 2, 1996.  The home page for the symposium has been terminated but information on the printed procedings volume is available from <A HREF="http://www.metal.ntua.gr/msslab/" TARGET="_top">http://www.metal.ntua.gr/msslab/</A> .  Additional information on the symposium, including an evaluation report, can be obtained by contacting the conference organizer, John Sturgul,  <A HREF="mailto:sturgul@uidaho.edu">sturgul@uidaho.edu</A>.

<P><STRONG>LINKS TO MINING COMPUTER APPLICATIONS INFORMATION ON THE WEB.</STRONG>  There are many useful Web sites dealing with mineral industry computer applications and the related software.  They are being started and updated almost daily by software and computer services companies, educators, consultants, users, students, and other interested parties.  Because the number of these sites is growing so rapidly, no attempt will be made to list them all here.  However, links to a few representative sites are included below to illustrate the variety of information available on the Web.  These sites contain many links to other mining applications sites.



<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.info-mine.com/technomine/software/software.html">

<STRONG>SOFTWAREMINE</STRONG></A>  contains links to mining software suppliers, newsletters, discussion groups, and job opportunities.  The <STRONG>SOFTWAREMINE MAILING LIST</STRONG> is a free discussion group on exploration and mining software-related issues.  To subscribe, send an e-mail message to  <A HREF="mailto:listproc@info-mine.com"> listproc@info-mine.com</A>  and type "subscribe softwaremine [your e-mail address]."</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ned.dem.csiro.au/DEM/LEGACY/index.html"><STRONG>Mining Software Catalogue</STRONG></A>  is a directory of information technology resources for exploration and mining.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.csn.net/~bgibbs/erthsci"><STRONG>GIBBS ASSOCIATES</STRONG></A>  publishes a newsletter and directory of mining applications software, and maintains the <STRONG>MINGEOL</STRONG>  mailing list for a free discussion group on mining, geology, and earth science software.  To subscribe, send an e-mail message to <A HREF="mailto:majordomo@csn.org"> majordomo@csn.org  </A>

 and type "subscribe mingeol [your e-mail address]."</UL>

</FONT4>





