<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting GEM Events
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I>GEM Events</I></H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<P>
The SME National GEM Committee will be presenting both <A HREF="#posters">Poster Sessions</A> and <A HREF="#workshops">Workshops</A> during the Annual Meeting. Posters will be gathered in Room A102, and presenters will attend their posters Tuesday afternoon from 2</FONT></B> - 3 p.m. Workshops will appear in the schedule of events. The list that follows details the currently available sessions and workshops.
</P>

<A NAME="posters">
<H2>
Poster Sessions
</H2>
<UL>
<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Publications</FONT></B> - Available for use in educational outreach programs.<BR>
<B>Presenters:</B> Nelson Fugate, Jackie Evanger<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Minerals Information Institute (MII)

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Teacher Workshops</FONT></B> - Demonstration of how to use hands-on materials.<BR>
<B>Presenters:</B> Jackie Beesley/Sharon Kirts<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Women in Mining Education Foundation

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Classroom Speaker Go-Kits</FONT></B> - As part of the National Mining Association's Mineral Education for Your Community, these kits were developed as a tool to assist people in planning and implementing classroom presentations. The goal is for each member company to choose one school in proximity to each of its operating or plant sites and establish a relationship of support and education.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Carol Sheppard<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> National Mining Association (NMA)

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">TEACHER ENHANCEMENT PROGRAMS:</FONT></B> Sponsored by the Colorado Mining Association Education Foundation and the Colorado School of Mines Office of Special Programs & Continuing Education. This program provides teachers with a comprehensive overview of all phases of the minerals industry.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Daniel S. Witkowsky<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Colorado School of Mines and the Colorado Mining Association Education Foundation, Inc.

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Southwest Wyoming Section Teacher Workshops</FONT></B> - These workshops were developed by a two time winner of the Local Section GEM Award. Types of activities included in the workshops will be demonstrated and a hands-on opportunity to try them will allow participants to feel more comfortable with the process. Handouts will detail the planning process, scheduling, costs and selected teacher feedback from workshop participants.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Susan E. Hutchinson<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B>  Southwest Wyoming Section of SME

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">High Impact Public Education Events</FONT></B> - Also a two time winner of the Local Section Award, the Colorado Section presents ways to reach the public in large numbers, such as NSTA, State Fairs, and other high visibility events, such as Taste of Colorado, with presentations such as Rocks on Your Face, free gold panning, and hands-on displays.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Guy Johnson<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SME</FONT></B> - Colorado Section

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Environmental Education in Farmington, NM</FONT></B> - Combined efforts of industry (BHP World Minerals), education, and government agencies use an easement as an outdoor classroom to train teachers at a Mineral Education Workshop and students at junior high level in mapping and observation skills, as well as instructing them in the complexity of the local environment.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Teri Conrad<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> BHP World Minerals, New Mexico Operation

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Government, Education, and Mining (GEM) in the San Francisco Bay Area</FONT></B> - San Francisco Section members pursue education outreach opportunities by making presentations, providing materials to schools, and sponsoring a travel award to deserving university undergraduate students to work at any mine in the world. The presenter was the winner of the 1995 GEM Individual Award.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Joseph J. Hanzel<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SME</FONT></B> - San Francisco Section

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">National Science Teachers' Association Area Conventions</FONT></B> - The significant role that the Minerals Education Coalition Booth in the Exhibit Hall plays in attracting and informing science teachers of all grade levels.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Sue Sawyer<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SME Headquarters

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">A Contrasting View: Students Who Were Exposed to the Common Ground Video Versus Those Who Were Not</FONT></B> - Based on written answers to teachers' questions on the subject of minerals and mining, a definite difference in students' attitudes towards the minerals industry is demonstrated by responses from those who viewed the video.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Nancy Bingham<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Caterpillar, Inc.

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Earth Day</FONT></B> - An opportunity to talk to people on the environmental side of the fence and attempt to create more positive attitudes towards minerals and mining. How to organize and run an Earth Day exhibit.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Walter S. Lombardo<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Nevada Division of Minerals & Southern Nevada Section of SME

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Reed Gold Mine</FONT></B> - Outreach activities based on a historic gold mine</FONT></B> - tours and classroom presentations. How to use available sites as a starting point for public education.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> John Dysart<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Reed Gold Mine

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Down to Earth</FONT></B> - Details are provided on training teachers in: mineral identification, the importance and value of mining in everyday lives, and ways the mining industry has changed and is changing. Working with teachers and science coordinators, this group planned materials and activities within the scope of the curriculum demands which were designed to provide a depth of knowledge for the teacher, and to interest and excite the students in the learning process.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Rocky Fulp<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> North Carolina State University & Carolinas Section of SME. 
</UL>

<A NAME="workshops">
<H2>
Workshops
</H2>
</A>
<UL>
<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Teacher Workshops as Presented by Women in Mining</FONT></B> - How to plan and execute teacher workshops, taking into account setup and teardown time, limited workshop time, location, availability of help, ease of activity to set up. Inlcudes ways to incorporate activities into different curriculums, not just earth science.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Arloa Woolford<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Women in Mining Education Foundation

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Activity-Based Teacher Workshops</FONT></B> - Information will be provided about making contacts with school districts, planning and scheduling a workshop, costs, and resources while participants experience the actual hands-on activities.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> Susan E. Hutchinson<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Southwest Wyoming Section of SME

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Rocks and Minerals Revisited</FONT></B> - This is a workshop which presents a review of basic tools used by field geologists and prospectors to identify specimens which teachers can use in the classroom. Topics addressed will include items needed for the course, what training is needed to present the course, physical properties for identification, the procedure used to identify rock specimens, what can be used as a handout to help teachers remember the procedure, and other sources of information.<BR>
<B>Presenter:</B> George S. Austin<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SME</FONT></B> - Central New Mexico Section

<LI><B><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial" COLOR="#008737">Fossil Exploration Workshop</FONT></B> - Using an educational fossil kit developed from waste material from the Lee Creek Mine in Aurora, NC, participants will learn about activities developed to appeal to 6-12 graders.<BR>
<B>Presenters:</B> Dennis LaPoint, Nancy West, 
	Cynthia Copolo<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SME</FONT></B> - Carolinas Section
</UL>	

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

