Membership</FONT>

</H1>

<P><CITE><FONT SIZE=5>Career Materials Available from SME</FONT><HR></FONT>

</CITE></P>

<P><CENTER><A HREF="http://rainbow.rmii.com/~pubs/navigator.html"><IMG SRC="art/navbtn.GIF" BORDER=0></A></P></CENTER>

<BR CLEAR=all>

<!-- Document Body Text --> <DL>

<DL>

<DT><H3><I>Careers for Engineers in the Minerals Industry</I></H3>

<DD>A career-guidance booklet for senior high/adult level.  Identifies career options in the minerals industry; describes specific professions and basic educational background required; lists colleges and universities with accredited engineering and engineering technology programs in minerals fields.  Cost: single copy, free; additional copies, 60 each.

<DT><H3>SME Guide to Minerals Schools, updated January 1996</H3>

<DD>Identifies educational institutions offering programs in mining-related environmental engineering, geological engineering, geophysical engineering, metallurgical engineering, mineral engineering, mineral processing engineering, mining engineering and mining engineering technology, and provides information and statistics (1985-1995) for those programs.  Listings include address, telephone number, fax and electronic mail code; where to get admissions information, persons responsible for the program; enrollment statistics by level and year; degrees offered and special program requirements; statistics on degrees conferred by level and year; and job placement assistance contact information.  Cost: $14.50

<P>The following booklets contain papers presented at the annual SME Career Planning Workshops.  Cost: $5 each.  Don't miss the next <B><A HREF="career_wkshp.stml">Career Planning Workshop</A></B>.</P>

<DT><H3>Career Opportunities-Changing with the Changing Times (1991)</H3>

<DD>"Career Opportunities in Manufacturing and Sales of Engineered Products and Equipment," "Career Opportunities in Waste Treatment," "Career Opportunities in Federal Agencies,"  "Minerals Processing: A Viable Career Option," "Graduate Programs in Mineral Processing and Extractive Metallurgy in the U.S.A.," "Perspectives on Career Planning and Placement for the Minerals Engineer," and "Making the Most of Your Institution's Career Placement Center."

<DT><H3>Competing in Today's Global Economy (1992)</H3>

<DD>"Job Search Strategies That Get Results," "Educational Opportunity Lost," "Skills in Most Demand for Geologists: A Perspective from the Mining Industry," "The Role of the Recruiter-Who, What, Where and Why!" "Selling Yourself and Other Things That Ain't Easy During the Career Search."

<DT><H3>SME Career Planning Workshop 1993</H3>

<DD>"Career Options Presented by Advanced Education: Advantages of M.S.- and Ph.D.-Level Studies in Geology, Mining, and Environmental Engineering," "Jobs-Where Are They?" "Success After Graduation: How to Get the Most of the University Career Center," and "Recruiting Firms Can't Produce What Doesn't Exist."

<DT><H3>SME Career Planning Workshop 1994</H3>

<DD>"Education-Who Needs It?" "Addressing Environmental Concerns: Preparing for Opportunities in the mid-1990's," "Career Opportunities for Mineral Engineers in the Industrial Minerals Sector," "Consulting Services-A Small Business Opportunity in Mining Industry," "The Ever-Changing Careers in the Mining Industry."

<DT><H3>SME Career Planning Workshop 1995</H3>

<DD>"After Graduation-New Challenges," "What is Needed to Be a Successful Researcher in the Minerals Industry," "Job Opportunities and Problems from an Academic Point of View," "Career Evolution: An Industrial Perspective," "Up the Down Staircase-Career Planning in a Time of Industry Consolidation and Downsizing"

<P>To order, call SME's Education Dept. at 800-763-3132, fax 303-973-3845, or e-mail <B><A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">smenet@aol.com</A></B></P>

</DL>

