<HEAD>

<TITLE>SME Students: About Accreditation.</TITLE>

<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><FONT SIZE=10>

<A HREF="membership.stml">
<IMG SRC="art/campus.GIF" ALIGN=right HSPACE=12 BORDER=0></A>

<A HREF="index.html">
<IMG SRC="art/smelogo.GIF" ALIGN=left HSPACE=12 BORDER=0></A>

SME Students</FONT>

</H1>

<P><CITE><FONT SIZE=5>About Accreditation</FONT><HR></FONT>

</CITE></P>

<P><CENTER><A HREF="http://rainbow.rmii.com/~pubs/navigator.html"><IMG SRC="art/navbtn.GIF" BORDER=0></A></P></CENTER>

<BR CLEAR=all>

<!-- Document Body Text --> <DL>

<DL>

<DT><H3>Accreditation in the United States</H3>

<DD>Accreditation plays a role in every college graduate's professional life.  Job and advancement opportunities may be less plentiful for graduates of nonaccredited institutions or programs.  Accreditation offers industry a certain minimum guarantee of the skills they can expect in recent graduates.  Accreditation promotes industrywide excellence.


<DT><H3>International Accreditation</H3>

<DD>The <B><A HREF="http://www.abet.ba.md.us" TARGET="_top">Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology (ABET), Inc.</A></B> has begun development of reciprocal accreditation recognitions with the signatory countries to the Washington Accord on mutual recognition of evaluation programs (Australia, Canada, Ireland, New Zealand, United Kingdom, Hong Kong, and the United States).  Requests are continually received for ABET to conduct consultancy visits to universities in other countries.  

<P>NAFTA requires that professionals be allowed to practice in Canada and Mexico without undue restrictions.  ABET is working toward that goal with a Policies and Procedures Manual for ABET Substantial Equivalency Evaluations.</P>


<DT><H3>SME's Role in Accreditation</H3>

<P>As a participating body of ABET, SME is responsible for appointing representatives to the ABET Board and Commissions.  SME also appoints members to serve on accreditation teams to visit the programs for which SME has curricular responsibility or shares responsibility with another participating society.  Qualified program evaluators are always in demand, particularly those employed in industry, women and minorities.  Click for information on <B><A HREF="program_eval.stml">how to nominate a program evaluator</A></B> or <B><A HREF="support_accreditation.stml">how to support accreditation.</A></B></P>

<DT><H3>Criteria</H3>

<DD>The SME committees concerned with accreditation are responsible for ratifying the general criteria with which engineering programs across the United States are evaluated.  They create and approve criteria specific to the <A HREF="geprog.stml"><B>geological engineering,</B></A> <A HREF="mincrit.stml"><B>mining engineering,</B></A> and mining engineering technology programs.  They also ratify environmental and metallurgical engineering program criteria.

<P>For a copy of the criteria for accrediting programs in engineering or engineering technology in the United States, contact <B><A HREF="http://www.abet.ba.md.us" TARGET="_top">ABET</A></B> at 410-347-7700, fax 410-625-2238.</P>

</DL>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Education Department</STRONG>.

<P><CITE>about_accreditation.stml</CITE><BR>Version 1.0</P>
<P>You are visitor number
402.</P>

