<HEAD>

<TITLE>SME Students: Mining Engineering Program Criteria</TITLE>

<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><FONT SIZE=10>

<A HREF="index.html">
<IMG SRC="art/smelogo.GIF" ALIGN=left HSPACE=12 BORDER=0></A>

<IMG SRC="art/campus.GIF" ALIGN=right HSPACE=12>

SME Students</FONT>

</H1>

<P><CITE><FONT SIZE=5>Proposed Mining Engineering Program Criteria</FONT><HR></FONT>

</CITE></P>

<P><CENTER><A HREF="http://rainbow.rmii.com/~pubs/navigator.html"><IMG SRC="art/navbtn.GIF" BORDER=0></A></P></CENTER>

<BR CLEAR=all>

<!-- Document Body Text -->

<CENTER><H1>DRAFT<BR>
ABET Program Criteria for Mining and Similarly Named Engineering Programs</H1></CENTER>
<P>Draft approved 14 March 1996 by the Society for Mining, Metallurgy, and Exploration (SME),  Inc.</P>
<H2>Applicability:</H2>
<P>These program criteria apply to engineering programs including "mining" and similar modifiers in their titles.</P>
<H2>Defining Statement:</H2>
<P>Mining Engineering applies extractive technologies to the earth's resources with an integrated planning and design approach.  Graduates of a basic-level program must be prepared to function as professionals in mining or related industries and can anticipate highly varied positions during their career.  Consequently, programmatic objectives will include specific knowledge and skills appropriate to anticipated tasks as well as sufficient breadth and depth of education to allow the graduate engineer to function in all aspects of mining and to acquire new skills as needed.</P>
<H2>Program Outcomes and Assessment (amplifies Criterion 3):</H2>
<P>Students must take the Fundamentals of Engineering Exam.</P>
<H2>Professional Component (amplifies Criterion 4):</H2>
<P>The basic-level curriculum must include appropriate instruction, such that students can demonstrate an understanding and fundamental knowledge of the following:
<OL>
<LI>mathematics through differential equations, calculus-based physics, general chemistry, and probability and statistics through applications;
<LI>in engineering sciences: statics, dynamics, strength of materials, fluid mechanics, thermo-dynamics, and electrical circuits;
<LI>in geology: characterization of mineral deposits and surrounding strata through concepts of physical geology, structural or engineering geology, and mineral and rock identification and properties. </OL></P>
<P>The basic-level curriculum must also include advanced study in engineering topics related to both surface and underground mining, including: mining methods, planning and design, ground control and rock mechanics, health and safety and environmental issues, and ventilation.  Additional engineering topics should include rock fragmentation, materials handling, mineral or coal processing, mine surveying, and valuation and resource/reserve estimation as appropriate to the program objectives.</P>

<P>The laboratory experience must include content on geologic concepts, rock mechanics, and other topics appropriate to the program objectives, such as mine ventilation or materials handling.</P>
<H2>Faculty (amplifies Criterion 5):</H2>
<P>Teaching of the professional components of a program must not be heavily dependent on just one faculty member.  Registration as a professional engineer is encouraged; at least one faculty member must be registered as a Professional Engineer.</P>

<P>Forward comments to: Eileen Ashworth at Dept. of Mining Engineering, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, 501 E. Saint Joseph St., Rapid City, SD  57701-3995; phone at (605) 394-1970),  FAX at (605) 394-5360  e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:eashwort@silver.sdsmt.edu">eashwort@silver.sdsmt.edu</A></P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Education Department</STRONG>.

