<TITLE>SME Students: Geological Engineering Program Criteria</TITLE>

<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><FONT SIZE=10>

<A HREF="index.html">
<IMG SRC="art/smelogo.GIF" ALIGN=left HSPACE=12 BORDER=0></A>

<IMG SRC="art/campus.GIF" ALIGN=right HSPACE=12>

SME Students</FONT>

</H1>

<P><CITE><FONT SIZE=5>Proposed Geological Engineering Program Criteria</FONT><HR></FONT>

</CITE></P>

<P><CENTER><A HREF="http://rainbow.rmii.com/~pubs/navigator.html"><IMG SRC="art/navbtn.GIF" BORDER=0></A></P></CENTER>

<BR CLEAR=all>

<!-- Document Body Text -->

<CENTER><H1>DRAFT<BR>
ABET Program Criteria for Geological and Similarly Named Engineering Programs</H1></CENTER>
<P>Draft available for comment for one year, as approved by the Society for Mining, Metallurgy, and Exploration, Inc.(SME) Accreditation and Curricular Issues Committee, Council of Education, and the AIME-SME Board of Directors on 14 March 1996.</P>
<H2>Applicability:</H2>
<P>These program criteria apply to engineering programs including "geological" and similar modifiers in their titles.</P>
<H2>Defining Statement:</H2>
<P>The program in geological engineering must provide the integration of science, mathematics, engineering, and communication in comprehensive design courses, problems, and reports concerning geological engineering.  Design activities in geological engineering normally require an understanding and application of the principles of geology, specifically the physical properties of the materials of the earth's crust, the effects of the processes that form the earth's crust, and the impacts of the works of society on these materials and processes in the solution to engineering problems.  Data gathering and analysis do not, by themselves, constitute design, but are important as a source of input to the design activities and are central to the process.  The recognition of constraints and alternative solutions along with optimal use of resources in reaching the best available resolution for the client and the public, while including ethics, environmental, economic, and societal considerations, constitute geological engineering design.</P>
<P>Geological engineering encompasses some or all but is not limited to:
<OL>
<LI>exploration for, development and exploitation of natural resources;
<LI>geomechanics;
<LI>site characterization, regulation cognizance, and planning;
<LI>natural and manmade hazard investigation;
<LI>studies of site and resource utilization; and 
<LI>hydrogeology and ground water studies and engineering.
</OL></P>
<H2>Professional Component (amplifies Criterion 4):</H2>
<P>Students should demonstrate proficiency in the following areas of study:
<OL>
<LI>Mathematics through differential equations, calculus-based physics, general chemistry, and probability and statistics through applications;
<LI>Geological subjects including physical geology, mineral and rock identification and properties, structural geology, principles of sedimentation or stratigraphy, field geology, and elements of geophysics;
<LI>Engineering sciences to include statics, properties/strength of materials, geomechanics, along with appropriate prerequisites.
</OL></P>
<H2>The faculty (amplifies Criterion 5):</H2>
<P>The program requirements must be controlled by a defined group of faculty members the majority of whom have at least one degree in engineering and who teach the majority of the program's required courses containing design experiences including the major design experience course.  Registration as a professional engineer is encouraged.</P>
<P>Forward comments to:  C. Dale Elifrits at 129 McNutt Hall, Rolla, Missouri 65409-0230; phone at (573) 341-4847,  FAX at (573) 341-6593  e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:cdfritz@umr.edu">cdfritz@umr.edu</A></P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Education Department</STRONG>.

