<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Short Courses
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I>Short Courses</I></H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<H1>
Belt Conveyor Drives: Advanced Mechanical and Electrical Considerations
</H1>
<H2>
February 22-23, 1997
</H2>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Overview</B></FONT><BR>
This course is an advanced course in the design and engineering of belt conveyor drives. The heart of a belt conveyor is the drive(s). It is the most important and complex component and offers the greatest number of available options. It is responsible for accelerating the belt, maintaining running speed, and in some cases, decelerating the belt. The application and control of torque from the drive system to the belt affects the performance, life, cost and reliability of the drive components as well as most other conveyor components. However, the selection of drive type and control algorithms are seldom easy. As conveyors become longer, faster and bigger, these decisions become more difficult. The best decisions require knowledge of the various drive characteristics and limitations, as well as knowledge of the overall conveyor system. This course will address conveyor drive requirements based on system parameters such as length, lift, tonnage, and profile. Extensive comparisons will be made between many drive options including complexity, versatility, maintenance, cost and reliability. Both mechanical and electrical engineers will benefit from this comprehensive study. A manufacturers poster session from 4-6PM on February 23 will highlight the newest products and services available in the industry.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Content</B></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><B>Determining Conveyor Drive Requirements (running)</B><BR>
How Much Horsepower, Single Vs Multiple Drives, Location (head, tail, return and carry) and load sharing
<LI><B>Determining Conveyor Drive Requirements (starting and stopping)</B><BR>
Starting Considerations and their Impact on the Whole Conveyor Design, Stopping Considerations and their Impact on the Whole Conveyor Design
<LI><B>Conveyor Drive Evaluation Criterion</B><BR>
Belt Drive System Introduction, Electric Motor Attributes, Belt Drive Attributes
<LI><B>Conveyor Drive Systems</B><BR>
AC Induction Motor with Full Voltage Starting and Direct Couplings, AC Induction Motor with Reduced Voltage Starting and Direct Couplings, Wound Rotor AC Motor and Direct Coupling, DC Motor and Direct Couplings, AC Induction Motor with Variable Frequency Control and Direct Couplings, AC Induction Motor with Full Voltage Starting and Fixed Fill Fluid Couplings, AC Induction Motor with Full Voltage Starting and Variable Fill Fluid Couplings, AC Induction Motor with Full Voltage Starting and Variable Fill Hydrokinetic Couplings, AC Induction Motor with Full Voltage Starting and Variable Mechanical Couplings
<LI><B>Belt Conveyor Controls</B><BR>
Drive Type Controller, Starting/Running/Stopping, Belt Protection Controls, Belt Operation Controls, Belt Control Apparatus
<LI><B>Case Studies</B>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Instructors</B></FONT>
Mark Alspaugh, Alspaugh Engineering Co., Littleton, CO (303-973-7357) and Michael Nave, CONSOL Inc., Pittsburgh, PA (412-831-4631).

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

