<H1>
Stormwater Management and Erosion Control
</H1>
<H2>
February 22-23, 1997
</H2>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Overview</B></FONT><BR>
Stormwater management and erosion control has become a significant concern for both active mining operations and closure activities. Recent legislation has changed the way that excavation work is performed on construction projects and is now being applied in varying degrees to mining projects. Regardless of the legal requirements, a good stormwater and erosion control plan can minimize site maintenance work, improve public relations, aid permitting and accelerate bond release. This course presents current environmental policy as it relates to erosion/sediment control and mining activities. Development of successful stormwater pollution prevention plans (SWPPs) are detailed. Generally accepted engineering hydrology principles are presented for analysis of the design "event", drainage basin affects and runoff potential. Erosion mechanisms and analysis of both overland and channelized flow conditions are presented. Finally, best management practices (BMPs) suitable for active sites and closures are discussed.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Content</B></FONT>
<UL><B>
<LI><B>The Regulatory Environment</B>
<LI><B>Preparation of Stormwater Pollution Prevention Plans</B>
<LI><B>Engineering Hydrology  Principles and Methods</B>
<LI><B>Analysis of Overland Flow Erosion Potential</B>
<LI><B>Analysis of Channel Erosion Potential</B>
<LI><B>Best Management Practices  Active Sites</B>
<LI><B>Best Management Practices  Closures</B>
</UL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Instructors</B></FONT>
This course is taught by Dwight Cabalka, American Excelsior Co., (303-973-0417) and Don Poulter, The Glasgow Engineering Group (303-904-4614) and an experienced team of lecturers who present and instruct within their expertise.

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

