<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Field Trips
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I>Field Trips</I></H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><CENTER><H2><I>
Thursday, February 27
</I></H2>
<H1>
Cresson Project<BR>
Cripple Creek & Victor Gold <BR>
Mining Company
</H1>
</CENTER></FONT>

<TABLE WIDTH=100%><TR><TD><B>
7:00 AM  5:30 PM
</B></TD>	<TD><B>
$65 per person
</B></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P>
The Cresson Project consists of an open pit gold mine, crusher, valley leach and carbon adsorptionelectrowinning facility. The Project is a revival of large-scale mining in the Cripple Creek Mining District and located 20 air miles southwest of Colorado Springs on the southwest flank of Pikes Peak, between the towns of Cripple Creek and Victor. The Project is operated by the Cripple Creek & Victor Gold Mining Company (a joint venture between Pikes Peak Mining Company and Golden Cycle Gold Corporation). The operation produces 160,000 ounces (troy) of gold per year along with silver, from a volcanic breccia and phonolite ore associated with 32 million year old volcanic diatreme. The average grade of the ore is 0.026 ounces per ton. The operation is the first to have been designed, constructed, and operated under new State mining and reclamation requirements. The 180-acre leach facility, with a capacity of 53 million tons, receives about 8.5 million tons of crushed ore per year, consists of double-and triple-lined sections, integrated with extensive surface and ground water monitoring. The tour includes an overview of past and present mining in the District, discussions of the geology, mining and recovery process, environmental permitting and reclamation activities.
<UL>
<LI>Attendees should wear warm, layered clothing, windbreakers and sturdy boots (steel toes preferred). Protective glasses and hardhats will be available on-site.
<LI>The trip includes transportation and a buffet lunch at the historic Imperial Casino Hotel in Cripple Creek. Additional time will be available at the Imperial Casino Hotel.
</UL>
</P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

