<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Field Trips
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I>Field Trips</I></H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><CENTER><H2><I>
Thursday-Friday, February 27-28
</I></H2>
<H1>
Powder River Basin<BR>
Northeastern Wyoming<BR>
North Antelope Mine & <BR>
Black Thunder Mine
</H1>
</CENTER></FONT>

<TABLE WIDTH=100%>
<TR>
	<TD><B>Departs:</B></TD>
	<TD>
	7 AM, Thursday, February 27, Hyatt Regency Hotel, Denver, CO
	</TD></TR>

<TR>
	<TD><B>Returns:</B></TD>
	<TD>
	2:30 PM, Friday, February 28, Hyatt Regency Hotel, Denver, CO
	</TD></TR>

<TR>
	<TD><B>Cost:</B></TD>
	<TD>
	$225
	</TD></TR>

<TR>
	<TD><B>Includes:</B></TD>
	<TD>
	Transportation from Denver to Wyoming, one night accommodation at the Best Western, Douglas, WY, two breakfasts, two lunches, one dinner, tour and guidebook.
	</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P>The Powder River Basin of Northeastern Wyoming is the largest strippable reserve of compliant coal (0.6 or less pounds of sulfur per million btu) in the United States. The Powder River Basin boasts annual production of 20% of the nation's coal and the six largest and most productive mines in the United States. This trip will visit two of these mines; the North Antelope Mine, Powder River Coal Company, 1996 projected 27.7 M tons and the Black Thunder Mine, Thunder Basin Coal Company, 1996 projected 39 M ton. The equipment used in these mines rivals the size of the Basin itself. Attendees will observe some of the largest moving equipment in operation; from 190 and 240 ton trucks, 15 to 84-cubic yard shovels and draglines of 45 to 160-cubic yard, to other specialized earth moving equipment in action. Attendees will also be able to see near-pit crushing and conveying systems and innovative dust control stilling sheds at both mines. As an added benefit, a film detailing the Powder River Basin's growth from the 1970s to its' current status as one of the most important coal-producing regions in the US is shown during the six-hour trip to the mine site. Attendees should wear warm casual clothing suitable for outdoor activity.</P>
<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

