<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Comminution Practices - High Pressure Roller Mills
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, A104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>E.Forssberg, Lule University of Technology, Lule, Sweden
<DD>A. K. Bakshi, Michigan Technological University, Houghton, MI
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B><I>Plenary Address:</I> Review of the Technical Literature on High-pressure Grinding Rolls:</B><BR>
<I>R. E. McIvor, Cleveland Cliffs, Inc., Cleveland, OH</I></FONT><BR>
Since their invention about 10 years ago, high-pressure grinding rolls have been widely adopted by the cement industry, and are now making inroads into mineral processing. Energy savings in the range of 25 to 50% compared to ball milling appear achievable. This paper reviews the technical literature on this important emerging technology.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Influence of the Feed Size Distribution on Throughput and Comminution of a High-Pressure Roller Mill:</B><BR>
<I>U. Sander and K. Shnert, Technical University of Clausthal, Clausthal-Zellerfield, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
The throughput of a high-pressure roller mill depends on the speed, the size distribution of the feed and the roller surface structure. The throughput increases proportional to the speed in the low speed range, then bends off the straight line and decreases above a certain limit. By reaching a critical maximum speed the mill beings to vibrate because of the acceleration effect and of the back-flow effect, especially by fine and very fine grinding. The fraction of the fine material in the feed controls strongly the mill performance. The paper deals with these aspects and discusses as well experimental results as theoretical considerations. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Towards the Development of a Work Index for the Roller Press:</B><BR>
<I>R. B. Klymowsky and J. Y. Liu, KHD Humboldt Wedag, AG, Cologne, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
This paper details the development of a functional work index that characterizes the relationship between the energy that is imparted by a roller press into materials, against the resultant size reduction achieved. Such a roller press work index is necessary for this new grinding technology to differentiate it from Bond's grinding work index, and to clear up confusion that arises with such a comparison to Bond. The energy usage in a roller press does not follow Bond's "Third Theory of Comminution" but rather Rittinger's theory of new surface creation. The relationships for such a work index have been developed from the viewpoint of an equipment manufacturer with the hope that they will be of assistance to the minerals industry in the design of grinding circuits incorporating roller press comminution. The work index contains modification factors that reflect the effect of oversize, fines, moisture, closed-circuit operation and roll surface characteristics on the energy versus size reduction relationship. It has evolved from the results obtained of testing a wide range of ore and mineral types that includes bauxite, coal, kimberlite, limestone, iron and chrome ores, base metal and gold ores. The results show that even for such a diverse range of materials, they all demonstrate similarities of behavior when comminuted in a roller press. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Operational Performance of Grinding Rolls at Cyprus Sierrite:</B><BR>
<I>L. G. Thompsen, Cypress Sierrita Corp., Green Valley, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The first high-pressure grinding roll in a copper mine was commissioned at Cyprus Sierrita in July 1995. This grinding roll is the world's biggest operating unit. It has a roll diameter of 2.4 meters and a face width of 1.4 meters. It is driven by two 3,000 horsepower motors. This paper will discuss the development of the grinding roll at Cyprus Sierrita and what it has done for comminution of Sierrita ore. Maintenance and operational performance will be discussed as well as test work including size reduction, power input, work index, and throughput.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Metallurgical Benefits of High Pressure Roll Grinding for Gold and Copper Recovery: </B><BR>
<I>W. Baum, Pittsburgh Mineral & Environmental Technology Inc., New Brighton, PA and N. Patzelt and J. Knecht, Krupp Polysius AG, Beckum, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
High pressure roll grinding (HPGR) is a mature but still expanding comminution technology. In the metals mining industry, HPGR is slowly gaining acceptance as a cost-efficient, high-throughput alternative for plant optimization. The increasing need to treat ores with progressively lower grades, complex mineralogies, refractory metal occurrence and variable rock types requires an energy-efficient comminution technology that reduces metallurgical problems inherent in conventional crushing and grinding, while stabilizing leach and flotation circuits and increases metals extraction. This paper will summarize the latest HPGR pilot test results for gold and copper projects in the United States and South America and describe the use of the high pressure grinding roll as a metallurgical tool. The application of HPGR for the treatment of heap-leach SX-EW copper ores, semirefractory gold ores, waste rock material and concentrator feeds will be illustrated with case histories. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Modelling of the HPGR Crusher: </B><BR>
<I>S. Morrell, W. Lim, F. Shi, and L. Tondo, University of Queensland, Indooroopilly, Qld, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
The high pressure grinding rolls (HPGR) is a relatively new technology which offers the potential benefits in energy savings, circuit simplicity and improved product characteristics in minerals processing applications. Over 300 machines are now operating world-wide, but most of these are used for grinding cement clinker, and relatively few are used in conventional mineral processing. One of the reasons for its current limited use in the minerals processing industry is that design, scale-up and flowsheet assessment procedures are seen to be relatively immature and untested. This has reduced confidence in the potential application of the technology. To help rectify this situation an industry funded research project was undertaken, one of whose aims was to develop and prove a mathematical model of the HPGR and a scale-up procedure. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Evaluation of High-pressure Roller Press for Teconite Comminution:</B><BR>
<I>R. L. Bleifuss, H. E. Goetzman, B. R. Benner, and S. Zhong, University of Minnesota, Duluth, MN</I></FONT><BR>
A commercial high pressure roller press (KHD 90/25) was installed at the Coleraine Minerals Research Laboratory for testing in October, 1994. Pilot plant evaluation of the high pressure roller press has shown that it can be used as an alternative to the rod mill for the comminution of taconite. A series of pilot plant tests were run to compare roller press products to rod mill products in a simulated taconite flowsheet using magnet separation and closed circuit ball milling. Further investigation of a hybrid grinding system, roller press crushing followed by ball mill grinding, indicate that the combination may represent the most energy efficient system for taconite processing. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

