<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Comminution Practices - Fine and Ultrafine Grinding, and Recycling
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, A104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. Wennen, Barr Engineering Co., Hibbing, MN 
<DD>K. J. Shoop, Michigan Technological University, Houghton, MI
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B><I>Plenary Address:</I>Ultrafine Grinding and Classification of Minerals:</B><BR>
<I>Y. Wang and E. Forssberg, Lule University of Technology, Lule, Sweden</I></FONT><BR>
This paper presents recent experimental results in wet ultrafine grinding and classification of industrial minerals (such as carbonates and kaolin clay) using a stirred ball mill and a high performance centrifuge. The studies have been focused on the effect of beads (size, density and load) on the grinding efficiency. The use of chemical additives and the control of slurry rheology is presented. The role of pre-crushing with a high-pressure roller mill on subsequent ultra-fine grinding is discussed for energy saving and size reduction. In addition, a disc-stack nozzle centrifuge for ultrafine classification duties at high solids contents is concerned. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B><I>Plenary Address:</I>Comminution Techniques for the Recycling of Wastes:</B><BR>
<I>H. Hoberg, RWTH Aachen, Aachen, Germany and G. Schubert, Tu Bergakademie Freiberg, Freiberg, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
A large and diverse array of size reduction equipment is now available for the comminution of waste materials. Selection is determined by the nature of the waste and by its behavior under external mechanical stressing. Accordingly, wastes can be divided into those with elastic/brittle and those with plastic or viscous behavior. Only in a few unique cases have the fundamentals of the comminution of plastic or viscous materials been presented. The paper centers on a systematic characterization of the types of stress fundamental to comminution. An analysis is presented of available technologies, centering on those machines designed for materials with plastic or viscous behavior. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>On Generation of Ultrafine Grinding Dusts:</B><BR>
<I>U. Schneider and H. Hoberg, RWTH Aachen, Aachen, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
Ultrafine dusts have achieved major technological significance, especially in the production of nanostructured materials. For a diverse range of substances the grinding behavior and the product characteristics change drastically in the transition from the micron to the colloid range. Apart from the material-specific peculiarities the type and intensity of stressing and the reactions between material and media in the grinding chamber are of utmost importance. On different high-melting oxides it was demonstrated that colloidally-disperse dusts with characteristic structures can be generated using special grinding techniques, often complemented by the use of grinding activities. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Charge Motion in Tower Mills:</B><BR>
<I>M. S. Duffy, Mount Isa Mines, Mount Isa, QLD, Australia and S. Morrell, J. K. Mineral Research Center, Indooroopilly, QLD, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
To exploit the mineral resources of fine-grained ore bodies the mineral processing industry is turning to fine-grinding technology, of which tower milling has become an established part. However, compared to other mills relatively little is known about the operating mechanisms in tower mills. In all milling processes one of the keys to understanding how they work is in knowing how their grinding media move. To investigate the ball motion in tower mills a glass mill was therefore constructed and measurements taken of the movement of the grinding media. This paper describes the results from this study. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Powder Surface and Polymer Structural Changes in Ultrafine Grinding in Stirred Media Mills:</B><BR>
<I>J. Zheng, C. C. Harris and P. Somasundaran, Columbia University, New York, NY</I></FONT><BR>
Powder surface and polymer structural changes have been studied as a function of grinding time, stirring speed and polymer and mineral types. It was found that specific surface area can be increased over 100% by using polymer additives; particle surface and polymer structure were also found to change during grinding. Powder surface and polymer properties have been determined using FTIR, ESR, Fluorescence, TOC, ICP, and HPLC/GPC analysis, and surface and polymer properties are correlated with operating variables and the mechanisms involved are explored. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Tertiary Grinding Circuit Installation at Chino Mines Company:</B><BR>
<I>J. L. Vanderbeek, Chino Mines Co., Hurley, NM</I></FONT><BR>
The Chino Concentrator commenced operation in 1982 as a SAG-ball mill circuit which could process 37,500 stpd of ore. Since 1982 a series of process improvements such as the addition of two stages of SAG recycle crushing allowed throughputs to increase to more than 48,000 stpd, at the expense of significantly coarser flotation feed sizing and reduced recovery. To compensate, a third (tertiary) stage of grinding consisting of four 1250 hp Vertimills was installed which has allowed the flotation feed size and recovery to return to historical levels. The design and operational characteristics of the Tertiary Grinding Circuit are described. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Feasibility of Gold Recovery from a Hellyer Concentrator Tailing Following Very Fine Grinding:</B><BR>
<I>K. R. Weller, M. Gao and B. J. I. Adlair, CSIRO, Pinjarra Hills, QLD, Australia and G. D. Richmond, 2 Aberfoyl Ltd., Burnie, Tas, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
After ultrafine grinding in a 4-litre continuous horizontal stirred mill to a P80 of 2.3 um, gold recovery by cyanide leaching from the concentrator tailing (containing 3 g/t gold and 144 g/t silver) increased to 23.3%; far short of a mill manufacturer's claim that ultrafine grinding would lead to extractions greater than 90%. Grinding and leaching conditions are discussed. An extensive QEM*SEM Trace Mineral Search on the unground tailing failed to identify any gold-bearing particles but did identify silver-bearing particles which displayed a variety of textural associations and liberation characteristics. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

