<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Comminution Practices - Mill Design Considerations
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, A104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>R. E. McIvor, Cleveland Cliffs, Inc., Cleveland, OH
<DD>H. Hoberg, RWTH, Aachen, Germany
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B><I>Plenary Address:</I>Worldwide Grinding Circuits Practice: </B><BR>
<I>D. Malhotra, Mineral Resource Development, Inc., Wheat Ridge, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Comminution circuits in general account for fifty percent of capital and operation costs for a processing plant. Significant advances have been made in optimization of these circuits. One would expect a few circuits would be the favored designs for plants. Review of worldwide grinding circuits indicate a variety of circuits designs are utilized for non-technical reasons. A brief review of circuits and reasons for their selection are discussed in this paper.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Comminution in a Mining Context: </B><BR>
<I>D. J. McKee, G. Chitombo and T. J. Kojovoc, JKMRC, Indooroopilly, Brisbane, QLD, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
The product sizing and tonnage from a grinding circuit are the end result of a series of linked size reduction stages which always involve: fragmentation in mining; degradation in transport of ore; crushing and finally grinding. A case study is presented which illustrates the substantial effect on autogenous mill throughput of different mining practice. It is shown that it is possible to model each of the size reduction steps of fragmentation, degradation, crushing and grinding. The way in which this predictive capability is used is dependent on the operating constraints of each mine-mill combination.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Effect of Media Sizing on Ball Milling Efficiency: </B><BR>
<I>R. E. McIvor, Cleveland-Cliffs, Inc., Cleveland, OH</I></FONT><BR>
This paper reviews the historical literature and the author's experience with regard to the effect of that the selection of grinding ball size or sizes has on ball mill grinding efficiency. The conclusions presented provide guidelines for single and multi-size charging practices in commercial milling operations. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Extrusion Effects in the High Pressure Grinding Rolls: </B><BR>
<I>W. I. L. Lim and J. J. Campbell, CSIRO, Pinjarra Hills, Brisbane, QLD, Australia and L. Tondo, JKMRS, Brisbane, QLD, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
Due to the abrasive nature of typical ores, significant wear rate has typically occurred in using high pressure grinding rolls (HPGR) to grind ores. A probable wear mechanism is the abrasion of the rolls surface due to extrusion of the compacted material as it leaves the rolls. This study involves laboratory, pilot and full-scale HPGR's. The results indicate that extrusion increase with increasing grinding pressure and rolls diameter, while the use of studded or profiled rolls significantly reduces the extrusion effect compared to smooth rolls. Rolls speed and feed moisture can also have significant effect on extrusion.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Developments in the Design of Large Size Grinding Mills:</B><BR>
<I>N. Patzelt and J. Knecht, Krupp Polysius AG Beckum, Beckum, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
There are several concepts on the market for the design of large size grinding mills. One difference is the way how to support grinding mills - either on trunnions with conical endwalls or on the mill shell itself applying slipper pad bearings. Also for the drive systems several possibilities exist - conventional open gear drives, gearless drives and a more recent development the COMBIFLEX drive. The design features of the world's biggest shell support SAG mill will be discussed. The 34 ft. SAG mill is equipped with an 11,000 KW (14,750 HP) double COMBIFLEX drive arrangement.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Design and Economic Considerations of Comminution Circuits: </B><BR>
<I>W. H. Cooksey, Kilborn International Inc., Englewood, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Two comminution scenarios are investigated to optimize the rate of return on a new plant investment. A combination of crushing (primary, secondary, and tertiary) and grinding (SAG mill, rod mill, and ball mill) circuits is required to achieve the desired product size with the best economic performance levels. The selected circuits are dependent on costs associated with numerous project, equipment, and ore specific criteria. Project specific items include location of ore deposit, tonnage, and production schedule. Equipment criteria entail capital costs for the equipment, installation and start-up time and operating costs associated with power efficiency, steel consumption, and maintenance. Ore specific items consist of required product size, recovery, ore hardness, ore abrasion, ore impact index, and chemical composition. Factors influencing the selection of the crushing and grinding plant require systematic evaluation to optimize plant performance and economic return. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Proper Mill Application for Today's Industry: </B><BR>
<I>C. M. Sams, Fuller Mineral Process, Bethlehem</I></FONT><BR>
Todays' large milling applications vary greatly from traditional duty. New approaches in mill process applications test the old tried and proven methods, compromising mill energy efficiency, for improvements in availability and production increases. This paper reviews the traditional application standards and evaluates the changes in operating philosophy of large mills since the mid 1980's. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Establishing the Energy Efficiency of a Ball Mill: </B><BR>
<I>R. P. King, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
It is generally accepted that the energy efficiency of a ball mill is low, but it has never been possible to establish a suitable base line for the calculation of the theoretical energy that is required. Calculations that are based on the production of new surface area are not appropriate. The problem is complicated because the energy is applied discretely to individual particles that absorb energy and may or may not break and, if they do, the size distribution of progeny particles from each breakage event is determined strongly by the amount of energy that is absorbed. Properly designed single-particle breakage tests in the laboratory have made it possible to measure the fracture energy of a wide variety of particulate materials under conditions equivalent to those found in industrial ball mills. The fracture energy is the energy that is actually required to break a particle under impact loading. The fracture energy also determines the relationship between the size spectrum of the progeny and the applied energy. These measurements make it possible to calculate the minimum energy required to reduce a particular material from a given feed size distribution to any required product size distribution. This gives a realistic base line for the calculation of energy efficiency. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

