<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Coal Availability/Recoverability
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:00 AM, C110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>T. J. Rohrbacker, US Geological Survey, Denver, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>National Coal Resource Assessment: Coal for the Twenty-First Century:</B><BR>
<I>H. Gluskoter, US Geological Survey, Reston, VA</I></FONT><BR>
The total coal resources of the US are large and will satisfy the increased demand that is projected for the next several decades. However, once we look beyond the life expectancies of existing mines, it is not easy to predict which regions and which coal beds will be produced. The current National Coal Resource Assessment, conducted by the US Geological Survey with the cooperation of many State agencies, other Federal agencies, and coal companies, is identifying those coals expected to be available to meet the demand during the next several decades and is reporting upon their location, quality, and other significant characteristics.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Changes in the National Coal Availability and Recoverability Studies:</B><BR>
<I>M. D. Carter, US Geological Survey, Reston, VA and T. J. Rohrbacher, US Geological Survey, Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Detailed resource analysis of individual 7.5-minute quandrangle areas by the US Geological Survey (USGS) and State geological agencies have found that, in those areas studied in the Appalachian region and Illinois basin, approximately 50 percent of the original coal resource is available for mining, 25 percent is recoverable, and a mere 8 percent of the total resource can be extracted and marketed profitably. During 1995 and 1996 three developments have added flexibility, versatility, continuity, and useability to the studies: 1) establishment of the USGS's National Coal Resource Assessment program, 2) institutional merging of the US Bureau of Mines' Coal Recoverability Studies into the USGS's Coal Availability Studies, and perhaps most significantly, 3) the ability to study multiple quandrangle areas in single models allowing a more regional approach in a reasonably short time frame. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Quality and Distribution of the Anderson-Wyodak Coal Zone, Powder River Basin, Montana and Wyoming-A First Step in the National Coal Resource Assessment:</B><BR>
<I>G. D. Stricker, M.S. Ellis and R. M. Flores, US Geological Survey, Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Region IV of the National Coal Resource Assessment includes the Tertiary coal producing basins within the northern Rocky Mountains and Great Plains. The principal source of coal in the Powder River Basin is the Anderson-Wyodak coal zone, which splits and merges, is missing in some areas, and is as thick as 140 feet. Over 800 samples of this coal zone were analyzed for moisture, ash, and total sulfur contents; heat-of-combustion; and for environmentally sensitive trace elements. Not all of the Anderson-Wyodak coal zone will be available for mining. Many geologic and economic factors and government mandates control the availability of the resource. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Coal Availability and Recoverability Studies in Kentucky: Implications for National Coal Assessment:</B><BR>
<I>G. A. Weisenfluh, Kentucky Geological Survey, Lexington, KY</I></FONT><BR>
The USGS national coal assessment program is evaluating original coal resources at a 1:250,000 scale, whereas the coal availability and recoverability programs have focused on single quadrangles (1:24,000 scale) and include analysis of factors that affect the mineability of the coal. Studies using single quadrangles tend to be weighted toward local factors affecting availability and recoverability, and do not always reflect regional patterns. To better measure these regional factors, contiguous areas with as many as 15 quadrangles have been analyzed without modifying the scale of data collection. Applying coal availability and recoverability factors to the results of the national coal assessment (1:250,000 scale) may be accomplished with an acceptable reduction in data accuracy.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Availability of Coal in Illinois for Efficient, Low-cost Mining:</B><BR>
<I>C. G. Treworgy and C. Chenoweth, Illinois State Geological Survey, Champaign, IL</I></FONT><BR>
Whether Illinois' huge reserves of bituminous coal play a role in future US coal production depends on their availability and mining cost. Residential and commercial developments restrict access to coal reserves in some parts of Illinois, but geological and technical factors (seam thickness, stripping ratios, roof conditions, partings, faults, and size and geometry of the reserve block) have greater effect on the coal's availability for mining. The collective impacts of these factors significantly reduce coal availability in some parts of Illinois, but large blocks of reserves suitable for efficient, low-cost mining operations appear to remain available elsewhere. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Late Paleozoic Illinois Basin Brine Migration-Consequences for Coal Quality:</B><BR>
<I>M. B. Goldhaber and J. R. Hatch, US Geological Survey, Denver, CO and E. L. Rowan, US Geological Survey, Menlo Park, CA</I>
This study describes geochemical data which confirm a major regional fluid-flow event in the Illinois basin during the early Permian (approximately 272 MY BP) which resulted in the genesis of two large sediment-hosted ore districts located at the north and south ends of the basin. One consequence of this basin-wide fluid flow is enrichments in the Pennsylvanian coals of western Illinois in ore-related elements, primarily Zn, Cd, Pb, As, Co and Mo. Previous fluid-inclusion studies on ZnS in coal from this region document formation from a brine whose temperature and salinity was similar to ore fluids. We hypothesize that the metal-enriched coals occur where rocks of the Mississippian system pinch out, permitting ore-bearing fluids to flow upward into the overlying coals. This mechanism is supported by paleoflow calculations employing a finite difference modeling code.</P>


<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

