<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Health and Safety
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, C110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>B. Francart, MSHA, Pittsburgh, PA
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Reducing Longwall Noise with Acoustical Material on the Shields-A Preliminary Analysis: </B><BR>
<I>J. P. Rider, E. T. Thimons and A. E. Prokop, US Dept. of Energy, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
The Mining Health and Safety Division of the US Department of Energy is studying the effect of covering the underside of longwall shields with acoustical material to reduce reverberating noise along the face. Experiments using acoustical absorptive insulation were conducted at the full scale simulated longwall test facility located at the Pittsburgh Research Center. The undersides of ten 1.5 m (5 ft.) wide shields were covered with acoustical material. Sound levels were recorded every 1.5 m along a 15.2 m (50 ft) section of the simulated face. The analysis of the data indicated that a 2.0-3.0 dBA noise reduction was achieved between the shearer drums and a 4.0-5.5 dBA attenuation was attained upwind of the headgate drum. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Effects of Intake Airflow Velocity on Average Face Methane Concentrations: </B><BR>
<I>C. D. Taylor, J. P. Rider and J. A. Zimmer, Pittsburgh Research Center, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
The purpose of this research was to examine how changes in the velocity of intake air affect face methane concentrations. A range of face operating conditions (scrubber flow: 1.9 and 3.3 m3/s, setback distances: 3, 9 and 15 m) were simulated in a surface test gallery. Methane gas released in the gallery was monitored at several locations to evaluate the effects of air velocity on methane dilution and removal. For each of the conditions tested, methane concentrations were reduced when intake velocity was increased from 1.3 to 2.5 m/s. Effects due to velocity were greatest for shorter setback distances and lower scrubber flow. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Forensic Investigations of Mining Accidents by the Mine Safety and Health Administration: </B><BR>
<I>S. Sawyer, MSHA, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
The Pittsburgh Safety and Health Technology Center of the Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA) provides engineering and scientific support to the inspectorate personnel of MSHA. One of the Center's myriad roles is to assist in the investigation of mining accidents, especially those involving fatalities. Center personnel utilize forensics to help uncover the causes of accidents and to make technical recommendations on preventing future similar mishaps. To exemplify a typical forensic investigation, this paper documents the methodology used in determining the reasons for a boat sinking, which resulted in a double fatality on a mine company pond. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Targeting and Prioritizing Safety Interventions in West Virginia:</B><BR>
<I> R. L. Grayson, University of Missouri, Rolla, MO and R. C. Althouse, J. M. Dean, G. L. Winn and M. J. Klishis, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
Using powerful database management software, nested-field analysis and micro-analysis of narratives have been recently made of West Virginia accident data, resulting in a new approach for targeting and prioritizing safety interventions by county, mine size, specific mine, job title, type injury, etc. and combinations of these parameters. The analyses can (and have) been useful in focusing training or discussion groups on specific work problems, trends, conditions, and situations for the targeted groups of miners. Application of the technique, which will be presented in this paper, also allows comparisons of various performance measures among mines. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Economic Decision-making for Methane Drainage Systems for Underground Coal Mines: </B><BR>
<I>J. M. Mutmansky and A. Wang, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA</I></FONT><BR>
The ventilation system in any underground coal mine requires a base level of ventilating air into every mining section to meet the minimum requirements of mining regulations. If the mine has high methane (or dust) levels, the ventilating air quantity is increased to keep methane and dust levels in check. However, other methods of controlling both dust and methane levels also exist. In the case of methane, control may be affected in part by a methane drainage system. This paper defines the basic economic model for decision-making when considering a methane drainage system for an underground coal mine. The adoption of a drainage system will require a significant capital and operating expense. The model outlines the economic structure of the decision and considers the costs and benefits when the he methane can be marketed and when the methane is vented to the atmosphere. The effects on the dust levels and the safety of the mine will also be considered, both in a general format and as economic variables. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Horizontal Stress and Longwall Headgate Ground Control: </B><BR>
<I>C. Mark and T. P. Mucho, US Dept of Energy, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Horizontal stresses are caused by global plate tectonic forces. During 1995 alone, they were largely responsible for closing two US longwall mines. This paper presents eight case histories from Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Kentucky, and Alabama. Each mine encountered roof falls or difficult ground conditions in the headgate, caused by horizontal stress concentrations. The problems are detailed, and the control measures adopted are described. The paper also discusses detailed measurements made at two adjacent Pennsylvania longwalls. One headgate was oriented to avoid a horizontal stress concentration, and the other was not. Eliminating the stress concentration dramatically reduced roof support loads and roof deformation. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Evaluating Jet Fan Performance in Conjunction with Machine-mounted Dust Scrubbers: </B><BR>
<I>J. P. Rider, C. E. Taylor, and J. A. Zimmer, Dept of Energy, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
The number of extended cut mining systems has increased significantly in coal mines over the last decade, and there is a constant push to extend the face ventilation systems to even greater setback distances. The need to maintain airflow at setback distances of 40 ft and beyond requires that methods for delivering intake air to the face be improved, or alternative ventilation techniques be implemented. For this reason, research was conducted at the Pittsburgh Research Center to evaluate the performance of jet fans used in conjunction with machine-mounted scrubbers. A series of tests utilizing a simulated mine entry were conducted with a full-scale continuous miner at jet fan setback distances of 40, 60, and 90 ft. Available air in the last open cross-cut was regulated at 9000 or 14000 cfm. Scrubber flows of 4000, 7000, and 14000 cfm were used in combination with jet fan flows of 4000 and 7000 cfm. In addition, blowing brattice ventilation systems were tested for comparison with the jet fan. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

