<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Coal Preparation I - Upgrading of Low-Rank Coals
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, C110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chairs:</B>
<DD>D. E. Walsh, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK
<DD>W. G. Willson, Coal-Water Fuel Services, Fairbanks, AK
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Overview of Low-rank Coal Drying:</B><BR>
<I>W. Willson, Coal-Water Fuel Services, Fairbanks, AK, B. Irwin, Int'l. Coal Preparation Consultants Ltd., Calgary, AL, Canada, and D. E. Walsh, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK</I></FONT><BR>
Low-rank coal (LRC) drying processes are generally categorized by operating temperature, drying environment and type of feed (either sized or ground coal). Within these broad categories, drying processes differ according to the type of drying equipment and methods of quenching and stabilizing the dried products. This paper focuses on the product quality of various LRC drying processes including conventional low and high temperature evaporative drying and non-evaporative, hydrothermal drying. The former may be preferred if the dried product can be utilized immediately, but moisture re-absorption, spontaneous heating and fines production during handling are problems associated with longer term storage, transportation and utilization. Methods for reducing these problems are discussed. Hydrothermal processing is an advanced technology featuring high pressure, non-evaporative drying, which solves stability problems by producing a liquid fuel. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Considerations for Blending Low-rank and High-rank Coals:</B><BR>
<I>M. W. Downing and O. I. Ogunsola, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK</I></FONT><BR>
An environmental regulations become more stringent and clean coal becomes more scarce and expensive, some interrelated factors must be considered to derive maximum benefits of coal blending. These factors may be broadly classified as technical, economical, environmental and geopolitical. While it is easy to determine the economic and geopolitical merits/demerits of a blend, it is difficult to predict the combustion and emission characteristics of a blend of those individual coals. This paper discusses some of these factors based on an ongoing study in our laboratory and on information obtained from the literature. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Low-rank Coal Ash Characterization:</B><BR>
<I>Washability and Utilization Implications: P. D. Rao and D. E. Walsh, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK</I></FONT><BR>
Chemical and physical properties of typical low-rank coal (LRC) ash are significantly different than bituminous coal ash. With the exception of extraneous ash, which is incorporated during mining or is due to ash partings within or between coal seams, LRC ash consists primarily of inherent ash that is bonded into the coal's organic matrix or finely disseminated mineral matter. This paper reviews the nature of LRC ash, both inherent and extraneous, and how this impacts the prospects for washing and utilizing LRCs. A literature review, as well as washability data, proximate and ultimate analysis and ash analyses of over 25 Alaskan LRC seams are used as a basis for this discussion. The authors' recent research into the nature and distribution of phosphorus in an Alaskan LRC is also discussed. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Characterization of Hydrothermally Dried Low-rank Coals:</B><BR>
<I>D. E. Walsh, P.D. Rao, O. Noirot, H. C. Owens and J. R. Mokka, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK</I></FONT><BR>
This study investigated the effects of temperature, residence time, and particle size on the degree of low-rank coal (LRC) upgrading for a non-evaporative drying process: hot water drying (HWD). Replicated, factorial tests were conducted on three Alaskan LRCs. Within tested particle size range, there was no significant effect due to particle size. Experimental results indicate that LRC upgrading via HWD occurs rapidly within the first 10-20 minutes of residence time; thereafter, the upgrading process slows down. The properties of the hot water dried products were very sensitive to process temperature. Calorific value, carbon and oxygen contents, equilibrium moisture and Hardgrove grindability all appear to change linearly with process temperature within the 275C to 325C range. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

