<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Surface Mining 
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, C112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>C. J. Johnson, K. T. K. Mining of Venezuela, Rolla, MO
<DD>W. R. Wallace, Kerr-McGee Coal Corp., Gillette, WY
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Driving Down Haul Road Costs: </B><BR>
<I>L. E. O'Neill, Caterpillar, Inc., Peoria, IL</I></FONT><BR>
During the past decade the trend has been toward larger mining trucks, placing demands for larger, more efficient support equipment. A well-designed and maintained haul road is important in achieving the lowest hauling cost per ton. This paper will cover the design features of a larger and more efficient motor grader to meet the needs of mines operating larger haul trucks. A comparison will be made with current designs, as well as predicted performance advantages. Initial customer experience will be shared regarding this new technology. This new technology will expand the application range of motor graders and should be of interest to the mining industry worldwide. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Computer-based Hazard-awareness Assessment Program for Surface Mines: </B><BR>
<I>D. A. Poukhovski and C. J. Bise, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Two integral components of the 30 CFR 48 training requirements mandated for new miners, newly employed experienced miners, and the annual refresher training of all miners are hazard recognition and prevention of accidents. Unlike instruction preparation for fact-based material, hazard-recongnition instruction preparation places a particular challenge before safety-training specialists because they are often limited in their ability to adequetely gauge the trainees' levels of awareness prior to training, in addition to the usual concerns of training relevance and thought-provoking presentation. Computer-based instruction is particularly well suited for assisting trainers in developing hazard-recognition topics because it can be used in pre-training and post-training modes for assessment of training effectiveness, as well as during training as a presentation tool. Therefore, this paper will present a recent approach developed at Penn State to apply this technology for assessment and instruction of accident prevention through hazard recognition, with a discussion of results gathered from field tests in several surface coal mines. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Towards a More Cost-effective Mining Truck: </B><BR>
<I>A. W. Dickerson, BHP Research, Clayton, VIC, Australia, F. A. Bartley, Liebherr Mining Truck Inc., Baxter Springs, KS and G. Hollier, BHP Australia Coal, Dysart, QLD, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
Following on from many years of research work aimed at improving the efficiency of truck haulage operations in mines operated by BHP Minerals, BHP Research developed a concept for a much more cost-effective rear dump mining truck. A proof of concept prototype truck is now operating in an Australian coal mine. The key features of the concept are outlined and some results from the initial evaluation of the proof of concept prototype truck are provided. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Backhoe/Truck Fleets versus Tractor-scrapers in Thin Lift Materials:</B><BR>
<I>J. G. Pippenger and R. J. Ziegler, The Coteau Properties Co., Beulah, ND</I></FONT><BR>
The Coteau Properties Company's Freedom Mine is a surface lignite operation located near Beulah, North Dakota. As part of the mining process, Coteau removes and replaces thin layers of suitable plant growth material (SPGM) generally ranging in thickness between one and five feet. Historically, tractor-scrapers have completed this work, however, rising tractor-scraper costs and increasing haulage distances sent Coteau in search of a lower cost method resulting in the acquisition of a backhoe/truck fleet in 1995. This presentation reviews the study justifying the fleet's purchase and the actual performance compared to tractor-scrapers during the first year of operation. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

