<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Coal Preparation II - Plant Design
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, C110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chairs:</B>
<DD>P. S. Jacobsen, Burns and Roe Services Corp., Littleton, CO
<DD>J. S. Laskowski, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Practical Optimization Strategies for Coal-washing Plants:</B><BR>
<I>R. P. King, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
Coal washing plants are commonly designed to process different size fractions of the feed material in parallel sections of the plant. This allows the choice of the optimal equipment type for each size range and significant gains in processing efficiency are consequently realized. However, plants with this structure must be nicely set up in terms of particle sizes at which the feed is split and in terms of the target separation densities that are set up for each of the individual washing operations. The choice of these operational settings is a difficult optimization problem since choices made for one setting affect the performance of all the other operations in the plant. A combination of classical optimization theory and modern plant simulation techniques provides solutions that can be easily implemented in operating plants and which lead to significant increases in yield with no sacrifice of ash or sulfur levels over conventional nonoptimal plant setups. The implementation of the optimal strategy does not increase operating costs. Typical examples of the optimization procedure are given in the paper. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Towards a General Distribution Model for Separator Design:</B><BR>
<I>M. S. Klima and P. T. Luckie, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Proper analysis of washability data can lead to the development of a maximum yield coal preparation plant flowsheet. Simulations, as simple as spreadsheet mass/water balancing, are important in examining yield maximization and middlings liberation. Key to flowsheet simulations is the distribution model, expressing the probability of a species reporting to the product stream. There are many such models in the literature. This paper examines a functional form that fits most of the proposed distribution functions. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>High Capacity Processor-A Novel Design for Coal Pre-combustion Cleaning:</B><BR>
<I>D. G. Chedgy, S. Yu, M. A. Sharpe and J. V. Ghelarducci, CLI Corp., Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
This article presents a novel design for coal pre-combustion cleaning, called the High Capacity Processor (HCP). This design is different  from the conventional designs with the equivalent capacity, and is characterized by four features: 1) the use of highly efficient cleaning devices operating within a wide size and specific gravity range; 2) the use of single units of high capacity equipment for each individual process; 3) much lower capital and operating costs; and 4) a very compact plant construction. This design has been applied for the Dipka Coal Preparation Plant in India. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Developments in Dense Medium Cyclone Circuit Design:</B><BR>
<I>R. Robertson, Massey Coal Services, Inc., Charleston, WV and D. S. Placha, R. L. Terry and L. A. Watters, Sedgman, Bridgeville, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Dense medium cyclones are the preferred means for cleaning 1/2 in. x 14 to 28 Mesh (12.7 mm x 1.0 to 0.6 mm) raw coal and are becoming a common choice for cleaning raw coal from a nominal top size of 2-1/2 in. to 3 in. (63.5 mm to 76.2 mm) down to 14 to 28 Mesh (1.0 mm to 0.6 mm). During the last ten years, dense medium cyclone circuitry design has undergone changes which have combined to improve process efficiency. This paper describes these improvements and compares present day design with the design used prior to the mid 1980's. Improvements in the following areas are described: raw coal desliming, cyclone configuration, drain and rinse applications, dilute medium circuitry, and instrumentation and control. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>An Overview of Russian Coal Preparation Technology and the Integration of US Principles and Practices:</B><BR>
<I>K. Wyzykowski, Scott European Capital Corp., Valencia, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Russian coal beneficiation technology developed essentially to meet both the problems common to the preparation of coals and the unique circumstances of their utilization marketplace, environment, and social/economic conditions. Steam coal preparation plants generally employ dry screening with only the coarse fraction washed. Plants preparing metallurgical coal are uniformly 3 circuit plants with a coarse heavy media circuit for +13 mm, jigs for the 13 mm x 0.5 mm and flotation of the fines. US principles of unit process efficiency, alternative equipment for fines washing and intensive mechanical dewatering have been introduced, well-received and are increasing in application. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Advances in the Development of Coal Spiral Technology:</B><BR>
<I>B. Weldon, Mineral Technologies, Bundall, QLD, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
The use of spiral separators for the washing of coal in the size range 2 x 0.1mm is now a well established practice throughout the world. Notwithstanding this almost universal acceptance of spiral technology for coal fines beneficiation and through use, some short comings in these processing units have been identified. A number of these shortcomings have been addressed in recently-developed hardware. Both laboratory and in-plant test data on new spiral models incorporating features to improve the performance of coal spirals are presented and compared with the performance of previous spiral models. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

