<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Issues in Coal Utilization
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, C110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. Luttrell, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Coal Resources, Coal Quality, Coal Reserves, and Interregional Competition for Utility Markets-Key Elements of the National Coal Resources Assessment:</B><BR>
<I>R. C. Milici, US Geological Survey, Reston, VA</I></FONT><BR>
US coal reserves are a small part of a great natural resource endowment. At present, depletion and environmental concerns have shifted much of the remaining reserves to the west and have enhanced the competitiveness of western coals in utility markets. Topics under consideration by the USGS are: 1. Rate of production from major coal fields in the US during the next several decades. 2. The effects of coal quality and environmental regulation on coal reserves. 3. Depletion of eastern coal reserves and the future sources of energy needed to supply the nation's ongoing need for electric power generation. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Water Quality Effects of Fly Ash/Coal Refuse Blending:</B><BR>
<I>W. L. Daniels and B. R. Steward, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
This paper reports five years of laboratory and field data on water quality effects of fly ash/coal refuse blends. When alkaline fly ash is blended with acidic refuse at rates that maintain a net alkaline balance over time, water quality effects are generally positive. However, when non-alkaline ash is utilized, or when the ash/refuse mix is net acidic, the blends acidify and heavy metals are preferentially stripped from the fly ash matrix, seriously degrading water quality, at least locally within the fill. This acidification process may be time-lagged for years after placement, but can be predicted. Refuse pile design options for ash co-disposal are discussed. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Issues Impacting Coal Ash Utilization:</B><BR>
<I>L. Larrimore, Southern Company Services, Birmingham, AL and D. Dodgen, Southern Company Services, Atlanta, GA</I></FONT><BR>
Electric utilities depend heavily on coal as a major fuel source for power generation, annually producing approximately 75 million tons of ash as a by-product. Utilities and others who burn coal have traditionally disposed of these materials in ponds or landfills. However, in the last 10-15 years there has been a greatly increased emphasis on beneficial utilization of coal ash by the producers themselves as well as by customers who purchase the materials. This document examines the regulatory, cost, and technical performance issues which currently impact the use of coal ash for various applications. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Upgrading Gasifier Slag:</B><BR>
<I>M. S. Klima, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA and V. Choudhry, Praxis Engineers, Inc., Milpitas, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Table concentration was used to process nominal -3.4 mm gasifier slag (~85% ash) to separate high (~100%) ash slag from low (~50%) ash char. The results indicated a nearly ideal separation of the slag from the char for sizes coarser than about 1 mm. An overall slag yield of 71% was obtained. The slag was sufficiently clean to be used as feed material for the production of expanded lightweight aggregate. Size separation could be used to reduce the ash content of the char product to under 35%. The upgraded char could then be combined with raw coal to be used as fuel. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

