<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Research and Development
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, C112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>H. K. Sacks, US Dept. of Energy, Pittsburgh, PA
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Assessing Roof and Rib Hazard in the Underground Stone Industry:</B><BR>
<I>A. T. Iannacchione and L. J. Prosser, US Dept. of Energy, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Currently, 96 underground stone mines are in operation with several more in the proposed or planning stage. The production from underground stone mines has increased 32% from 1991 to 1994, reaching a total of 6 metric tons. Unfortunately, from 1991 through 1995, 44 miners were fatally injured in the stone industry with 11 occurring at underground mines and from a workforce of less than 2,000 miners. Nine of these 11 miners were fatally injured in falls of roof or rib. Clearly, a safer environment for the miners can be achieved by better control of hazardous ground. To help characterize the types of ground control hazards experienced in the stone industry, information related to accidents within the industry since 1978 was collected and analyzed. Also, 24 mines visited in Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Maryland, Kentucky, and Indiana were used to assess ground conditions in underground stone mines. In general, ground failures could be classified as those occurring near-surface and initiated by solution (water) processes or those occurring under moderate overburden and initiated by geologic structures and stress concentrations. This paper will overview the factors which effect ground control and provide several examples of assessment efforts aimed at improving miner safety. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Use of Tomography in Mining:</B><BR>
<I>D. F. Scott and T. J. Williams, Spokane Research Center, Spokane, WA and M. J. Friedel, Lakeville, MN</I></FONT><BR>
Seismic tomography can be a valuable tool for mine planning and can increase miner safety. It is a time-efficient, relatively inexpensive, and reliable method of determining relative stress in deep underground (<1220m) pillars. If high-stress areas are detected, these areas can be destressed prior to development or avoided. High-stress areas can be monitored with successive seismic surveys to determine if stress decreases to the point where development can be initiated safely. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Cribless Tailgate in the Pittsburgh #8 Coal Seam Employing Cable Trusses: </B><BR>
<I>J. G. Oldsen, J. C. Stankus and S. Guo, Jennmar Corp., Pittsburgh, PA and A. W. Khair, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
During the last several years, implementation of trusses, in lieu of wood cribs, has been successful for supplemental tailgate support in the Pittsburgh seam. This paper reviews the truss support system provided by the new high strength 0.6" tensioned cable truss, which is now also being used in cribless tailgates. Cable loading and roof deformation were monitored, as well as panel and pillar stress loading, to evaluate roof and floor performance. The test results indicate that the cable truss system successfully controlled the roof and floor during first and second panel extraction. This paper will describe the advantages of cable trusses and their load transfer mechanism as well as mine evaluation. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Ignition of Methane and Coal Dust by Air Compression-The Experimental Proof: </B><BR>
<I>W. Lin and M. J. McPherson, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
When a large area of open gob collapses suddenly, a windblast is produced that can cause considerable damage throughout the infrastructure of a mine. In a few cases, the windblast has been accompanied by ignitions of methane and/or coal dust. Earlier in this project, analytical and numerical analyses investigated the transient behavior of the air through the small time period during which the roof is falling. This is sufficiently short to allow adiabatic compression of the air, i.e. negligible heat transfer to rock surfaces. Controlled escape of the air interconnecting entries limits the build-up of air pressure. However, this same phenomen causes the potential energy of the falling strata to be concentrated into a diminishing mass of air. Computer simulations predicted that the temperature of the air would increase rapidly as the roof descends, reaching values that are capable of igniting either methane or coal dust. This paper concentrates on a series of laboratory test involving the compression of mixtures of air, methane and coal dust under a falling weight and while allowing controlled escape of the mixture. The transient responses on pressure and temperature sensors were recorded. In addition to an analysis of those records, the paper highlights those conditions in which ignitions occurred. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Electrical Fault Detection on Downed DC Trolley Lines: </B><BR>
<I>J. S. Peterson, G. P. Cole and M. R. Yenchek, US Dept. of Energy, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
The US Bureau of Mines (now part of the Department of Energy) has conducted research to improve electrical fault detection on coal mine dc trolley systems. Tests were conducted at cooperating mines to assist in developing a neural network-based detection algorithm for distinguishing between electrical faults and normal operation of the trolley system. Rectifier current measurements were taken during normal loading, during induced faults, and during transitions between them for data to train the neural network. During field tests, when the trained neural network detects an electrical fault it provides an indication signal to the user. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Laboratory Assessment of Rock Fragmentation Process by Continuous Miners: </B><BR>
<I>V. B. Achanti and A. W. Khair, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
Laboratory studies were carried out at West Virginia University to investigate the rock fragmentation mechanism by continuous miners using an automated rotary cutting simulator. The primary factors influencing the fragmentation process were found to be: bit spacing, bit geometry, depth of cut, type of rock, and attack angle. This paper presents a quantitative relationship among these parameters to achieve optimum energy consumption and minimize dust generation during rock fragmentation process. Three bits were used simultaneously on Indiana limestone while the bit geometry, namely, bit tip angle and bit tip size were varied. Bit spacing was varied from 2.5 cm (1 in.) to 7.5 cm (3 in.) while the cutting process was assessed for varying cutting depths. Triaxial tests were also conducted to correlate the failure angle of the rock during cutting. Assessment of these parameters has led to a better understanding of the cutting mechanism by continuous miners in terms of energy consumption and dust generation. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Protection of Pipelines Affected by Surface Subsidence: </B><BR>
<I>Y. Luo, S. S. Peng and H. J. Chen, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
Surface subsidence often has potential to cause problems to buried pipelines which differ largely in their services, materials, sizes, joints and burying conditions. This paper presents the methods for assessing the subsidence influences on pipelines. The basic steps are: (1) prediction of dynamic and final surface movements and deformations along the pipelines, (2) identification of the weaknesses of the pipeline structures and the major contributors to the problems, (3) assessment of severity of the problems. If necessary, proper mitigation measures will be designed to maintain the safe operation of the pipelines during and after subsidence process. A number of field cases of protecting pipelines are also presented. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

