<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
The Outlook for Industrial Minerals I
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, C108

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. M. Elzea Kogel, Thiele Kaolin Co., Sandersville, GA
<DD>A. F. Alsobrook, Alsobrook & Co., Inc., Medford, NJ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Industrial Minerals in the 21st Century: A Perspective of Trends in Markets, Technologies and Applications: </B><BR>
<I>C. C. Harvey, Indiana University, Bloomington, IN and A. F. Alsobrook, Alsobrook & Co., Medford, NJ</I></FONT><BR>
As we move towards the 21st Century, there are several factors which influence the markets and processing technologies for industrial minerals. Traditional markets for industrial minerals in the developed world are frequently stagnant or decreasing because of their maturity or due to environmental factors such as reclamation, recovery of byproducts and recycling. Some industrial minerals are greatly affected by these factors, while others are either immune or have adapted successfully to meet these challenges. In the developing countries of the world, there is rapid market growth and resource exploitation. The future of specific mineral commodities in these environments will be discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Outlook for Graphite and Graphite Technology: </B><BR>
<I>G. P. Hand, Superior Graphite Co., Chicago, IL</I></FONT><BR>
The graphite industry as a whole has gone through many changes over the years. Most of the graphite used in major applications since the turn of the century were basic natural or electrode by-product synthetic materials, processed using simple crushing, screening, or grinding techniques. In the mid 1970's new thermal technology was developed which changed the face of the graphite industry, and opened up a panacea of new products and capabilities. Materials produced through this new technology have helped revolutionize new products and processes in industries including automotive, batteries, fuel cells, electronics, iron, lubricants and steel. This paper outlines the continued improvements in those industries as well as the outlook for new technology in this rapidly changing area. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Vermiculite - Outlook 1997: </B><BR>
<I>E. M. Moeller, W. R. Grace & Co., Greer, SC</I></FONT><BR>
Review of worldwide vermiculite production and markets with particular emphasis on recent technologic advances.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Bentonite Technologies and their Potential Markets: </B><BR>
<I>C. R. Landis, F. J. Reisch, and C. E. Davis, American Colloid Co., Arlington Heights, IL</I></FONT><BR>
In recent years, emerging bentonite technology is exposing this versatile ore into new product markets, as well as, more efficient exploration and development. These opportunities require familiar performance attributes, but within the context of the specific new application. For example, high viscosity, Na-montmorillonite-based bentonite products improve gel stability of ceramic body compositions. In other cases optimization of surface modification convert non-swelling clays into swelling clays capable of broader market use. Organic-based surface modifications offer viscosity enhancements of an order of magnitude with only a factor of two or three increases of solids such as cosmetic, consumer, and environment markets. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Ball Clay Developments in the Americas: </B><BR>
<I>T. Deems, S. Leese, J. Larimore and T. Vincent, United Clays, Inc., Brentwood, TN</I></FONT><BR>
Increases in consumption of ball clay in Central and South America as well as North America initiate a review of major deposit locations, technical properties and access to imported clays. The review will include the nature and quality of deposits and market requirements. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Barite: World Sources and the US Market: </B><BR>
<I>S. D. Bearden, New Riverside Ochre Co., Inc., Cartersville, GA</I></FONT><BR>
The world's reserve base is adequate for at least 100 years at the current consumption rate. China, United States, and India are expected to remain the leading barite producing countries. The United States will continue to be the largest consumer of ore in all end use categories. None of the known substitutes for barium sulfate are expected to impact existing applications. World production for the past decade is near five million tons per year. This is about 50% of the projected capacity. The US consumed 1.6 million tons of barite in 1995, which is approximately 40% of the record year high of 4.3 million tons set in 1981. Consumption is directly proportional to hydrocarbon well installation activity as about 90% of all barite end use is in drilling fluid additives. Imports are expected to continue to supply more than half of the US requirements. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

