<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
The Outlook for Industrial Minerals II
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:00 AM, A109/111

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. M. Elzea Kogel, Thiele Kaolin Co., Sandersville, GA
<DD>A. F. Alsobrook, Alsobrook & Co., Inc., Medford, NJ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Lime: An Industry Poised for Growth:</B><BR>
<I>D. H. Stowe, Dravo Lime Co., Pittsburgh, PA,  W. S. Blakefield, Dravo Lime Co., Butler, KY and R. C. Forsythe, Dravo Lime Co., Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
For the past 6000 years lime usage has continued to broaden with today's worldwide consumption estimated at 140 million metric tons. It is fair to say that lime in one form or another was utilized to produce products consumed by virtually every person in attendance at this conference. On a very broad scale, lime utilization from country to country correlates with two major factors: population and Gross National Product. This paper will explore those growth opportunities and discuss the factors which significantly influence lime consumption.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Outlook for Cement Raw Materials:</B><BR>
<I>S. A. Regis, Arizona Portland Cement Co., Rillito, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Cement raw material demand is affected, not only by cement demand, but also by environmental regulations, technological changes in cement manufacturing, and cement market demands. The utilization of recyclable industrial by products as a substitute for mined materials is a trend that will continue, albeit at the whim of new regulations. Concrete market trends such as the recent awareness of Alkali-Silicate Reactivity or high early strength requirements also cause manufacturers to search for new raw materials. Finally, modern cement plants are more sensitive to raw mix variability and the effects of trace elements than older facilities and the analysis of raw material supplies is much more sophisticated. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Outlook for Refractory Raw Materials in North America:</B><BR>
<I>C. J. Kessler and J. L. Cunningham, Harbison-Walker Refractories Co., Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Specific trends in raw materials critical to the future of the refractories industry begins with a demand base of current materials, product-segmented, and projections of the future "mainstays" and newer, emerging materials required to maintain tomorrow's cost-effective products. Supply sources and impact of future materials, parameters of good supply, and specific trends in the refractories industry driving materials outlook are presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Advances in Acid-activated Clays:</B><BR>
<I>T. Dombrowski, Engelhard Corp., Gordon, GA and J. Henderson, Engelhard Corp., Beachwood, OH</I></FONT><BR>
Acid-activated montmorillonite is used worldwide as a catalyst and as a sorbent for the enhancement and purification products as well as vegetable and animal-based facts. The solid-acid character of the activated montmorillonite is imparted by the manufacturing process, giving it unique properties that are exploited in these industries. Several international companies and a multitude of local clay producers are focusing on improving the efficiency of their standard and specialized products. This paper will describe the use of acid-activated montmorillonite in traditional sorbent applications, as a solid acid catalyst, and other new uses. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Magnesia, Moving Beyond Refractories:</B><BR>
<I>M. L. T. Maniocha, Martin Marietta Magnesia Specialties, Baltimore, MD</I></FONT><BR>
Most magnesia, whether of natural or synthetic origin, is utilized in its dead burned or periclase form as refractory linings for the production of steel. Continued research in refractory science combined with good refractory maintenance and improvements in steel making practice have resulted in decreasing use of magnesia. To make up for this loss of business producers of synthetic magnesia have started to manufacture a variety of magnesium based chemicals that are utilized in many diverse industries and applications. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

