<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Quality in Industrial Minerals: From ISO 9000 to TQM and Other Systems
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:00 AM, C108

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>D. A. Holmes, Pincock, Allen & Holt, Lakewood, CO
<DD>G. Chlumsky, Pincock, Allen & Holt, Lakewood, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Kaolin Company's Journey to ISO 9002 Certification: </B><BR>
<I>L. A. Arrington-Webb and E. Loyd, Thiele Kaolin Co., Sandersville, GA</I></FONT><BR>
The International Standards Organization (ISO) 9000 series of quality standards was published in 1987. First initiated by the British in the mid-1970's to assure the quality of British goods and services, ISO 9000 certification demonstrates the capability of a supplier to meet the requirements of the customer. Thiele Kaolin Company has invested considerable time and money achieving and maintaining ISO 9002 certification. Through a regimen of process control and documentation, routine audits, and a commitment to quality management, this kaolin producer continues to be a competitive pigment supplier in a world-wide market. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Quality Control Practices in the US Bentonite Industry: </B><BR>
<I>R. K. Brown, WYO-BEN, Inc., Billings, MT</I></FONT><BR>
The quality of finished bentonite products is heavily influenced by the physio-chemical characteristics of the base clay itself. Knowledge of these properties is critical if the correct clay is to be chosen for each product type. Laboratory testing of clay samples during exploration, pit development, mining and processing ensures that clay quality remains consistently appropriate for the requirements of each product. Plant processing of the clay is limited to drying, sizing, and in some case incorporation of chemical additives to modify the properties of the clay. Drying and sizing are monitored on a continuous basis using statistical process control (SPC) methods. The affect of additive addition is monitored by laboratory testing of finished product. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Total Quality and the ISO Quality Standard-SMI's Approach: </B><BR>
<I>W. M. Conboy, Specialty Minerals Inc., Gulliver, MI</I></FONT><BR>
The ISO 9000 series quality standards have their roots in the quality control systems which preceded the move to quality assurance through Total Quality Management. Specialty Minerals has moved past the initial resistance to ISO as a "necessary evil" and come to recognize the quality standard as system which strongly supports their Total Quality effort (aka Minerals Total Quality). This presentation will detail the elements of the ISO standard which support and promote Total Quality (as experienced by one mining/mineral processing company). 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Between a Rock and a Hard Place: ISO 14000 and the Mining Industry: </B><BR>
<I>P. Nazaryk and H. Ilenda, Harding Lawson Assoc., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
ISO 14000 is a series of voluntary international environmental standards. These standards describe how a corporation should manage its environmental affairs. Some experts predict that ISO 14000 will have the same impact on corporate environmental management that ISO 9000 has had on corporate quality management programs. This paper will discuss ISO 14000 and the future of ISO 14000 in the mining industry. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Clay: Measuring up to ISO 9000: </B><BR>
<I>M. G. Leidich, Robinson Brick Co., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
As our customers demand quality in all aspects of the brick manufacturing process, the Robinson Brick Company has chosen to become ISO 9001 certified. This process will extend to the performance verification of the clays where we have developed testing programs that address the numerous physical properties of the clays. The reporting of those results wil greatly improve manufacturing's confidence that the end product will meet Robinson's rigid quality standards. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

