<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Fillers and Extenders
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, C108

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>T. S. Harris, Kline & Co., Fairfield, NJ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Capim River Kaolins, Para, Brazil:</B><BR>
<I>C. A. Alves, DOCEGEO, Belem, Para, Brazil and H. H. Murray, Indiana University, Bloomington, IN</I></FONT><BR>
The kaolin district along the Capim River in Para in northern Brazil contains reserves of more than 500,000,000 metric tons. These deposits are in the Ipixuna Formation of Tertiary age and are exceptionally pure. The major mineral is kaolinite along with quartz and minor quantities of anatase, zircon, and tourmaline. The particle size ranges between 60 and 90 percent greater than 2 microns and the crude ore brightness percentages are between 80 and 87. The processed products for paper coating are 89 ISO to 91 ISO and the Brookfield viscosity is less than 200 centipoise. These Capim River kaolins will be the dominant source of high quality paper coating kaolins in the 21st century. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Comparison of fine and Coarse Commercial Kaolin Deposits from Georgia, USA and Brazil:</B><BR>
<I>S. M. Pickering Jr., Industrial Mineral Serlvices Inc., Macon, GA and M. A. Linkous, US Borax Inc., Raleigh, NC</I></FONT><BR>
Commercial quality kaolins occur in fluvial sediments in both central-eastern Georgia and in the eastern Amazon River area. Distinctive coarse and fine particle size kaolin deposits are present in both areas; they have many remarkable similarities for mineral deposits occurring at such wide geographic separation. Industrial, mineralogical, crystalline, and chemical resemblance of the coarse and fine kaolin deposits from the two areas will be described in detail. Knowledge of similarities of the Brazilian clays to those which have dominated world production in Georgia will help to develop superior quality kaolin products for world use in paper, paint, plastic, ceramic, and other applications. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Functional Fillers for Plastics-Outlook Beyond the Year 2000:</B><BR>
<I>C. H. Eckert, Kline & Co., Fairfield, NJ</I></FONT><BR>
Industrial minerals are utilized as additives in dozens of industries including paint, paper, adhesives, and rubber. However, of all of their additive applications, plastics represents the highest in value with current mineral prices averaging twice those for all other filler applications. In 1995, an estimated 1.8 million tons of minerals were consumed in the US plastics industry. The outlook for demand is very encouraging, in some applications, growth in demand will exceed 10% per year. This paper will focus on the performance benefits of specific mineral additives in various polymer systems, key trends impacting demand, and provide insights on emerging applications. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mica-A Unique Mineral for Emerging Markets:</B><BR>
<I>R. C. Freas, Franklin Industrial Minerals, Nashville, TN and J. Barton and L. Canova, Franklin Industrial Minerals, Kings Mountain, NC</I></FONT><BR>
The physical and chemical properties of mica are unique relative to most other industrial minerals. As such, mica is suitable for a variety of functional applications in new and emerging markets. This paper examines some of these applications and particularly the contribution mica makes in end product performance. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

