<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Toxicity of Minerals - Current Trends in Understanding and Regulation 
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, C108

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>W. Moll, Oil-Dri Corp. of America, Vernon Hills, IL
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Crystalline Silica-Health and Regulatory Aspects: </B><BR>
<I>R. E. Glenn, National Industrial Sand Assoc., Calverton, MD</I></FONT><BR>
The health affects on the lung from the inhalation of crystalline silica will be reviewed. The listing by the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) of crystalline silica triggered numerous regulatory requirements at the federal and state level. IARC will reconsider the carcinogenicity of crystalline silica in October 1996. The preliminary findings of the reconsideration and possible impact, if any, will be discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Geology of Silica and its Significance in Crystalline Silica Regulation: Part 1: </B><BR>
<I>S. G. Ampian, Ampian & Assoc., Mount Airy, MD and M. L. Raymond, Ralston Purina, St Louis, MO</I></FONT><BR>
This paper is the first in a series to help regulators better understand the natural occurrence of silica to avoid over-regulation. Photomicrographs of typical rock thin-sections are used to illustrate the differences between single crystal, cryptocrystalline, glassy, and amorphous silicas continually encountered down-stream. The petrographic differences between the crystalline silicas, largely ignored, are used to both correlate and critically examine the mineralogy of the epidemiological and biological evidence routinely cited justifying regulation. The regulators almost total reliance on X-ray diffractometry for quantifying crystalline silica is questioned because its resulting total crystalline silica analysis is incapable of distinguishing between the crystalline silica varieties commonly encountered in many bulk and monitor samples. Examples of quartz and cristobalite over-regulation are discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Quantitative Measurement of Crystalline Silica: </B><BR>
<I>W. J. Miles, Bentonite Corp., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Current worker right to know regulations have created the need to analyze many industrial products for crystalline silica polymorphs at a threshold of 0.1% and determine the concentration of each for identification of health risks and compliance with government regulations. X-ray diffraction is the preferred analytical method for identification of the polymorphs, quartz, cristobalite and tridymite, and for quantification of these mineral species. However, quantification at the 0.1% threshold is extremely difficult or impossible with complex mineral and chemical systems typically found in industrial products. Concentration techniques for the crystalline silica polymorphs are required to enhance sensitivity of X-ray diffraction for both identification and quantification of initial concentration.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Measure and Mismeasure of Opal: </B><BR>
<I>W. F. Moll, Oil-Dri Corp., Vernon Hills, IL</I></FONT><BR>
Misidentification of opal as cristobalite can have regulatory consequences. Opal is a non-crystalline form of hydrated silica whereas cristobalite is a crystalline and regulated. The X-ray diffraction effects for opal bear some similarity to the diffraction pattern of cristobalite, and is the source of the confusion. These effects are not Bragg reflections arising from long-range order but arise from different sources. Methods of differentiating between opal and cristobalite include careful examination of the diffraction effects, acid dissolution, and effects of heating. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Good Science and Regulation-An Indispensable Pair: </B><BR>
<I>C. S. Thompson, Norwalk, CT</I></FONT><BR>
A simple incorrect mineralogical definition caused untold hardship to a company and could have destroyed a major segment of the mining industry. Usually such an affected industry reluctantly accepts such a decision, regardless of its scientific validity. In a major case, the particular industry challenged the decision, and promoted good and correct science by enlisting the help of scientists in academia, government and industry. Eventually, the regulatory groups altered their position, and ensured not only the viability of the industry but also public health and safety. Professional organizations have a duty to address regulatory actions and through cooperative efforts with all concerned, ensure that good science prevails. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

