<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Recent Developments in Industrial Minerals
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, C108

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>K. Santini, Santini & Assoc., Lakewood, CO
<DD>M. Gallagher, Industrial Minerals, New York, NY
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>ISK Wollastonite-Strategic Development of a High Grade Deposit: </B><BR>
<I>B. A. Slim, MineStart Management Inc., N. Vancouver, BC, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
Investigations, by Super Twins Resources Ltd, of high-grade wollastonite in the Coast Mountains of north-west British Columbia show raw grades of 80% purity yielding 95% concentrates with aspect ratios of 20:1. The mountain location, at 1500 m elevation in the undeveloped Iskut region with low cloud and short summer season will impose constraints on bulk shipping and operations. A 100 mm, HDPE pipeline is being investigated to transport a raw wollastonite slurry either to the Strikine River for barging or for trucking on the proposed road extension joining the nearby Snip Gold mine to Eskay Creek. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Breakthrough Technology May Revolutionize the Soda Ash Industry: </B><BR>
<I>J. S. Wold, Wold Trona Co., Inc., Casper, WY</I></FONT><BR>
Wold Trona Co., Inc. (WTCI) of Casper, WY is building the sixth mine and soda ash plant in the Green River Basin of Wyoming. Patented technology developed for Wold by Hazen Research, Denver, permits the production of Benetron (dry beneficiated trona 98% Na2 Co3) and Benetron Plus (99.5+% Na1 CO3) at 1/3 the capital investment and 1/2 the operating cost of the five monohydrate plants in Green River which produce 1/3 of the world's soda ash. WTCI's trona resources are the largest in the basin giving an unparalleled opportunity to become an international leader in the soda ash industry. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>U.S. Zeolites, An Emerging Company: </B><BR>
<I>T. R. van Fleet, US Zeolite, Inc., Golden, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Nearly 10 years ago, four retired mining executives formed a company to develop and commercialize a natural zeolite resource, Clinoptilolite, on the Union Pacific land grant in Sweetwater County, Wyoming. The struggle to develop markets and raise investment capital over the years has been an interesting and frustrating story. Like most Industrial Minerals projects, the success of failure lies in your ability to develop markets and locate funding. This paper will discuss our many adventures, failures, and hopefully success in developing a zeolite business. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development of Calcium Borate Production: </B><BR>
<I>G. J. Hartman, Fort Cady Minerals Corp., Newberry Springs, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Fort Cady Minerals began borate production by in situ leaching techniques in 1981 and is now marketing Cadycal 100, a calcium borate product. Mine production in by in situ leaching of a deep seated colemanite deposit using dilute acid. After the rich boric acid solution is pumped to the surface, the solution is purified then calcium borate product is precipitated. The resulting product is then dried and sold to ceramic and fiberglass manufacturers. This paper discusses the recent activity and future plans. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mining and Processing Ca-Feldspar at the Industrial Mineral Fillers, LLC's CASPAR Mine: </B><BR>
<I>J. C. Heter, Industrial Mineral Fillers, LLC, Canyon Country, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Industrial Mineral Fillers, LLC is in the initial stages of mining and processing Anorthosite (CASPAR) at its Caspar mine located in Soledad Canyon, Los Angeles County, California. The CASPAR it being mined from the Precambrian San Gabriel Anorthosite Complex of the western San Gabriel Mountains. Preliminary results suggest that CASPAR is a desirable alternative to silica sand used in construction applications, such as stucco, grout, abrasives and other uses including filtration and golf course recreation sands. With the use of standard ore dressing techniques, CASPAR is suitable for use as a filler in paint, plastics and rubber. Environmentally, CASPAR has advantages over silica sand, in that, there is no detectable Free Silica.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mexico's Fledspar Markets through the Year 2000: </B><BR>
<I>E. R. Berlanga and M. Garza, Vitro Quimica y Empaghes, Monterrey, Neon Leon, Mexico</I></FONT><BR>
This paper examines Mexico's feldspar industry and it's related consumer sectors, glass and ceramics. The feldspar industry has changed during the last 10 years into a more concentrated one. Moreover, glass has taken a second place as compared to ceramics, a fast growing sector. Mexico's economic situation is now turning to positive growth after the crisis brought about the by the peso devaluation in December 1994. It is expected that a significant growth in the demand for feldspar by the year 2,000 will occur, triggered by ceramics and construction sectors. Companies in these sectors are highly competitive in the U.S. market and have been expanding their capacity in spite of the economic crisis. Container producers are the main consumers in the glass market due to the slow down in consumption of aluminum and plastics containers in which prices went shoulder to shoulder with the US dollar exchange rate, glass consumption is expected to have a moderate growth through the year 2,000.

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

