<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Access to Mineral Lands
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, C108

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>F. Heivilin, Oil-Dri Corp., of America, Ochlocknee, GA
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Access to Reserves on Fee Lands: </B><BR>
<I>F. Heivilin, Oil-Dri Corp. of America, Ochlocknee, GA</I></FONT><BR>
An option for or the lease, mineral deed, or warranty are no longer the sole key to gain or maintain access to mineral reserves on fee lands. You need a plan which has a reasonable chance of success to handle all present or future local, state, or federal laws. Your neighbors, the perception of the community, a complete mine plan, and potential liability are all part of the plan. Examples from New Jersey, Florida, Georgia, Alabama and Mississippi.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Update on the 1872 Mining Law: </B><BR>
<I>S. Dempsey, Royal Gold, Inc., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Perhaps more than ever before, pressure to reform the 1872 Mining Law has created an environment of uncertainty for miners. Contrary to popular reports, the mining industry supports reform, and has played a significant role in Congressional reform efforts. Since its passage in 1872, the Mining Law has been modified on numerous occasions to meet the changing needs of America's society and economy. Despite evolution, the Mining Law continues to be criticized as outdated. Although all sides of the issue have shown support for reasonable reform legislation, these interests have been unable to reach agreement on specific provisions of proposed reform legislation. The debate has focused on such issues as the size and type of royalties to be paid to the government, payment of fair market value for lands, claim maintenance fees, and abandoned mine cleanup programs. Although in last year's Budget Reconciliation Bill, Congress passed comprehensive reform legislation for the first time ever, the Bill was vetoed by President Clinton. In the absence of effective reform measures, some innovative approaches have been used to prevent mining operations on the public lands. These include everything from the use of environmental laws to delay or prevent operations, to inflammatory rhetoric by the Secretary of the Interior directed at mining companies complying with the law, to presidential withdrawals of mineral lands. This paper will address in more detail the current state of the Mining Law, and likely proposals for change. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Patenting of Industrial Minerals: </B><BR>
<I>J. R. Evans, Bureau of Land Management, Sacramento, CA</I></FONT><BR>
In order to patent an industrial mineral placer mining claim, it must incorporate an economic deposit. Each ten acre parcel is evaluated for its mineral-in- character nature. Nonmineral-in-character parcels cannot be patented. Economic concerns include: claim location, dummy locators, common variety nature, "excess reserves," and environmental constraints. Also, geologic and mineralogic studies, sampling and testing procedures are vital. Mining, milling, processing costs, and taxes must be evaluated. Product marketability analysis is necessary before starting any cash flow or discounted cash flow study. Valid data is essential to evaluate an economic industrial mineral deposit. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Access to Mineral Lands in the Western United States: </B><BR>
<I>D. H. Sherwood, Parcel, Mauro, Hultin & Spaanstra, PC, Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Government agencies managing public lands are limiting mineral exploration. Land is being closed to mining, and even where exploration can still be done, there is no longer much certainty that one can mine what might be found. The government in some cases argues that what has been found cannot be mined economically, and in others that too much has been found. Courts, which once zealously protected private claims to the public domain, now favor the land managers and those who on general principle oppose mining. Furthermore, recent events in Congress suggest that the end is near, especially for industrial minerals. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Access to Crushed Stone-The East and Front Ranges: </B><BR>
<I>J. Hayden, National Stone Association, Washington, DC</I></FONT><BR>
It is becoming increasingly difficult to secure local aggregate resources that meet quality standards and local restrictions without conflicts with other land uses and environmental regulations. The successful integration of natural-resource information into land-use decisions is increasingly difficult as the needs for land and resources become more numerous, complex, and urgent. Well-reasoned decisions about land-use are critical to the National interest if Infrastructure resouces are to remain economically available. Provisions for uninterrupted future supplies of aggregate should be made using proper long-range planning that incorporate a multiple land-use program. That program would inlcude identification and protection of natural resources, strategies that will permit development of resources in relation to future market needs and environmental considerations, and a beneficial use of mined-out areas. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

