<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geochemistry-Magmatic Components of Hydrothermal Systems
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, C109

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. S. Cline, University of Nevada, Las Vegas, NV
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Fluid Inclusion Evidence for a Magmatic Source for Metals in Hydrothermal Systems: </B><BR>
<I>R. J. Bodnar, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
Fluid inclusions provide one of the most direct means of determining the source(s) of components in hydrothermal ore deposits. Results of synchrotron XRF analyses of individual fluid inclusions from various paragenetic stages in porphyry copper deposits show clearly that many metals of interest (Cu, Fe, Pb, Zn) are sourced in the magma and are introduced into the hydrothermal system when aqueous fluids exsolve from the crystallizing magma. The results also indicate that volatile elements such as As, Hg, T1 as well as Au, Ag and some Cu are partitioned into the vapor phase and transported into the near-surface where precipitation and mineralization occurs. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Are Mafic Alkaline Rocks Needed to Make a Good Porphyry System?: </B><BR>
<I>J. D. Keith, D. T. Maughan, K. A. Waite and D. H. Tomlinson, Brigham Young University, Provo, UT</I></FONT><BR>
Large porphyry molybdenum and porphyry copper systems often contain small amounts of mafic alkaline rocks that occur as late mineralized dikes. Petrogenesis of latitic rocks from the Bingham Canyon porphyry copper system indicates that ore-related magma contained more than ten percent intermixed mafic alkaline magma. Mafic alkaline magma is often oxidized and much more sulfur-, metal- and water-rich than the intermediate or silicic magma that crystallizes adjacent to the ore. Should we assume that the silicic magma is more critical to ore formation than the underplated mafic magma because it is more proximal?</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Magmatic Contributions to a Mineralized Geothermal System, Valles Caldera, New Mexico: </B><BR>
<I>F. E. Goff and J. N. Gardner, Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, NM</I></FONT><BR>
The 1.2 Myr Valles caldera is the "type" resurgent caldera and post-caldera eruptions are as young as 60 kyr. Within the caldera, a 200-300C hydrothermal system circulates mostly in intracaldera tuff and tuffaceous sedimentary rocks. Isotope results show the fluids are dominated by meteoric water. Epithermal mineralization (propylitic and phyllic alteration) characterizes the reservoir rocks and sub-ore grade molybdenite is the major ore mineral found to date. The only component of obvious magmatic/mantle origin is anomalous 3He although it is possible that magma still contributes some C, S, Cl, and water to the system.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Why Small Porphyry Intrusions Can Host Big Ore Deposits: </B><BR>
<I>J. B. Lowenstern, US Geological Survey, Menlo Park, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Recent work suggests that Climax-type Mo deposits form from relatively normal granitic magmas, rather than from extraordinarily trace-element enriched melts. This requires that the large tonnages of ore are not derived solely from the small associated intrusions. Instead, cupolas serve partly as conduits for degassing of large, subjacent magma reservoirs. One important mode for degassing may be convective magmatic flow, whereby magma rises, degasses at the top of the cupola, and then descends back down through the center of the conduit. Advection through bubble-rich magmatic foam may be a critical aspect of degassing at the magma/wallrock interface. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Gold Degassing and Deposition, Galeras Volcano, Colombia: </B><BR>
<I>F. E. Goff, Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, NM and J. A. Stimac, Union Geothermal Co., Santa Rosa, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Galeras is a composite, andesitic stratovolcano that has formed during the last 0.7 Myr and has erupted frequently in the last few years. Magmatic fluids (360C in early 1993) contained significant Co2, So2, H2S, and HCl, plus ~0.04 ppm Au. Altered andesite breccia on the cone contains alunite, anhydrite, quartz, pyrite and ~2 ppm Au. Older veins within the edifice contain ores with visible electrum and sulfosalts. The hydrothermal environment surrounding the magma conduit is "high sulfidation". Assuming constant SO2 flux of 500 t/d, Galeras can emit ~0.5 kg/d Au during short-lived eruptive events. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Descriptive Exploration Model for Porphyry Gold Deposits: </B><BR>
<I>An Update from the Maricunga Belt, Northern Chile: J. L. Muntean, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Maricunga porphyry gold deposits (~25-300 MT), occur in Miocene subvolcanic andesitic to dacitic intrusive centers. Pervasive propylitic alteration and banded, epithermal-like quartz veinlets that occupy radial and concentric fractures predominate at the Verde deposit at Refugio. Along a 300m vertical exposure at the Pancho deposit at Refugio, porphyry Cu-type veinlets and pervasive potassic alteration predominate at the lowest levels and are cut by banded veinlets that predominate at higher levels. The banded veinlets are cut by quartz-alunite ledges at the highest levels. At the Cavancha deposit at La Pepa, quartz veinlets and pervasive potassic alteration are cut by pyrite veins with sericitic envelopes which may be feeders to quartz-alunite-enargite-barite ledges (locally >100g/t Au) that are within 100m of Cavancha. At all of the deposits, both the porphyry Cu-type and banded quartz veinlets cut and are cut by the intrusions suggesting a genetic relationship between mineralization and intrusive activity. Zones of abundant banded veinlets generally contain 0.5-2g/t Au and <0.1% Cu (hypogene), whereas zones of abundant porphyry Cu-type veinlets contain mostly <1g/t Au and 0.1-0.4% Cu (hypogene).</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Carlin-type Gold Deposits-Products of Magmatism?: </B><BR>
<I>J. S. Cline, University of Nevada, Las Vegas, NV and A. H. Hofstra, R. O. Rye, and G. P. Landis, US Geological Survey, Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Although gold production from Carlin-type deposits has made Nevada one of the world's leading gold producers, the geologic processes that generated these systems are poorly understood. To address questions concerning the source and evolution of ore fluids, the chemical and isotopic composition of fluid inclusions from the Getchell gold deposit have been examined. Microthermometric measurements and quadrupole mass spectrometer gas analyses show that ore stage fluids are H2O-dominant and contain significant CO2 and H2S. High dDH2O (250 to 297%) and d18OH2O (112 to 0%) values of ore stage fluids provide clear evidence for a deep-sourced ore fluid at Getchell that is either magmatic or metamorphic, or both.</P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

