<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Operations Research I
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, C105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>K. V. K. Prasad, Amoco E&P Technology, Tulsa, OK
<DD>T. Kovach, Sabine Mining Co., Hallsville, TX
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Knowledge-based Ore Systems for Associated Manganese of South Africa: </B><BR>
<I>R. Cook and R. Cowley, Anglovaal Ltd., Johannesburg, South Africa</I></FONT><BR>
Knowledge-based applications are becoming important to Associated Manganese for efficiently dispatching ores of appropriate grades to customers on time. The G2 expert system shell has been used to develop blending and scheduling applications using a combination of object-oriented rule-based procedural and heuristic approaches. The blending application, for example, uses a heuristic approach for creating blends from over 4000 stacks of ore of various grades and sizes, to meet customer specifications while fully exploiting the available inventory. Data capture and data warehousing have become important issues, and the Internet shows strong potential for distribution of the processed information.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Multi-mineral Cutoff Grade Optimization with Option to Stockpile: </B><BR>
<I>K. Dagdelen and W. A. A. Mohammed, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Cuttoff grade optimization is very critical to the open pit production scheduling. In case of single mineral deposits, algorithms have been developed for determining cutoff grade policy that maximizes the net present value of yearly cash flows. For determining cutoff grade policy for projects with two minerals including stockpiles the problem becomes much more complex. The purpose of this paper is to present an algorithm for the optimization of cutoff grades for two minerals that will maximize NPV subject to mining, milling, and marketing constraints with option to stockpile. Benefits of the methodology developed are demonstrated on a number of case studies coming from copper-gold deposits. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Comparison of Belt Loading Models and Simulated Belt Capacity: </B><BR>
<I>S. D. Thompson and X. Wang, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
For underground coal mining, several discrete-event simulation models have been developed to design conveying system capacities. Most of these models require the use of a step-function approach to mimic the loading process at each conveyor loading point. Over the years, practitioners have generally employed one of three versions of the step-function approach. An important issue is how these three versions compare in terms of simulated capacity requirements. This paper addresses this issue by statistically and quantitavely comparing their simulation results. The consequences and problems associated with using each version are also discussed and summarized. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Preliminary Simulation and Animation Model of the Green's Creek Mine, Juneau, Alaska: </B><BR>
<I>J. R. Sturgul, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID; T. L. Tecsa, Technical University of Petrosani, Petrosani, Romania and W. L. Jacobsen, Kennecott Corp., Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The Green's Creek Pb-Zn mine is an underground mine near Juneau, Alaska. It is proposed to drive a 3000 m incline both for existing operations and development. There will be traffic both going into the mine and coming out of this incline. It can accommodate only one way traffic. A simulation and animation model was constructed using the GPSS/H simulation language and PROOF for the animation to determine the effect of adding a long loop for empty trucks returning to the mine to avoid congestion. The whole haulage system from underground to the surface is shown in the animation. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>An Algorithm for Exact Solution to a Mesh Equation in the Hardy Cross Method for Ventilation Network Analysis: </B><BR>
<I>Y. J. Wang, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
The Hardy Cross iterative method is the most popular technique for solving the ventilation network problem with natural air splitting. This method traditionally solves each mesh equation by an approximation during each iteration. It is thus interesting from both theoretical and computational viewpoints to be able to solve for an exact solution to the mesh equation. Presented in this paper is an algorithm for computing the exact solution to the mesh equation. The algorithm uses signum functions for air quantities to generate an alternative mesh equation in the form of a quadratic equation, which has two solutions defined by the well-known quadratic formula. The condition that the derivatives of the alternative and the original equations must be the same provides a basis for a proper choice of the solution. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

