<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Solution Mining I
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, C101/103

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. E. Pahlman, Gold and Manganese Resources Co., Bloomington, MN
<DD>D. S. Ramey, BHP Copper Co., Tucson, AZ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>An Overview of Hydrogeology for In Situ Leaching of Copper at San Manuel, Arizona:</B><BR>
<I>C. T. Williamson and D. S. Ramey, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The oxide copper resource at San Manuel, Arizona has undergone in situ leaching since 1986 by BHP Copper (formerly Magma Copper). Approximately 900 injection and extraction wells are located on the benches of the successfully completed open pit mine. The current water table is over a thousand feet below the pit bottom which is at 2100 ft m.s.l. The active leach zone, therefore is a bulb of saturation suspended over the water table separated by an apparent unsaturated zone. Preferential flow conduits existing in the unsaturated zone lead to an underground collection reservoir in abandoned mine workings. A steep local fluid gradient has been induced because of leaching over the past ten years which mirrors the topography of the open pit and plays a major role in fluid flow. A firm understanding of the hydrological aspects of the system is necessary before any optimization of flow or chemistry can take place for in situ leaching. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>In Situ Leach Solution Chemistry at the San Manuel Porphyry Copper Deposit, Arizona:</B><BR>
<I>R. E. Beane and R. K. Preece, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
BHP Copper has over 10 years experience leaching copper in situ from chrysocolla at San Manuel, Arizona. Acid leach solutions contain high concentrations of magnesium aluminum and sulfate, in addition to lesser copper and iron. This brine composition demonstrates that copper is not the only element mobilized by leaching. When acid concentrations increase above a characteristic threshold, overwhelming acid consumption is by non-copper-bearing minerals. The solution composition results in stability of a suite of product minerals (chiefly sulfates), precipitation of which can inhibit copper leaching. Copper leaching is optimized when the minimum acid concentration of chrysocolla dissolution is used. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Minnesota Manganese Environmental Mining Project:</B><BR>
<I>S. C. Carlton, Gold & Manganese Resources Co., Emily, MN</I></FONT><BR>
One of the largest known higher grade manganese deposits in North America is located in Emily, Minnesota. Gold & Manganese Resources Company is utilizing environmental technologies to enhance and develop this well-defined deposit, and to develop, produce, and market manganese-based sorbents for desulfurization of fuel and flue gases in coal-fueled electrical generation systems, sour gas desulfurization in refinery applications, and effluent cleanup in paper mill waste. Current reserve estimates indicate that more than a billion pounds of contained manganese may be extracted utilizing in-situ techniques. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development of In Situ Leaching of Boron:</B><BR>
<I>G. J. Hartman, Fort Cady Minerals Corp., Newberry Springs, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Fort Caddy Minerals Corp continues to develop in situ techniques for the recovery of boron. Testing was initiated in 1981 and work continues to optimize the recovery of boron from a deep seated ore body of colemanite. A small scale production facility has been constructed in southern California and has operated for approximately two years. This paper will be primarily concerned with development of the equipment and procedures used in the operation of the well field. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

