<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Hydrology
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:00 AM, C109

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chairs:</B>
<DD>E. Schwarz, BHP Copper, Ruth, NV
<DD>J. Rowe, Water Management Consultants, Denver, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Monitoring Techniques for Assessing ARD Development in Waste Rock Piles: </B><BR>
<I>D. A. King, C. F. Luckay and W. M. Schafer, Schafer & Assoc., Bozeman, MT</I></FONT><BR>
Monitoring devices have been installed at several mine sites to assess the potential for the development of acid rock drainage (ARD). These devices monitor temperature, oxygen, and water movement in he waste rock pile. This information can be used to evaluate the current ARD risk, the effectiveness of caps and covers, and provide information to aid in the design of other reclamation strategies that limit ARD development. The instrumentation includes nested thermisters and oxygen sensing ports, neutron access tubes, heat dissipation units (HDUs), and lysimeters. Many of the monitoring devices can be linked to a datalogger and cellular telephone connection to allow monitoring data to be download from the office. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Ground-water Flow Simulations and Geochemical Modeling of Arsenic Transport in the Madison Aquifer and Bear Butte Creek Watershed of the Black Hills: </B><BR>
<I>A. D. Davis and C. J. Webb, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
The Bear Butte Creek watershed, in the northern Black Hills of South Dakota, shows the effects of past mining activities in the form of dissolved metals and arsenic in stream water. Bear Butte Creek, during normal flow periods, loses all of its discharge to sinkholes that recharge the Madison Limestone aquifer. This work focused on the geochemical fate an transport of arsenic and on understanding ground-water flow conditions in the Madison aquifer through development and a three-dimensional ground-water flow model that was coupled to a geographical information system (GIS). Stream sampling and discharge measurements helped determine sinkhole losses and loading rates. Column laboratory tests provided data on arsenic adsorption and the mixing of stream water and with aquifer water, which also was simulated with the geochemical models, pHREEQE and NETPATH. The models and GIG can be updated with new information and will be useful in managing the water quality of the Madison aquifer. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Small Scale Characterization for In Situ Leaching at the San Manuel Copper Mine: </B><BR>
<I>S. Orr and D. S. Ramey, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
As an ongoing operation, in situ leaching of copper in the San Manuel mine has moved to a phase in which changes to original well pattern are necessary to maintain high/economic copper grade in pregnant leach solution (PLS). Such changes require an investigation of preferential pathways, short circuiting, and well efficiencies. Various bore hole logging techniques are being used in San Manuel in order to understand the mechanisms that reduce leach efficiency. Previously, most attention was devoted to functional 2D sweeping of the ore. Currently, the third dimension (vertical) is equally treated, providing small scale characterization to increase sweeping. In this paper, we describe such characterization and the problems associated with it and with sweeping efficiency. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Management of Environmental Quality Data Using GIS Techniques in a General Mine Planning Framework: </B><BR>
<I>P. Croney, CGSS, Denver, CO and J. C. Herweijer, Water Management Consultants, Inc., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Environmental monitoring requires major effort and expense but management of data receives less attention. A modern database system can manage hydrochemistry, water levels, meteorology, geology and downhole geophysics data and is flexible to allow the storage of ad hoc data. Reports can be customized by the user and derived data generated from input values. The production of high quality maps with contours and hydrochemical diagrams is an essential part of the reporting process. These maps integrate directly with the current site survey information. These facilities are best provided by storing the data in an industry standard database such as Oracle or Access to which customized AutoCAD and Microsoft Office routines make direct SQL calls. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

