<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Operations Research II
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:00 AM, C105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>K. V. K. Prasad, Amoco Corp., Tulsa, OK
<DD>F. Seymour, Newmont Gold Co., Denver, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Practical Geostatistics at Newmont Gold Company: A Story of Adaptation: </B><BR>
<I>J. M. Rendu, Newmont Gold Co., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Methods used by Newmont Gold Company to model mineral deposits are presented. These methods vary depending on the geologic properties of the deposit, the economic feasibility of the project, and the availability of historical information. It is shown that understanding of the geology, knowledge of the strengths and weaknesses of the various modeling techniques, and flexibility in choosing the appropriate method are critical to successful modeling. Each major deposit is discussed separately. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Some Methods of Producing Interval Estimates for Global and Local Resources: </B><BR>
<I>B. M. Davis, Littleton, CO</I></FONT><BR>
The problem of assessing uncertainty in grade estimates has been a topic of research and debate since kriging was first introduced. Use of the kriging variance was originally touted as all that was necessary in order to produce confidence limits for grade estimates. Since then the prudence of using kriging variance for local confidence interval estimation has been questioned, and techniques such as the jackknife and conditional simulation have been proposed to develop better interval estimates. This paper compares interval estimates produced by the three methods and draws conclusions about the performance of these methods. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>How to Use Conditional Simulation for Determining Volume Variance Relationship in Recoverable Reserve Estimation:</B><BR>
<I>K. Dagdelen, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO and G. Verly, Placer Dome Inc., Vancouver, BC, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
Accurate prediction of recoverable reserves in open pit mining relies heavily on determining how the distribution of grades change as we go from point support to the selective mining unit (SMU) support. The affine correction and direct log-normal correction are two traditional techniques that allow us to do change of support on the local grade distributions. These two techniques are also very sensitive to determining the appropriate variance reductions that will take place as the SMU size increases. The geostatistical conditional simulation has become an important tool in estimating recoverable reserves that are a function of SMU size. This paper will demonstrate how conditional simulation can be used directly for estimating recoverable reserves as well as how it can be used to determine variance reduction factors in various parts of the deposit. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Conditional Bias and Smoothing Effect in Kriging: </B><BR>
<I>G. Pan, Independence Mining Co., Englewood, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Conditional bias tends to overestimate high grades and underestimate low grades, which distorts the tonnage - grade curves. Smoothing effects, however, are referred to as the opposite effect, i.e., kriging tends to underestimate high grades and overestimate low grades, which also causes incorrect tonnage - grade relations. Both effects lead to biased estimates of recoverable reserves. Based on a "ground true" blast hole data set, conditional simulation is used to generate reference estimates from which conditional bias and smoothing effect are related. Solutions are finally highlighted. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Multi-mineral Recoverable Reserve Estimation and Whittle Pit Optimization: </B><BR>
<I>S. Zhang, Echo Bay Minerals, Battle Mountain, NV</I></FONT><BR>
Recoverable reserves are defined as the estimated tons and grade that can be recovered by a mining operation at a given economic cutoff. The accuracy of grade estimation is important to minimize the over and under estimation of contained metal. The tonnage distribution at different economic cutoffs is also equally important for a mining company, since mine design and ore processing capacity, such as mill throughput or leach pad capacity, depend on the grade-tonnage distribution. Open pit optimization and mine planning should be based on the recoverable reserves which will reflect what should be recovered and processed in both grade and tons. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

