<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Underground Mining I - From Comstock to the Carlin Trend: The Resurgence of Underground Mining in Nevada
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:00 AM, C101/103

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>T. D. Arnold, Barrick Bullfrog, Inc., Beatty, NV
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>From Surface to Underground: Carlin East: </B><BR>
<I>J. M. Driscoll, Newmont Gold Co., Carlin, NV</I></FONT><BR>
After 30 years of success, Newmont Gold Co has temporarily ceased production from its Carlin Pit. In late 1993, the Carlin East Decline was driven and an extensive underground exploration program was started. Today, Newmont Gold produces refractory ore from the Carlin East underground at the rate of 700 t/d (770 stpd) for an annual ounce production of over 100,000 ounces. Over 70 underground miners enjoy the 6-8 year mine life at Carlin East. About 70% of the ore mined at Carlin East is accomplished by mechanized longhole stoping with cemented backfill. The remaining ore is mined by underhand drift and cemented fill methods. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mining at the Getchell Property: </B><BR>
<I>R. D. Russel, T. R. Harter, and R. M. Barker Getchell Gold, Golconda, NV</I></FONT><BR>
The historic Getchell property is currently being mined from the Getchell Main Underground workings (1.3 million oz.), a footwall extension of the Getchell open pit deposits along the Getchell fault. Drift-and-fill techniques are used to extract the ore via ramp access. The adjacent Turquoise Ridge deposit (1.4 million oz.) is currently under development via two vertical shafts. Together, the two mines will continues to provide feed to the Getchell's 3,200 t/d autoclave mill, taking Getchell Gold from its current production rate of 200,000 oz. per annum, to over 400,000 oz. per annum by 1999.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Jerritt Canyon's Transition to Underground Mining: </B><BR>
<I>W. W. Bristol, Independence Mining Co., Elko, NV</I></FONT><BR>
Since its discovery, the Jerritt Canyon Mine, located 50 miles north of Elko, Nevada, a joint venture between Independence Mining Company Inc. (70%) and FMC Gold Company (30%), refractory gold ore has predominantly been mined by conventional open pit methods. Since the early 1990's, the discovery of deeper ores has required the joint venture to develop and mine a significant portion of the 325,000 troy ounce annual production utilizing underground mining methods. The recently developed Murray and West Generator underground mines now produce 120,000-140,000 ounces annually. Two additional underground projects are also being concurrently developed by IMCI. This paper documents the major transition/redevelopment of the Jerritt Canyon mining methods. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Design and Development of the Meikle Mine: </B><BR>
<I>R. D. Pye and J. W. Breen, Barrick Goldstrick Mines Inc., Elko, NV</I></FONT><BR>
The Meikle Mine, the first shaft accessed underground mine on the Carlin Trend and destined to become the largest underground gold producer in the United States, presented a number of interesting challenges in its design and development. The design of the mine and its associated infrastructure is described together with a review of the mine development program leading to full production status. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

