<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Mechanical Mining and Excavation
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, C109

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>P. J. A. Lever, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ
<DD>L. Ozdemir, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mining of Medium Hard and Hard Rock Without Blasting by Means of Cutting Experiences and Economics of the Wirtgen Surface Miner: </B><BR>
<I>B. Schimm, Wirtgen GmbH, Windhagen, Germany</I></FONT><BR>
Improve the mine's productivity by simplifying the mining process, for these tasks the Wirtgen Surface Miner offers an attractive alternative. Surface Miners cut, crush and load material in one operation with only one machine. The cutting depth is controlled exactly. This allows: Selective mining of different material qualities, mining without blasting, production of small particle sizes, preparation of level and stable surfaces, walls and haulroads. The result: Less investment, less production costs, low noise and dust, no vibrations, high systems availability, simple mine and operation planning and coordination, less labor for operation and maintenance and less spare parts. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>TBM Tunneling at the San Manuel Mine: </B><BR>
<I>R. R. Allum, BHP Copper, San Manuel, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The application of high speed tunneling in a deep underground copper mine was essential for the Lower Kalamazoo expansion project at BHP Copper's San Manuel Mine. At stake was the future of over 1,300 employees at one of the largest producing block caving copper mines in the world. This paper examines the details required to assemble, deploy and operate a 4.62 meter open main beam tunnel boring machine (TBM) in a 1048 meter deep operating mine accessible only by shaft. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Selection, Design Optimization and Performance Prediction of Tunnel Boring Machines: </B><BR>
<I>L. Ozdemir and J. Rostami, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Tunnel Boring Machines (TBM's) are finding increasing use in underground mine development due to the potential benefits they offer in terms of higher production rates, reduced ground support and ventilation requirements and lower excavation costs. As with any mechanical tunneling project, the successful application of TBM technology to mining lies in the selection of the most suitable equipment and cutting tool for the rock and ground conditions to be encountered. Once a decision is made on the type of machine, the next step is to optimize its design to achieve the highest advance rates feasible. This paper will present and discuss the process of conducting site investigations, laboratory testing, machine selection, design optimization and performance/cost estimation for TBM use in mine development.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mechanical Mining Machine Start-up at a Western Ag Minerals Carlsbad Potash Mine: </B><BR>
<I>S. M. Hodgson, Wester Ag-Minerals, Carlsbad, NM</I></FONT><BR>
A comprehensive feasibility study began by asking: Why wouldn't a mechanical mining machine cut potash. Six years later a continuous miner has doubled the tons per man-shift at the Nash Draw Mine. The program: Considered all continuous miners, roadheaders, and borers. Visited mines experienced in mechanical mining. Evaluated machine cutterhead layout, power, and RPM. Contacted manufacturers for specifications and innovative risk sharing. Determined torque and power requirements using large rock block cutting tests. The program indicated a potash miner with high torque, and weighing at least 50 tons. The new 90 ton machine mines an 8 by 32 foot 11-entry production panel for 132 feet before roof bolting. The financial package shares both ownership (price in cost per ton) and maintenance. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

