<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Open Pit Mining I - Case Histories of Developing Mines Overseas
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, C105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>H. Welhener, Independent Mining Consultants, Inc., Tucson, AZ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Study-BHP Robinson and BHP Tintaya: </B><BR>
<I>K. L. Browne II, BHP Nevada Mining, Co., Ruth, NV</I></FONT><BR>
After a decade of high copper prices, major mining companies are renewing their interest in purchasing operating properties and/or development of ore bodies. An existing operation carries with it a history that can present unique opportunities, while a greenfield operation allows for the establishment of a defined culture. Capital investments are distinctly different. A comparison of BHP Copper Robinson Operation, a greenfield property, and BHP Copper Tintaya Operation, a government-owned Peruvian property, will provide insights into mining, concentrating and cultural differences between North and South American operations. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development and Operation of the La Choya Open Pit Heap Leach Gold Mine: </B><BR>
<I>A. H. Summers, Minera Hecla, S. A. de C. V., Hermosillo, Sonora, Mexico</I></FONT><BR>
La Choya is located 55 km south of Sonoyta in northwestern Sonora. Hecla Mining Co. purchased the concessions in May 1992 and designed and constructed the mine which started production in January 1994. Mineralization is controlled by a low angle thrust fault-which created a permeable host for the metal bearing hydrothermal solutions. Open pit-heap leaching methods are used to recover gold and silver from low grade ore. Approximately 9 tons of gold will be recovered over the four year productive life of the mine which was the second largest gold producer in Mexico during 1995 and 1996. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Candelaria Copper-gold Mine, Chile: </B><BR>
<I>P. J. Ryan and J. L. Madson, Phelps Dodge Corp., Phoenix, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The Candelaria copper-gold mine is located 20 kilometers to the south of the town of Capiop in Northern Chile, Phelps Dodge owns 80 percent of the mine and the remaining 20 percent is owned by the Sumitomo group of companies. The deposit was discovered by Phelps Dodge in 1987 and minable reserves extractable by open-pit methods have been estimated at 366 million tons averaging 1.09 percent copper and 0.26 grams of gold per ton. A detailed feasibility study, dated March 1991 demonstrated the economic viability of the project and construction and development commenced on October 1, 1992. By September 1994, the first concentrate was produced about four months ahead of schedule and within the approved budget of $570 million. During 1995, the first full year of production, Candelaria produced 521,478 tonnes of concentrate containing 150,340 tons of salable copper and 97,796 ounces of gold. The unit cash cost of production for 1995 was less than $0.50 per pound of copper making Candelaria one of the low cost copper producers in the world. Taking into account the large ore reserves, Phelps Dodge is currently doubling the milling rate to 20 million tons per year. The Candelaria copper-gold mine is the largest and most successful project ever undertaken by Phelps-Dodge outside the United States. Details of the geology, ore reserve estimates, mine planning and operating procedures, metallurgical process development and operations and the port facilities are discussed. In addition, the development of power, water, roads and housing are covered. Permitting and environmental requirements for the project and the financing arrangements are also discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Minera Candelaria: A Retrospective View: </B><BR>
<I>W. F. Baker, Phelps Dodge Mining Co., Tierra Amarilla, Chile</I></FONT><BR>
Minera Candelaria represents the first greenfield venture by Phelps Dodge Mining Company in South America. Although a resounding success, the project in retrospect presents an opportunity to evaluate the effectiveness of our U.S. based philosophy as it has been applied in this new geographic arena. This paper will review the brief history of the project with emphasis placed on lessons learned during the development, construction and initial operation of the facility as well as a current look at Candeleria. In conclusion, a quick glimpse into the future of Phelps Dodge's newest world-class mining operation will be presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Kubaka, The Arctic Mining Challenge in Far East Russia: </B><BR>
<I>T. L. Owen, Cyprus Amax, Englewood, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Not since 1917 has a foreign company developed a stand-alone, grass roots gold mine in Russia. With Russia's political change, in the late 1980's development of mineral prospects once again beckons foreign investors. In 1991 Cyprus Amax began aggressively searching for such an opportunity. Early in 1997, production will commence at the Kubaka gold project located in Far Eastern Russia, near the Arctic Circle. The Kubaka proj-ect is a 1,750 ton-per-day open pit operation that will produce over 300,000 ounces of gold per year. This paper will focus on the challenges of locating such a prospect, doing business in Russia, developing supply lines, identifying workforce capabilities, gaining government approvals, secure financing, arrange for gold sales and ultimately building the facility in this arctic region. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

