<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Underground Mining II - Projects and Productivity
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, C101/103

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>T. D. Arnold, Barrick Bullfrog, Inc., Beatty, NV
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Dilution Control at Doyon Mine: </B><BR>
<I>R. Quesnel, L. Chenad, and D. Janoien, La Mine Doyon, Quebec, PQ, Canada, and P. Stgeonges, ICI Explosives, Quebec, PQ, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
In order to increase shareholders value, Barrick Gold Corporation has embarked, beginning January 1996, on a 3-year 10% cost reduction program. At La Mine Doyon, we believe that this can be achieved mainly through our Dilution Control Program. Multiple task team, comprising of geologists, engineers, key underground personnel and explosives consultants are auditing and reviewing all phases of mining. Innovative techniques and structures are being implemented and management is committed in supporting and supplying the required tools. This paper outlines what has been accomplished and where La Mine Doyon is headed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Shaft versus Ramp-An Empirical Decision Model: </B><BR>
<I>P. Moser, Montan University, Leoben, Austria</I></FONT><BR>
As a contribution to an improved primary development design procedure beyond the already existing studies a study for the identification and quantification of the influence of parameters on primary development based on operational data from working mining operations has been completed. For that purpose a worldwide analysis of the design of the primary access of about 200 underground hardrock mining operations in industrialized countries was completed. Based upon the mine data collected a sequenced decision model has been developed, that enables us to develop an initial concept for the design of the accesses from the surface based upon a few critical parameters. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Effects and Control of Overbreak in Underground Mining:</B><BR>
<I>G. F. Revey, GEOTEK & Assoc., Inc., Highlands Ranch, CO</I></FONT><BR>
All underground operations have limiting factors that influence their overall profitability. Hoisting, hauling, available headings, labor, milling capacity and other factors limit how much material can be removed from an underground mine. Consequently, when limited labor is used to handle additional rock from overbreak and perform extra ground support tasks, productive activity is replaced by non-productive work. This paper reviews the effects of overbreak on mining costs, and presents a quality improvement approach that has been successfully used to significantly reduce overbreak at several large underground metal mines. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Cost-per-ton Improvement Ideas for Underground Equipment:</B><BR>
<I>J. D. Wiebmer, Caterpillar Elphinstone Pty. Ltd., Peoria, IL</I></FONT><BR>
This paper helps identify the most important factors in managing underground loading and hauling fleets for lowest cost per ton over the long term. The paper keys in on the most important factors and discusses some practical improvement ideas. The paper closes with a look ahead at technological developments that will impact cost-per-ton.

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

