<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Environmental Control and Reclamation Evaluation and Mitigation of Adverse Environmental Impacts of Mining
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, C105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>R. Singh, Office of Surface Mining, Denver, CO
<DD>J. W. Coleman, Kerr McGee Coal Corp., Oklahoma City, OK
</DL>


<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Comprehensive Inventory of Abandoned Mines in the Black HIlls of South Dakota:</B><BR>
<I>A. D. Davis, C. J. Webb and C. J. Paterson, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
This work focused on identifying, examining, and ranking the physical and environmental hazards at inactive and abandoned mine sites in the Black Hills of South Dakota. Earlier inventory projects in the Black Hills concentrated on federal lands, while more recent efforts have examined abandoned mines on state and private lands after passage of legislation by the State of South Dakota requiring a comprehensive inventory. The inventory information provides criteria for identifying those sites that require further investigation through characterization of the physical safety or environmental hazards. For most AML sites in the Black Hills, locational information is all that is typically needed because the majority of sites pose little environmental or physical hazard. This comprehensive inventory of abandoned mines in the Black Hills included the identification and ranking of hazards, and provided information on the extent of potential water contamination as well as remediation strategies. The inventory also resulted in the linking of previous information sources such as the US Bureau of Mines, US Geological Survey, and US Forest Service databases.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Watershed Approach to Evaluating Impacts of Abandoned Mines in the  Bear Butte Creek Basin of the Black Hills:</B><BR>
<I>C. J Webb, A. D Davis, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD and T. V. Durkin, SD Dept. of Environment and Natural Resources</I></FONT><BR>
This project took a watershed approach in the evaluation of water-quality impacts from past mining activities and current restoration projects in the Bear Butte Creek basin, a small and well defined drainage in a heavily mineralized area of the northern Black Hills. The basin contains numerous inactive and abandoned mines as well as a currently active heap-leach surface gold mine. Bear Butte Creek normally loses all of its discharge to sinkholes in the Madison Limestone aquifer and thus can affect the water quality of this regionally important water resource. Water-quality data were analyzed, stream surveys were conducted, and two abandoned mine restoration projects were monitored to evaluate the effectiveness of the watershed approach and to identify practical remediation techniques that could be applied to other watersheds. A geographic information system (GIS) was developed to organize information on stream quality, abandoned mine locations, and other geologic and hydrologic data. The watershed approach toward assessing and reclaiming abandoned mines appears to be effective when compared to a point-source approach that might  improve water quality at specific sites but not result in significant overall improvement to the watershed because of adjacent sources. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Ore Permeability Testing for Heap Leach Design:</B><BR>
<I>M. E. Orman and K. R. Criley, Vector Engineering, Inc., Grass Valley, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Many factors must be considered when designing a heap leach pad. Geotechnical properties of the ore can and will affect how well an ore leaches, the solution recovery, stability of the heap, and ore settlement. As a heap is stacked, some of these properties will change due to the increased load. In order to properly design a heap, these properties should be determined beforehand, so that the heap performs as intended. As a heap is stacked, stresses in the lower portion of the heap increase and cause a reduction in ore porosity and permeability. This paper presents a test method which has been successfully used to estimate ore permeability and deformation under simulated heap loading conditions. Once these factors are determined, the heap drainage system can be properly designed and the appropriate rates can be selected. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Leach Pad LIner Systems: Selection and Optimization:</B><BR>
<I>M. E. Smith, Vector Engineering, Inc., Grass Valley, CA and K. Crompton, Vector Chile Ltd., Santiago, Chile</I></FONT><BR>
Leach pad liner system selection practice ranges from "we've used it before" to exhaustive considerations of all possible combinations of foundation soils, geosynthetics, and cover materials. On one end of the spectrum engineering judgement is the only tool used and on the other the analytical tools often out-gun the quantifiable factors. The authors present a rational design method, applicable to any liner project but specifically developed for heap leaching, which balances the needs for a simplified approach with the engineering appropriate for the investment represented. Illustrative case histories are also presented. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Designing Leach Pad Liners for Differential Settlement:</B><BR>
<I>T. V. Ramey, M. E. Orman and M. E. Smith, Vector Engineering, Inc., Grass Valley, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Heap leaching brings unique design problems in the form of possible large differential settlements of the foundation soils due to the dissolution of salts. Soils often contain very high concentrations of soluble salts (nitrates, potassium, magnesium, and common sodium). Leaking solution can dissolve these salts and trigger settlement. If the differential settlement is great enough, the geomembrane tears, the leakage increases, triggering more settlement. The authors present a simplified technique to quantify the differential settlement resulting from dissolution of salts and present a method to select a geomembrane which provides suitable flexibility to tolerate the predicted settlement. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>On/Off Leach Pads: Special Liner Design Requirements:</B><BR>
<I>M. E. Smith, Vector Engineering, Inc. Grass Valley, CA</I></FONT><BR>
On/off leach pads have traditionally been constructed of asphalt. But geomembranes have become increasingly popular substitutes for a number of reasons, including cost and reliability. Geomembranes for on/off leach pads require special design considerations to withstand the large, repetitive loading. Combinations of bedding, geomembrane selection and protective cover design can be optimized for cost and performance. Design techniques, common trade-offs and examples are presented. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The North American Bats and Mines Project: A Cooperative Approach for Integrating Bat Conservation, Mining, and Mine Land Reclamation:</B><BR>
<I>D. A. R. Taylor, Bat Conservation International, Inc., Austin, TX</I></FONT><BR>
Inactive underground mines provide essential habitat for a majority of North America's largest remaining bat populations. These bats are primary predators of insects that cost American farmers and foresters billions of dollars annually. Mine closures without checking for bats could endanger even currently abundant species. Fortunately, cost-effective closure methods exist that can protect both bats and humans, and new habitat can be created during mining, preventing future endangered listings. BCI and the BLM founded the Bats and Mines Project to provide coordination and leadership among public and private agencies and the mining industry to minimize the loss of bats living in mines. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Identification of Sources of Metals in Stream Sediments Using Electron Microprobe Techniques:</B><BR>
<I>K. Whiting and R. L. Olsen, Camp Dresser & McKee, Inc., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Elevated concentrations of copper, cobalt, and arsenic within the Panther Creek Basin sediments in north central Idaho prompted an evaluation of the sources of the metals. Potential tailings and wasterock source samples collected at the head of Blackbird Creek were compared to sediment samples in the Panther Creek Basin using electron microprobe techniques. The mineral types, degree of alteration, and the morphology of the metal-bearing sediment grains within Blackbird and Panther Creeks were found to closely resemble the tailings material, suggesting the copper, cobalt and arsenic concentrations in the basin were derived principally from the tailings impoundment. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

