<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geomechanics I-Advanced Geomechanics Methods for Productivity Enhancement
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, C101/103

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>K. Kim, Columbia University, New York, NY
<DD>M. Karfakis, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA 
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Coupled Finite Element Modeling of Slope Stability: </B><BR>
<I>W. G. Pariseau and S. C. Schmelter, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The well-known destabilizing effect of water pressure on rock mass stability is examined quantitavely by the finite element method. A coupled code that accounts for the simultaneous effects of rock mass deformation and fluid flow is used for this purpose. Equivalent elastic moduli, strengths and hydraulic conductivities are composited from laboratory test data and joint set map data using a non-representative volume element (NRVE) procedure. Of concern is the Mandel-Cryer effect of transitory but elevated water pressure following a cut, a phenomenon not taken into account by simple before and after equilibrium analysis. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Geomechanics and Geohydrological Issues in Mine Sealing:</B><BR>
<I>K. Fuenkajorn, Rock Engineering Int'l., Tucson, AZ and J. C. Stormont, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM</I></FONT><BR>
This paper presents an overview of sealing methods for mine openings, with an emphasis on geomechanics and goehydrological performance of the emplaced seals. Discussions include design considerations and criteria, material selection, placement methods, and current regulations and practices. The site conditions that may impact the seal performance are addressed, including geological and hydrological considerations, borehole conditions, fluid pressures, geochemistry, in situ stresses, temperature, and impact from nearby activities. General design criteria are provided. The recommendations are based on the results of laboratory and in situ experiments conducted as part of research effort on nuclear waste repositories. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Incorporating End Effects in the Lamda, Alpha, Chai Model of Pillar Strength:  </B><BR>
<I>L. A. Panek, Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
This mathematical model of pillar compressive strength was developed by interpreting numerous published tests performed under laboratory conditions, to eliminate poorly controlled end effects as a source of data variability. Log strength was show to be a bilinear function of c (itself and function of size and aspect ratio), with small slope for small width/thickness and much greater slope for large W/D, thus providing a straightforward basis for accurately computing the strength of typical, wide mine pillars. The present paper extends the model to include end effects, which depend on sliding friction, internal friction, prism/platen deformability and bond, and lateral earth pressure.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>LoSCoMS: an Interactive Longwall Strata Control and Maintenance System: </B><BR>
<I>D-W Park and D. Deb, The University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL</I></FONT><BR>
Longwall mining is considered as the most effective underground coal mining technique in terms of coal extraction ration, productivity, and safety. But roof falls, excessive face convergence, shield damage, and other maintenance problems cause interruptions of coal production and safety hazards. The University of Alabama has been developing software called Longwall Strata Control and Maintenance System (LoSCoMS), which integrates real-time shield monitoring, data presentation, analysis, forecasting, and warning modules. The main objectives of this system is to provide information on excessive load, inadequate setting load, leg leakage, etc., and to synthesize mining and geological parameters to determine past and present ground behavior and forecast loading patterns for the mining cycles, next periodic weighting, etc. Using this unique system, mine personnel can learn past and present roof loading patterns, and predict future loading trends at a longwall face, thus proper safety measures can be taken ahead of time. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Characterization of Polyester Grouts for Ground Control: </B><BR>
<I>M. G. Karfakis and S. W. Kan, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA and R. Wilson and J. Zelanko, Sandvik Rock Tools, Bristol, VA</I></FONT><BR>
Chemical grouting is often used as a remedial measure when the implemented ground control program is unable to completely prevent structural failures or when there is a need for preventing a structural member from unraveling. The polyurethane grout, which is currently being used, has a limited range of mechanical properties that restrict its utilization. Polyurethane grout cannot be used for applications where reinforcement and strengthening, together with deformability, is desired. The strength and deformability of chemical grout must be compatible with the intended purpose of grouting and the expected deformation of the rock that is to be grouted. To overcome these limitations, research has been conducted on a newly developed polyester based grout. The newly developed polyester grout, depending on its formulation, is flexible enough to have a wide range of mechanical properties. The assessment of mechanical properties of polyester grout is the focus of this work. Field experiences and laboratory research have defined the properties of an effective grouting material. Experimental results indicate that the polyester grout meets or exceeds these recommended properties and has the potential to expand the applicability of chemical grouting in ground control. By adjusting its formulations, mechanical properties of polyester grout can be engineered to solve specific ground control problems. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Design and Evaluation of Entry System Stability by Using Reliability Theory: </B><BR>
<I>V. Z. Sun and S. S. Peng, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
One of the major concerns of ground control in a coal mine is safety against failure in the mine entry system (i.e. roof-pillar-floor). In order to better design and evaluate stability of the entry system with a certain confidence, a reliability approach is introduced rather than using the conventional factor of safety (CFS) only. Since the reliability approach can take variability of both rock properties and stress distribution into consideration, it is anticipated that, by using this approach, the current state-of-the-art-based ground control design in coal mines will convey a better sense of confidence. The results of this study show a significant influence on the current design concept and evaluation of entry system stability. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

