<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Open Pit Mining II - Mine Planning
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, C109

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>H. Welhener, Independent Mining Consultants, Inc., Tucson, AZ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Strategic Planning Model at White Springs, Florida Phosphate Mining and Chemical Operations: </B><BR>
<I>J. T. Crawford, Behre Dolbear & Co., Inc. Gainesville, FL</I></FONT><BR>
A comprehensive strategic planning model has been developed for the phosphate strip mining and chemical operations at White Springs, Florida. The computerized model covers ore body modeling, production simulation and financial analysis. Several innovative features in the model include using NPV techniques in ore body block economics, adapting the floating cone method to a floating template for generating dragline mining units automatically, using interactive graphics for designing mining units, and a dragline move economics algorithm for automatic scheduling of mining unit assignments and moves. Simulation of chemical plant production uses linear programming and concentrate inventory levels control mine operating schedules. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Computer-aided Earthmoving in Mining Applications: </B><BR>
<I>D. Greene, Caterpillar, Concord, CA</I></FONT><BR>
The paper will summarize Caterpillar's products and experience using Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) monitoring and information systems for mining machines. The paper will include overviews on the background, development, and field application of systems which allow digital mine design plans to be used directly on-board various mining machines in real-time via moving map displays. These systems help eliminate many time consuming error-prone survey operations and paper maps. In addition, the systems help eliminate many excavation errors, ranging from incorrect haul ramp slopes to bench over/under-excavation and mis-excavation of ore vs. waste. The paper will close with a look at the significant management advantages gained from use of a real-time database of as-mined and as-built information, which is automatically created as the machines are operated. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Strategic Planning in Open Pit Mine Optimization: </B><BR>
<I>A. J. Basu and S. Belohlawek, Western Australia School of Mines, Kalgoorlie, WA, Australia and B. McFadzean, Kalgoorlie Consolidated Gold Mines, Kalgoorlie, WA, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
Computer-assisted mine planning and design applications are routinely used by many Australian mining companies. However, the design process requires human expertise to recognize and evaluate the potential pitfalls. This paper introduces the application of a commercial optimization software (WHITTLE 4D) for strategic planning of an open pit mine in Western Australia. The authors present their experience in intelligent application of the optimization program while incorporating many technical and nontechnical obstacles. It is expected that this paper will provide some guidelines on how to apply the optimization software without losing sight of practicalities. Moreover, this paper also shows how to build project evaluation guidelines for nonexperts. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>In-pit Crushing and Conveying in Open Pit Mines: </B><BR>
<I>S. A. Jeric, Phelps Dodge, Morenci, AZ and M. J. Hrebar, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO</I></FONT><BR>
In-pit crushing and conveying of ore and waste has been utilized in the mining industry for many years. In recent years, innovations in crushing, conveying, and particularly heap leach and waste stacking technology, have sparked a renewed interest in continuous haulage systems for large scale open pit applications. This paper examines current operations that are using large scale continuous haulage systems. A review of the advantages/disadvantages and operating techniques of crushers, feeders, conveyors, and stacking systems currently available is made. Finally, a case study is presented that evaluates the application of a continuous waste haulage system in a large open pit mine in the Western United States. The case study includes an economic comparison with the existing truck haulage system. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

