<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geomechanics II-Application of Geomechanics Technology to Enhance Productivity
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, C101/103

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>M. Karfakis, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA
<DD>K. Kim, Columbia University, New York, NY
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Gate Road Design in Overlying Multiple Seam Mines: </B><BR>
<I>J. Luo, C. Haycocks and M. Karmis, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
A major design problem for upper seam longwall gateroads is to predict the effect of stress transferred from lower seam mines on operating stability. Case study data were analyzed to develop empirical stress transfer relationships between seams for both longwall and room-and-pillar mines. Analysis showed vertical movement in the upper seam and roof CMRR to be controlling factors in damage prediction and therefore gateroad planning and design. Results from selected case studies were correlated with upper seam stress predictions calculated by LAMODEL for additional planning opportunities. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Study of Weathering Actions on Pillar and its Effect on Long Term Stability: </B><BR>
<I>K. Biswas and S. S. Peng, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
Pillar stability long after mining can be attributed to the weathering action in presence of mine moisture. From the field observations, it has been found that this phenomenon becomes more critical in case the coal seam contains a parting or binder in it. The weathering action degrades both the coal and parting in terms of their load-bearing capacity as the mine moisture penetrates into the pillar and it has been found that the deterioration is more severe in parting as it converts to clay-like material when exposed to moisture for a long period of time. The expansion of weathering zone in either coal or parting is a time dependent phenomenon as the moisture gradually penetrates into the pillar. This paper investigates the effect of weathering action on coal and parting in laboratory and in field. Also an attempt has been done to establish formulae for time dependent strength of coal and parting. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Real-time Operation of LoSCoMS at Shoat Creek Mine: </B><BR>
<I>D-W Park and D. Deb, The University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL</I></FONT><BR>
Longwall Strata Control and Maintenance System (LoSCoMS) is a computer software developed to monitor, analyze, and forecast longwall ground control problems in real-time. Recently, this system has been installed in Shoal Creek Mine, Alabama. This system is designed for monitoring pressure data from all the shields at regular intervals and storing them in the hard disk of the surface computer in real-time. Using LoSCoMS, hourly reports of maintenance problems such as high load, inadequate settings, leakage of hydraulic systems, etc., can be generated along with shields locations. Presentation of past and present data, analysis of mining cycles and subsequent forecasting of next mining cycles and periodic weighting location are generated to facilitate everyday operation. Moreover, the surface computer is connected with Drummond's internal networking system, thus, any terminal equipped with LoSCoMS software can access the remote data files and perform the analysis in near real-time. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Numerical Simulation of Rock Strength Testing: </B><BR>
<I>A. J. Basu and M. Kuruppu, Western Australian School of Mines, Kalgoorlie, WA, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
Rock mass properties testing for determining strength parameters is an integral part of geomechanics. These tests are performed either in a laboratory environment or in a field (in situ). The authors share their experience in using numerical modelling in simulating the laboratory test procedures. This approach helps studying the rock breakage and failure mechanism more efficiently and provides a high degree of visualization. Moreover, imperfections and discontinuities can be easily incorporated in these models. This capability of providing arbitrary fractures and discontinuities facilitates in building a large knowledgebase of rock strength and failure mechanisms. This knowledgebase may then be used to generate heuristics for determining rock strengths for rock mass with fractures and discontinuities. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Back-analysis of Stresses Associated with Longwall Face Bursts at the Deer Creek Mine, Energy West Mining Company, Utah: </B><BR>
<I>J. F. T. Agapito, R. R. Goodrich and M. Moon, Agapito Assoc., Inc., Grand Junction, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Experience at Energy West Mines in the Wasatch Plateau Coal Field, Utah has shown that longwall face bursts occur mostly near the tailgate when extracting the third adjacent longwall in a panel section where depths exceed 2000 ft. It is believed that this is due to a combination of cover depth and side abutment stresses created by the widening of a pressure arch formed by interlocking and bridging of large blocks of very competent strata. The 200-ft-thick Castle-gate Sandstone probably plays a key role in pressure arching. This paper presents a back-analysis of the location and magnitude of the stresses associated with face bursts that occurred when mining the 7th Right Longwall at the Deer Creek Mine. Improvement of these conditions may be achieved by widening the longwalls to achieve critical subsidence width sooner while mining the second longwall, and to reduce the stresses at the face. Wider longwall faces, however, increase the change of sandstone channel interception often associated with bursts. Satisfactory mitigation of face bursts beyond cover depths of 2000 ft to 2200 ft may be difficult without using destressing techniques. Development and testing of hydraulic fracturing/liquid infusion technique is recommended. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Numerical Modeling of Dilution-Cave Mining Method: </B><BR>
<I>R. L. McNearny and K. A. Barker, The University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
Some unresolved questions from previous investigations into the physical and numerical modeling of the block caving mining method (McNearny and Abel, 1993), are investigated and reported in this paper. The previous work investigated both the physical and numerical modeling of the effects of drawpoint spacing, undercut thickness, and the rate of draw. Specifically, the questions raised by the prior investigation include (1) unequal draw rates and its effect on dilution, (2) planes of weakness within and along the boundary of the model, and (3) the progression of deformations into the undisturbed rock mass prior to cave development. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

