<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Solution Mining II
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, C105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. E. Pahlman, Gold and Manganese Resources Co., Bloomington, MN
<DD>D. S. Ramey, BHP Copper Co., Tucson, AZ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Hydrological Characterization for In Situ Leach Mining at Florence, Arizona:</B><BR>
<I>G. Chen, BHP Copper, Florence, AZ and S. Orr and D. S. Ramey, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
A feasibility study of in situ leach mining at Florence, Arizona is being conducted by BHP Copper. The hydrogeologic characterization covers large (regional) scale pumping tests, intermediate scale pumping tests, and small scale tests along boreholes. The initial findings indicate that the site is sufficiently permeable for in situ leaching and behaves like a porous medium at these scales. The vertical distribution of hydraulic conductivity, fracture distribution and mineralization are investigated. Parameters determined in this characterization are being used in numerical simulations of leaching processes and optimization of the mine design. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Breakthrough Core Logging Techniques in Characterizing Buried Ore Deposits: Case Study-BHP Florence Project, Arizona:</B><BR>
<I>C. K. Hoag and J. M. Sguin, BHP Copper, Florence, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
BHP Copper has developed a method to study fracture intensity, mineralogy, and orientations to optimize structure-mineralogy data gathered on buried, in situ copper oxide leach targets. This new method utilizes an acoustic borehole televiewer logging tool to determine structure orientations for fracture and fault planes, in conjunction with detailed fracture and mineralogy data collected from drill core. The downhole distribution, as well as the preferred orientations, of common ore and gangue minerals are determined. Overall structure-mineralogy trends are identified, which contribute to the geologic and hydrologic model, as well as influence wellfield design and extraction methods. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development of a Leachable Copper Resource Model for In Situ Mine Expansion:</B><BR>
<I>T. L. Carstensen and M. P. Neira, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The Miami in situ mine of BHP Copper is located in Globe-Miami, Arizona. The mine leaches mineralized leach capping over a supergene enriched sulfide deposit, and has produced over 500 million lbs. of copper during the last 50 years. The Miami unit has identified several opportunities to enhance and expand in situ production. A computer block model consisting of strict geologic controls, mineralogy, and metallurgical data, was developed to assist in the determination of the leachable copper resource. An understanding of the accessibility and solubility of the resource to leaching solutions, and the integration of hydrogeologic and hydrometallurgical information was necessary for completion of this project. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Numerical Simulation of In Situ Leaching and Metal Attenuation:</B><BR>
<I>A. Getahun, Brown and Caldwell, Phoenix, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Numerical modeling has been used to simulate a near-surface in situ leaching of oxide-copper minerals using acid sulfate solution. Several types of reactions expected to occur during leaching are evaluated by a series of calculations at 25C: 1) reaction of acid-sulfate  solution with ore-bearing silicate rock, 2) reaction of metal-rich acid-sulfate solution with carbonate rock, minerals, and carbonate cemented alluvial material, 3) reaction of metal-rich acid-sulfate solution with lime, and 4) mixing of metal-bearing acid-sulfate solution with groundwater. The results demonstrate the importance of 1) host rock composition, 2) type of copper-bearing minerals, 3) pH of the solution during reaction, and 4) the water/rock ratio. Such simulation results provide a systematic evaluation of the chemical and hydrologic conditions that are tied to in situ leaching and help to focus toward appropriate production and environmental questions. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Numerical Simulation of Hydraulic Control for In Situ Mining:</B><BR>
<I>J. M. Oliver and F. Sirjani, Brown and Caldwell, Phoenix, AZ and The BHP Copper Group, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
An analysis was conducted of multidimensional groundwater flow and solute transport for a proposed in situ copper mine in Florence, Arizona. The two key features evaluated in the mathematical simulations were: (1) hydraulic control of mine solutions within an active mine block; and (2) potential effects of the mining operations on the regional aquifer system. A representative mine block was modeled with injection and recovery wells simultaneously pumping in a repeating 5-spot well pattern. Results of the modeling illustrated that hydraulic control of the mine solutions within the simulated mine block could be achieved over a wide range of hydrogeologic scenarios. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

