<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geology I-Geologic Factors that Influence the Economic Viability of Mineral Deposits 
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, C102/104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>M. Osterberg, BHP Minerals, Tucson, AZ
<DD>S. K. Hamilton, Behre Dolbear & Co., Denver, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Turning Discoveries into Mines-What's Required from the Geologist?:</B><BR>
<I>P. G. Monzon, Eldorado, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
A producing mine has to meet technical as well as economic constraints in order to operate profitably. Among some of the technical parameters are the geological features that each deposit has. The shape and the depth of the orebody as well as the grade and type of mineralization will determine the mining method to be used. Information on the structural geology, lithology, alteration and type of mineralization will help to determine the metallurgical process and the slope design. The information provided by the geologist is of utmost importance in turning discoveries into mines. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Utilization of Geologic Information in Computer Block Models:</B><BR>
<I>J. A. Waegli, Phelps Dodge Exploration Corp., Lakewood, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Key geologic features of a mineral deposit are modeled to control grade interpolation, and to quantify other parameters which affect the economic viability of a deposit. Although numerous papers discuss grade interpolation aspects of geologic modeling, the impacts of lithology, mineralogy, alteration, and structure on mining and mineral processing are often not considered, and therefore not modeled. Three examples of geologic modeling are presented: modeling recoveries and acid consumption in a copper leach project, modeling milling and leaching characteristics at a combination concentrator SX/EW operation, and modeling RQD for slope optimization. Careful collection of these kinds of information during the exploration and development phases of a project is critical in forming a solid foundation for feasibility-stage models, and will avoid the considerable time and expense involved in relogging drill holes months or even years later. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Process Development for Exploration Projects:</B><BR>
<I>J. T. Hanks, Phelps Dodge Exploration Corp., Phoenix, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Process development is one of the principal tasks required in the course of turning an exploration discovery into a mine. Exploration geologists should have an understanding of the more important metallurgical processes and the test work required for each process. The paper discusses the important metallurgical processes, the test work and sample requirements for each, and the costs and time requirements to accomplish the testing. The limitations of reverse circulation drill samples for metallurgical testing are discussed. The level of process definition required to support engineering studies: scoping, prefeasibility and feasibility studies is also described. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Practical Geotechnical Drill Core Data Collection Requirements for an Underground Mine:</B><BR>
<I>L. A. Sandbak, BHP Copper, San Manuel, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The purpose of collecting rock mechanics data from drill core is the eventual use in operations, planning, or characterization work. Information gathered must be quantitative and repeatable. Fracture frequency and rock block sizes are commonly overlooked in most rock classification methods. Data for the Kalamazoo porphyry copper deposit feasibility study included geology, alteration, and rock mass characterization. The primary benefit of adequate data retrieval is prediction. Additional drift mapping is compared to drill hole data for subsequent refinement and correlation, and to determine what data is most useful.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Considerations in Business Negotiations for Exploration Projects:</B><BR>
<I>R. W. Schafer, Kinross Gold Corp., Toronto, ON, Canada and J. Tarazoff, BHP Minerals, San Francisco, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Among the technical aspects of a mining venture that determines whether a mining venture is successful or not, one of the most important, but least acknowledged, is the property agreement with the underlying owner. In the case of public lands, the administrator is defined (BLM or NFS) and the "terms of agreement" are well-regulated. In the case of a private mineral and/or surface ownership, virtually all aspects of an agreement may be open for negotiation. No matter whether a lease, purchase, or joint venture is desired, the most certain way to assure failure is to strike an agreement that results in one side believing he agreed to unfair terms or was misinformed about the implications of  the terms. Both participants to a minerals negotiation need to be informed about the negative impacts of overly generous royalties, rapidly accelerating bonus payments or work commitments, onerous earn-in expenditures, and accelerated dilution clauses. Concern for the time implications of the permitting process and the current uncertainties of evolving environmental compliance codes should allow some flexibility in establishing contractual timeframes for completing certain tasks or attaining production.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Building Confidence in Assays:</B><BR>
<I>L. B. Bloom, Analytical Solutions Ltd., Toronto, ON, Canada and D. Titaro, A. C. A. Howe, Toronto, ON, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
In 1996, lack of confidence in assaying methods and sample handling affected companies as diverse as Bre-X and Timbuktu. Both share prices and the ability to raise financing are impacted when the quality of assay data is suspect. Overseas projects are subject to enhanced scrutiny when local facilities are used that are unfamiliar to brokers, financing agencies and banks. Quality control systems can be used to monitor sampling through assays but there are associated costs. These costs should reflect the risk to the mining company, investors and financiers and the size of the proposed investment. Assay control can be considered a form of insurance to enhance the value of an exploration or mining project. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

