<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geology II-Case Histories of Discovery Southeast Asia and Africa
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, C102/104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>S. K. Hamilton, Behre Dolbear & Co., Inc. Denver, CO
<DD>W. M. Shepard, Lakewood, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Discovery and Exploration of the Batu Hijau Deposit, Sumbawa, Indonesia:</B><BR>
<I>B. K. Levet, Newmont Mineral Exploration, Perth, WA, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
The Batu Hijau porphyry copper gold deposit on the island of Sumbawa, in the Sunda-Banda island arc of Indonesia, was detected up to 15 kilometers from a mineralized outcrop by the analysis of active stream sediments using the Bulk Leach Extractable Gold technique and the identification of limited float in the stream. Analysis of <80 mesh stream silts proved to be the most effective method for defining the extent of the anomaly within 1 to 2 kilometers of outcropping mineralization. The deposit was defined by the integration of geological, geochemical and geophysical data sets, and was confirmed by diamond drilling. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Discovery and Exploration of the Gosowong Quartz-adularia Vein Deposit, Halmahera, Eastern Indonesia:</B><BR>
<I>J. C. Carlile, PT Austindo Mining Corp., Jakarta, Indonesia, G. R. Davey, Newcrest Mining Ltd., Jakarta, Indonesia, I. Kadir, PT Aneka Tambang (Persero), Jakarta, Indonesia, R. P. Langmead, Newcrest Mining Ltd., East Perth, WA, Australia and W. J. Rafferty, PT Barrick Gold Corp., Jakarta, Indonesia</I></FONT><BR>
The Gosowong quartz-adularia vein, in the Halmahera magmatic arc, represents a new discovery in an area of primary tropical rain forest with no history of gold mining or mineralization. The newly recognized mineralized district is so far known to contain several other epithermal vein systems, three centers of porphyry Cu-Au mineralization, and a number of argillic and advanced argillic alteration zones. Gosowong was discovered and tested through the application of basic exploration techniques including drainage sampling, soil sampling, trenching, magnetics, IP, and diamond drilling. Lapse time from the initial discovery of a stream sediment anomaly to the release of an inferred resource of approximately 1.0m ounces was just over 3 years.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Exploration Success in the Philippines: The Discovery of the Dinkidi Au-Cu Porphyry, Didipio, Luzon:</B><BR>
<I>J. A. Haggman, Climax Arimco Mining Corp., Makati City, Philippines</I></FONT><BR>
In a country richly endowed in mineral wealth, Climax Arimco Mining Corporation's (CAMC) Dinkidi porphyry Au-Cu deposit located in Barangay Didipio, Neuva Vizcaya, Philippines, represents the most significant mineral discovery in this country in recent times. The deposit is located within a belt of young intrusive and volcanic rocks in the Sierra Madre mountain chain of north Luzon a region previously unassociated with porphyry-style mineralization. A new mining law was passed in March 1995 and earlier CAMC was the first foreign company to be granted a Foreign Technical Assistance Agreement (FTAA)) by the Philippine government allowing 100% foreign ownership of mining projects. Since 1989, drilling of the Dinkidi deposit has outlined a resource of 124 million tons of 1.0 g/t gold and 0.4% copper with regional exploration throughout CAMC's 37,000-hectare FTAA identifying a further sixteen satellite porphyry-related targets. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Siguiri Gold Deposits-Case History of Discovery:</B><BR>
<I>P. R. Davies, Socit Aurifre de Guine, Guinea, West Africa and M. L. Page, Golden Shamrock Mines Inc., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
The Siguiri gold deposits occur in a Lower Proterozoic Birimian meta-sedimentary basin in the northeastern corner of Guinea, West Africa. Lithologies are generally fine grained and volcanics are unknown in the project area. Extensive artisanal gold mining of active high grade alluvials and a defunct mechanized alluvial mining operation highlighted the potential of the Siguiri area. The local affiliate of Golden Shamrock Mines Ltd., Socit Aurifre de Guine, initially trenched and drilled known saprolitic sheeted quartz vein and minor breccia systems and identified 0.5 million ounces by the end of 1994. Orientation laterite lag and follow-up laterite rockchip sampling in December 1994 indicated the potential in the laterite itself. Widely spaced open hole rotary air blast (RAB) drilling quickly outlined the broad dimensions of the mineralization. Aircore and reverse circulation percussion drilling defined the resources, which by April 1995 were estimated at 2.7 million ounces. Step-out drilling of the laterite mineralization has brought current (July 1996) resources to 67.4 mt @ 1.57 g/t Au (3.4 million ounces). Fifty percent of the gold is contained in near surface laterite, and consequently, reserve strip ratios are 1:1. Both in situ and transported, aeriferous laterite profiles are recognized. Several lateritized paleochannel deposits form an annulus around the Kami sheeted vein deposit, the main source of active alluvial gold channels in the area. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Segala Gold Discovery, Mali, West Africa:</B><BR>
<I>R. Thivierge, Oliver Gold Corp., Bamako, Mali and L. L. Duffett and J. R.</I></FONT><BR> Allan, Oliver Gold Corp., Vancouver, BC, Canada
In Mali, Oliver Gold Corp is exploring the Segala gold discovery, occurring within Proterozoic Birimian metasedimentary rocks of the "Keneiba Inlier" which straddles the Mali-Senegal border. The deposit is hosted by a lower greenschist facies turbiditic sequence of greywacke, phyllitic siltstone and argillite which is intruded by felsic plutons and small-scale dykes, northeast trending diabase dykes and a number of kimberlite bodies. Gold mineralization is identified in several zones. Mineralized intervals in the Main Zone are characterized by bleached, iron-carbonate and sericite altered metasediments containing disseminated pyrite and arsenopyrite and a complex network of quartz veinlets. Gold occurs as fine intercrystalline patches and fracture fillings in sulphide minerals, and as coarse visible grains within iron carbonate-quartz veinlets. A preliminary resource of over one million ounces has been calculated in the Main Zone. The 1996 work program and prefeasibility study on the Main and Northwest Zones includes 10,000 meters of diamond drilling to delineate the deposit at shallow to moderate depths, and 10,000 meters of RC drilling to test for supergene mineralization in the laterite and saprolite horizons overlying the zones. Preliminary metallurgical results indicate over 95% gold recovery by a combination of gravity and cyanide leach procedures. Concurrently with the drilling programs, detailed soil geochemical and geophysical surveys are underway to evaluate additional mineralized zones on the property.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Zimbabwe Platinum: The Sleeping Giant Awakes:</B><BR>
<I>P. M. Vanderspuy, Delta Gold N.L., North Sydney, Australia</I></FONT><BR>
The Great Dyke in Zimbabwe, second only after South Africa's Bushveld Igneous Complex as a repository of platinum group metals, was first recognized in the 1860's. Its layered mafic-ultramafic character was recorded in the 1890's and its platinum content was first noted in 1914. Recovery of alluvial platinum was attempted around 1930. In the 1960's and 1970's four separate trial underground mines were established and subsequently suspended for technical and financial reasons. In 1986 Delta Gold started re-evaluating the economic and technical viability of platinum mining on the Great Dyke. In 1990 BHP joined Delta in this evaluation, leading to mine construction between 1994 and 1996, with first production scheduled for early 1997. Initial platinum production from the Hartley Platinum mine will account for 3% of world supply possibly growing to between 10% and 15% of world supply by 2010.</P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

