<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geology III-Recent Copper Developments in Latin America
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, C102/104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. E. Dreier, Mega Metals, Inc., Golden, CO
<DD>D. M. Spatz, BHP Minerals, Tucson, AZ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Geology of the Lomas Bayas and Fortuna de Cobre Porphyry Cu Deposits, Chile:</B><BR>
<I>T. C. Shrake, Gibraltar Mines Ltd., Reno, NV; D. R. Ernst, Gibraltar Mines Ltd., Santiago, Chile; P. Thurston, Girdwood, AK; and J. Ashleman, Spokane, WA</I></FONT><BR>
Lomas Bayas and Fortuna de Cobre are leachable porphyry deposits located in Region II, Chile. The two deposits are 2 km apart. Dacite porphyries intrude a Late Cretaceous granodiorite batholith along a northeasterly strike-slip fault zone. The higher grade hypogene systems are restricted to veins and breccias that are surrounded by very large low-grade shells. The hypogene system was subjected to a long period of enrichment and oxidation. The majority of the copper was contained in various species of copper sulfate. The combined reserve/geologic resource for the deposits total 8.9 billion pounds of contained copper.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Geology of the El Abra Porphyry Copper Deposit, Chile:</B><BR>
<I>R. E. Graichen, Cyprus Amax Minerals Co., Englewood; CO; D. A. Dean, Cyprus Amax Minerals Co., Sparks, NV; and L. F. Barrett, D. K. Christensen; and W. D. Burton, Cyprus Amax Minerals Co., Englewood, CO</I></FONT><BR>
El Abra is a deeply eroded and oxidized, low-sulfide porphyry copper system. Chrysocolla, pseudomalachite and copper clays are the principal oxide ore minerals. A poorly developed chalcocite zone lies at the base of the oxide zone with disseminated chalcopyrite and bornite lying beneath it to beyond 1,000 meters depth. Ore occurs in a potassically altered system of diorite to quartz monzonite intrusives of late Eocene to early Oligocene age. Commonly these rocks appear fresh in hand sample. The deposit is situated within and probably controlled by a wrench fault system related to the nearby West Fissure as are other copper deposits in Northern Chile. Mining of the 798 million ton oxide reserve of 0.54 percent copper began in July, 1996. The oxide deposit economics are related to its continuity and thickness (65 to 350 meters), low stripping and a central high grade zone at the surface. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Geology of the Cerro Verde and Santa Rosa Prophyry Copper Deposits, Arequipa, Peru:</B><BR>
<I>B. Gillies, A. Plazzolles, J. Guillen, L. Prieto, and F. Linares, Sociedad Minera Cerro Verde, Arequipa, Peru</I></FONT><BR>
The Cerro Verde and Santa Rosa deposits, situated 30 km southwest of the Peruvian city of Arequipa, are of the porphyry copper molybdenite type, emplaced in the south segment of the Coastal Batholith, Arequipa section. Similar to the Cuajone, Quellaveco, and Toquepala settings, Cerro Verde is thought to lie along a northwestern splay of the West Fissure, a dominant tectonic feature common to some of the largest copper deposits in northern Chile. Surface copper oxide mineralization had been known for centuries and high grade mining operations were run by various small miners from 1868 until 1916. Since then, the property experienced 3 phases of exploration drilling by Newmont and Anaconda until 1970. Minero Peru constructed a modern treatment facility in the mid seventies and commenced leaching operations in 1977. Cyprus Amax Inc. acquired the operation in 1994 and through an aggressive exploration and development program, has expanded SX/EW production to 48,000 tons of cathode copper, annually.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Cerro Negro-A New Discovery at Cerro Verde:</B><BR>
<I>J. R. Wilson, Cyprus Minera de Panama, Panama City, Panama; T. W. Bidgood, Cyprus Amax Minerals Co., Englewood, CO; W. Loza, and J. Mercado, Sociedad Minera Cerro Verde, Arequipa, Peru; and E. F. S. Downes, Kent, WA</I></FONT><BR>
The Cerro Negro oxide copper deposit is located 3 km southeast of the Cyprus Amax Cerro Verde porphyry copper mine. Cerro Negro is hosted in a distinctive quartz-tourmaline breccia with mineralization and alteration related to the intrusion of quartz-tourmaline breccia bodies along the bounding faults of a 1.5 km near circular, volcano tectonic depression. The Cerro Negro deposit is the largest breccia (300 m by 900 m) and has near vertical contacts with adjacent host rocks. Several breccia phases are recognized. They consist of matrix supported quartz-tourmaline breccias with angular to subrounded fragments of Yarabamba granodiorite. Copper mineralization post dates but is associated with tourmaline and specularite in the quartz-tourmaline breccias. Oxidation occurs to 200 m depth. Chrysocolla, tenorite, malachite, cuprite, and anterlite occur in veinlets, fracture and vug fillings, and as replacement of breccia matrix and fragments. Primary sulfides (pyrite and chalcopyrite) occur in veinlets, fractures, and vug fillings.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Cu-(Au, Ag) Skarn Deposits at Tintaya, Peru:</B><BR>
<I>P. L. Zweng, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The Cu-(Au, Ag) skarn deposits of Tintaya are located in the Yauri district, southern Peru. Calcic skarn forms principally within roof pendants of lower Cretaceous Ferrobamba limestone engulfed in Tertiary monzonite, or along contacts separating limestone from monzonite or diorite. Skarn is spatially associated with K-silicate altered monzonite, and is characterized by diopside skarn replaced by andradite skarn and magnetite replacement bodies. Over 80% of the copper occurs with andradite and magnetite in low-sulfur assemblages, magnetite-bornite, bornite-chalcopyrite, and chalcopyrite. Minor chlorite, epidote, and clay-bearing assemblages containing pyrite-chalcopyrite overprint skam. Unusual features of Tintaya relative to other copper skarans include: (1) poorly developed mineral zonation in skarn; (2) minor hydrolytic alteration, and (3) the abundance of skarn in roof pendants. These features together suggest skarn formed by highly focused fluid flow in a deep environment.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Discovery of the Pierina, Peru, Gold Deposit by Arequipa Resources:</B><BR>
<I>J. D. Lowell, Lowell Mineral Exploration, Rio Rico, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Staged regional exploration in 1995 identified a 400 3 600 meter anomaly averaging 1.6 ppm Au. A grid of 3m deep pits averaged over 6 ppm Au. The deposit was explored by two adits and a 100 3 100m grid of RC and diamond drill holes. A continuous block of ore grade mineralization 1100 3 200-400 by 10-200m deep had been delineated by August, 1996, when Arequipa Resources was acquired by American Barrick. The mineralization occurs in a strongly silicified lithic tuff which overlies feldspar porphyry with strong argillic and sericite alteration. The ore grade varies from one to several grams of Au and 10-200g of Ag. Most of the strong mineralization occurs in vuggy silica. It contains alunite, native sulfur, barite and iron oxide minerals with occasional sparse disseminated pyrite, enargite and covellite. Oxidation may be of hypogene origin. Gold is late stage and very fine grained, and cyanide leach tests indicate it is readily soluble. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

