<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Geology IV-Advance and Transfer of Exploration Technology
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, C102/104/106

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>D. M. Spatz, BHP Minerals, Tucson, AZ
<DD>J. L. Wright, Newmont Exploration Ltd., Carlin, NV
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Remote Sensing into the Twenty-First Century:</B><BR>
<I>D. W. Coulter, Newmont Exploration Ltd., Denver, CO</I></FONT><BR>
Over the past decade, the Landsat based Thematic Mapper has become the remote sensing instrument of choice for mineral exploration applications. As the decade and century draw to a close we are experiencing renewed Interest and growth of satellite remote sensing with more than twenty instruments scheduled for launch by the year 2004. While most of these systems are designed to meet the needs of the civil engineering, agricultural, news gathering, and environmental industries, explorationists will greatly benefit from their capabilities. High resolution radar imagery may already be obtained from Radarsat and we will soon have access to near aerial photographic quality stereo images. Mineral mapping from space will also soon be a reality with one hyperspectral system scheduled for launch and others in the process of being designed. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The LASI High-resolution Electromagnetic Sounding System:</B><BR>
<I>B. K. Sternberg and M. M. Poulton, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
We have developed a series of new electromagnetic (EM) sounding systems at the Laboratory for Advanced Subsurface Imaging (LASI) during the last 6 years. These include low frequency (LF, 30 Hz to 30 kHz), medium frequency (MF, 1 kHz to 1 MHz), and high frequency (HF, 30 kHz to 300 MHz) systems. Applications have included: mapping of plumes of contaminated groundwater, tracing leachate for an in situ leaching operation, locating buried hazardous waste, identifying subsidence-prone zones, and detecting buried voids. These systems are also applicable to exploration for ore bodies. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>GIS-An Exploration Tool: </B><BR>
<I>G. L. Raines, US Geological Survey, Reno, NV and B. R. Johnson, US Geological Survey, Spokane, WA</I></FONT><BR>
A geographical information system (GIS) is a system of computer hardware, software, geographic data, and personnel designed to efficiently capture, store, update, manipulate, analyze and display all forms of geographically referenced data. Two limitations to the geologic application of GIS are availability of digital data and analytical methods. A critical issue of data availability is the lack of digital geologic maps, especially at larger scales. Another issue is the lack of data standards. Significant progress is being made in GIS analytical methods. Recently a new massive sulfide discovery in Canada was predicted using the weights-of-evidence, fuzzy-logic, and other GIS data integration techniques. A weights-of-evidence model for hot springs gold deposits in the Great Basin has provided a mineral assessment comparable to that of an expert team. Estimates of numbers of undiscovered deposits from this model are identical to the estimates of traditional expert teams. Research suggests that which data and how they are used is more important than which analytical method is used to integrate the data. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Geophysics Research, Development and Applications to Mineral Exploration: </B><BR>
<I>K. L. Zonge, Zonge Engineering & Research, Tucson, AZ and C. S. Lide, Zonge Engineering & Research, Sparks, NV</I></FONT><BR>
Research and development in both airborne and ground geophysics has emphasized increased resolution, greater depth of exploration, multi-component measurements, higher productivity and better interpretational tools. These efforts have resulted in microprocessor-based instruments which have more channels, better noise rejection, lower power consumption, and are smaller and lighter than instruments available 5 years ago. The decrease in size and weight of the instrumentation is important to geoophysical exploration in remote areas. Algorithms for automated construction of depth sections have become relatively standard for many techniques and provide a complement to standard psuedosection presentation of data. Development is continuing on 2D and 3D modeling and inversion algorithms. Increased effectiveness in mineral exploration provided by these recent advancements is demonstrated by case studies. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recruiting and Training for Exploration: Changing Times, Changing Needs: </B><BR>
<I>N. C. White, BHP Minerals Int'l. Exploration, Sparks, NV</I></FONT><BR>
The world is opening up to explorers. We have more technology, and better understanding of mineralization than ever before. Global explorers need a command of both advanced and simple methods. They need to understand their targets, alternative exploration techniques, and logistical, legal, economic, environmental and social factors. An interdisciplinary approach is increasingly essential. Lack of jobs discourages students from training for the industry, so there are fewer schools producing graduates. The quality and number of graduates is declining and this is made worse by adverse social attitudes. Industry expectations of new graduates vary widely. Companies with strong commitment to training want graduates with basic academic skills to train on the job. Others want graduates already trained in operations. So the remaining schools have the problem of who to try to satisfy. In some third world countries there are well-trained graduates. However, their training commonly lacks practical experience and industry awareness. Quality recruits are available, but they need training and supervision. Present trends will continue unless the industry changes them. We allowed some of the problems to develop; only we can fix them. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Laterite Development and Gold Mineralization at Siguiri, NE Guinea-Genetic and Exploration Models: </B><BR>
<I>P. R. Davies, Socit Aurifre de Guine, Guinea, West  Africa</I></FONT><BR>
Lateritic weathering over perhaps the past 70 million years has dominated the Siguiri region in northeastern Guinea. Erosion has produced a complex regolith of partially preserved residual and transported material, and commonly inverted relief. In situ laterite gold mineralization occurs in the ferruginous part of the weathering profile above saprolite and fresh rock mineralization. Gold content is often higher near surface due to volume reduction caused by silica and carbonate loss during weathering. Grades are smoothed by hydromorphic dispersion in the lower part of the ferruginous zone. Profiles can be recognized by the presence of fragmental duricrust at surface, and underlying vermiform duricrust grading down to mottled clays and ferruginous saprolite. Transported laterite mineralization occurs as aprons of clay-rich colluvial or palaeochannel gravel derived from a now eroded in situ laterite profile previously developed over bedrock mineralization. Profiles contain downward fining lateritic pebbles, cutens on lateritic pisoliths, underlying transported clays, and basal quartz and lateritic boulder beds. The palaeochannels may be subsequently lateritized, with the clay matrix duricrusted up to 10 meters deep above a mottled zone, producing a profile similar to the in situ type. Gold grades are enhanced and further smoothed in this event, but drop with decreasing iron content and increasing depth in the profile. Higher grades may occur at the base of the duricrust and in the quartz boulder beds. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

