<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Concentration I-Environmental Aspects of Dewatering and Drying
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, A112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>R. Seitz, J. M. Huber Corp, Atlanta GA
<DD>J. Groppo, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY
</DL>


<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Filtration Studies of Wet Processed Fly Ash:</B><BR>
<I>J. G. Groppo and T. L. Robl, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY and C. H. J. McCormick, Advanced Pozzolan Technologies, Inc., Atlanta, GA</I></FONT><BR>
Froth flotation has been demonstrated to be an effective method for selective separation of unburned carbon from high LOI fly ash, particularly ponded ashes. Although fly ash is quite fine (-325 mesh) it demonstrates unique filtration characteristics. The results of laboratory batch and continuous vacuum filtration studies will be presented. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Predicting the Moisture Content of Coals Dewatered by Screens:</B><BR>
<I>B. J. Arnold, CQ Inc., Homer City, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Utility coal specifications usually contain a requirement for a maximum moisture content in order to prevent handling problems and to minimize evaporative losses in the boiler. As most coal cleaning processes are water-based, dewatering and sometimes drying steps are required to meet moisture specifications. Screens are often used for dewatering, with centrifuges and filters used to further reduce moisture in many cases. Algorithms to predict the performance of commercial dewatering devices were developed for the Coal Cleaning Simulator running under Aspen Plus during a project sponsored by the US Department of Energy and the Electric Power Research Institute. This paper discusses the algorithm for predicting the moisture content of coal dewatered by screens. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Use of Fly Ash as a Binder for Iron Ore Pellets:</B><BR>
<I>T. C. Eisele and S. K. Kawatra, Michigan Technological University, Houghton, MI</I></FONT><BR>
The US iron-ore industry consumes approximately 560,000 tons of bentonite clay binders every year, most of which is shipped from Wyoming to the Great Lakes region at considerable expense. There is therefore incentive for finding a more local alternative to bentonite for this application. In this project the use of various coal fly ashes as binders for iron-ore pellets has been studied.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development of the Outokumpu Pressure Filter at Outokumpu Tara Mines:</B><BR>
<I>D. O'Murchu, Outokumpu Tara Mines, Navan, Ireland</I></FONT><BR>
Outokumpu Tara Mines located near Dublin, Ireland is Europes largest producer of lead and zinc concentrates. To reduce dewatering costs and to improve environmnetal and working conditions, elimination of the lead concentrate thermal dryer was required. This paper describes the development and implementation of the pressure ceramic technology at Tara to replace a conventinal vacuum filter/oil-fired dryer system. The pressure ceramic filter is currently dewatering 80,000 tons/year of lead concentrate, producing a cake with less than 6% moisture. Substantial operating cost savings have been realized. Commissioning of a second pressure ceramic filter to handle over 300,000 tons/year of zinc concentrates is scheduled for the first quarter of 1997.</P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

