<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Mineral Processing Fundamentals-Dewatering and Dispersion
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, A108/110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>B. K. Parekh, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY
<DD>J. E. Gebhardt, Process Engineering Resources, Inc., Salt Lake City, UT
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Polymer Flocculation and Coagulation for Sedimentation of Copper Flotation Tailings: </B><BR>
<I>F. F. Peng and Z. L. Lu, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
Employing the combination of two polymers might become necessary to enhance both settling rate and water clarity of fine particle suspension in high capacity thickening process. The effects of pH, feed rate, polymer dosage, the sequence and number of polymer additions end rake speed on the settling rate, underflow solid, and water clarity were studied in a dynamic thickening device with adequate mixing feature and various polymer addition points. The results were evaluated quantitatively, using supernatant total solid suspension and settling rate as the measure of effectiveness. The purpose of this paper is to quantify and explain some of the parameters involved in the sedimentation of copper flotation tailings. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Ultra Low Dosage Flocculation of Alumina Suspensions Using Polyacrylic Acid: </B><BR>
<I>K. K. Das and P. Somasundaran, Columbia University, New York, NY and Pradip, Tata Research Development & Design Center., Pune, India</I></FONT><BR>
Flocculation experiments have been conducted on alumina suspensions using different molecular weight polyacrylic acids. In the absence of polymer maximum settling of alumina suspension occurred near its point of zero charge (~pH 9). Under all pH conditions as expected, while low molecular weight (average MW 5000) polyacrylic acid effectively dispersed the alumina suspensions, polymers of higher molecular weight (50000 and above) resulted in flocculation. The effect of pH, ionic strength, dosage and solid/liquid ratio was studied. Surprisingly marked flocculation was obtained with parts per billion (ppb) level polymer dosage. Also interestingly at such ultra-low dosages a minimum in flocculation was observed at ~pH 4.5 close to the reported pKa of polyacrylic acid. Zeta potential studies did not reveal any significant change in the electrokinetics of alumina suspensions due to low dosage addition of polyacrylic acid. It suggests that fewer than 10 molecules per particle might be sufficient to obtain the desired flocculation if the polymer is introduced efficiently.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Adhesion of Mycobacterium phlei to Hydrophobic and Hydrophilic Mineral: </B><BR>
<I>A. K. Mouat, Carroll College, Helena, MT and A. M. Raichur, R. W. Smith and M. Mishra, University of Nevada, Reno, NV</I></FONT><BR>
The adhesion of Mycobacterium phlei onto minerals processing different degrees of hydrophobicity (hematite, stibnite, coal, talc, orpiment, graphite and molybdenite) was studied by zeta potential, contact angle and flocculation measurements. The bacterium strain studied exhibited a contact angle of 68-70 degrees. The minerals studied exhibited contact angles between 0 and 70 degrees. In general, the magnitude of the contact angle on the minerals, both with and without the presence of M. phlei, was a function of pH. The flocculation of the various mineral suspensions was roughly related to the observed contact angle on the minerals. In general, the less hydrophobic the mineral, the greater was the effect of the bacterium on contact angle and flocculation. An attempt is made to relate the interaction of the minerals and M. phlei, as expressed in the accompanying change in contact angle and flocculation of the minerals, to extended DLVO theory. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Enhanced Vacuum Filtration for Ultrafine Coal Dewatering: </B><BR>
<I>D. P. Tao, J. G. Groppo and B. K. Parekh, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY</I></FONT><BR>
The vacuum filtration was investigated for ultrafine coal dewatering on laboratory- and pilot-scale. It has been shown that enhanced dewatering of ultrafine coals can be achieved with vacuum filtration by modifying surface properties of coal particles. Filter cake containing less than 20% moisture can be obtained by use of flocculants, surfactants, metal ions, or a combination of them. In situ polymerization was explored as a novel process for coal dewatering that can substantially reduce the cake moisture. The effectiveness of coal dewatering was evaluated under various conditions and mechanisms responsible for enhanced dewatering discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Centrifugal Dewatering and Reconstitution of Fine Coal: The GranuFlow Process: </B><BR>
<I>W. W. Wen and R. P. Killmeyer, Pittsburgh Energy Technology Center, Pittsburgh, PA</I></FONT><BR>
A continuous bench-scale testing of a GranuFlow Process was conducted on both high-g force solid-bowl and screen-bowl centrifuges for dewatering and reconstitution of fine-clean-coal slurry at 300 lb/h by the Pittsburgh Energy Technology Center. In this process fine-clean-coal slurry was treated with a bitumen emulsion. In one example, the treated products from a solid-bowl centrifuge appeared to be dry and in a free-flowing granular form, while the untreated products were wet, lumpy, sticky, and difficult to handle. Specifically, test results from the solid-bowl centrifuge indicated that the moisture content, handleability, and dust reduction of the dewatered coal product improved as the addition of emulsion increased from 2 wt% to 8 wt%. Because of the moisture reduction and the granular form of the product, the freezing problem was also alleviated. The preliminary cost estimation of using Orimulsion in the GranuFlow Process was also included. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Comparison of Pressure and Vacuum Filtration of Ultrafine Clean Coal Slurry-A Pilot Scale Study: </B><BR>
<I>J. G. Groppo and B. K. Parekh, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY</I></FONT><BR>
Pilot scale dewatering tests were conducted at the Powell Mountain Coal Company's Mayflower Preparation Plant located in St. Charles, VA, using Andritz Hyperbaric Filter (HBF) and WesTech's vacuum drum filter. The feed to the filter was from the Ken-Flote' columns with an average particle size of 25 microns. The HBF provided a dewatered product containing 23.6 percent moisture. The optimum operating conditions of the HBF filter were: 165 cake formation angle, air consumption 460 scf/t, air pressure 3 bar (43 psi) and solids throughput of 34 Kg/m2-hr. The vacuum drum filter provided 27 percent moisture filter cake at a solids throughput of 5 Kg/m2-hr. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

