<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Pyrometallurgy
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, A105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>W. F. Schwartz, Fuller Mineral Processing, Bethlehem, PA
<DD>R. P. Faulkner, Allis Chalmer Corp., Milwaukee, WI
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Pyro Process for the Production of Lightweight Aggregate from Fly Ash and Wastewater Sludge: </B><BR>
<I>D. M. Conner, Svedala Industries, Inc., Waukesha, WI</I></FONT><BR>
An innovative patented process has been developed to convert high volume wastes-fly ash from coal-fired power plants, municipal solid waste (MSW) ash from incineration, solids from wastewater treatment and paper mill sludge-into a high value and environmentally benign product in the form of a lightweight aggregate. Lightweight aggregate is widely used in the building construction industry in the United States, Europe and some Asian countries. This paper will present the development of the process, the process itself and details on the first commercial-scale plant. The commercial plant is owned and operated by Wisconsin Electric Power. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Thermal Plasma Processing of Materials: </B><BR>
<I>P. R. Taylor and E. E. Vidal, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID</I></FONT><BR>
The use of thermal plasma in materials processing industries is becoming an increasingly active and attractive field for the development of new technology. The potential applications of thermal plasma processing technology cover a wide range of activities, such as: the extraction of metals, the refining/alloying of metals/alloys, the synthesis of fine ceramic powders, spray coatings and the consolidation and destruction of hazardous wastes. A review of thermal plasma applications in materials processing is presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Thermal Processing of Industrial Minerals, Profitable Value Migration: </B><BR>
<I>M. W. Ginn, Ginn Mineral Technology, Inc., Sandersville, GA</I></FONT><BR>
Thermal processing of industrial minerals adds profit to the manufacturer and value to the customer. This concept known as "Value-added Processing" is one of the most strategic goals of industrial mIneral producers. Calcination of industrial mInerals, such as kaolin, adds value to pigments for the paper industries and functional fillers for the refractory and plastic industries. Accounting principals using EVA concepts, demonstrate the economic advantages and encourage the application of value-added processing. Advanced thermal processing technology combined with new operating models and business designs are key drivers for profitable value migration in industrial minerals. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The GRATE-CAR System Process Design and Commercialization:</B><BR>
<I>D. W. Rierson, Svedala Industries, Waukesha, WI</I></FONT><BR>
Svedala has a ported kiln process, designed specifically for the direct reduction of pelletized or natural lump iron ores. The process is called ACCAR. This ported kiln technology has been coupled with Svedala's GRATE KILN-System, for iron ore pelletizing, into the GRATE-CAR System for the reduction of the fine grained ore concentrates through the steps of agglomeration, induration and reduction in a single production line. Svedala conducts tests to confirm certain operating parameters of various ores through process simulations of the GRATE-CAR System. Svedala has also assessed the issues of process variables, heat transfer, equipment sizing, retention time and endothermic demand associated with the reduction process. Information is also provided on a 300,000 tpy commercial GRATE-CAR System operating on ilmenite concentrate. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Toxic Elements Removal from Copper Smelter Discard Slags:</B><BR>
<I>R. G. Reddy and G. P. Singh, The University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL</I></FONT><BR>
Copper smelter discard slags contain significant quantities of As, Sb and Bi elements. From the slags dumps, over a period of time, these elements center hydrosphere and atmosphere. Since all the three elements are harmful to human life, it is warranted to minimize their release into the environment. A study was undertaken to reduce to quantities of these elements in the discard slags by a combination of high temperature carbothermic and sulfide treatment of industrial Cu smelter discard slags. Slags samples were treated with C and FeS in the temperature range of 13738 to 15738 K. A low grade matte high in these metals was produced. Removal of metals from slags increased with increase in the time of treatment, temperature and the addition of CaO, SiO2, and CaF2 to the slags. With the addition of 4 wt% CaO to the slag, the maximum removal of As, Bi and Sb were 79%, 37% and 68% respectively were obtained. Based on the present study, key factors which influence the environmentally safer disposal of industrial Cu smelter slags were identified. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

