<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Concentration II-Waste Utilization and Recycling in Mineral Processing
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:30 AM, A112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>R. Honaker, Southern Illinois University, Carbondale, IL
<DD>M. Mankosa, Carpco, Inc., Jacksonville, FL
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Volume Reduction of Radionuclide-contaminated Soils Using Mineral Processing Technologies:</B><BR>
<I>G. H. Luttrell and G. T. Adel, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA and R. T. Burchett and C. R. Phillips, Sanford Cohen & Assoc., Montgomery, AL</I></FONT><BR>
Considerable attention has been given to the restoration of low-level radioactive (<1000 pCi/gm) sites that were contaminated during the early years of the atomic energy program. Current cleanup activities which involve the relocation of contaminated soils to licensed disposal sites have been shown to be very costly due to the large volumes of soil which must be excavated, transported, and stored. Recent characterization studies conducted at Virginia Tech suggest that the volume of soil requiring disposal can be greatly reduced by mineral processing operations such as hydroclassification, density separation, and froth flotation. This article describes the application of these technologies for soil remediation and provides examples of commercial-scale flowsheets for two contaminated sites located in the eastern US.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Application of Mineral Processing Techniques for Secondary Materials Recovery:</B><BR>
<I>M. J. Mankosa and P. Venkatraman, Carpo, Inc., Jacksonville, FL</I></FONT><BR>
Recent work conducted at Carpco has evaluated the use of standard mineral processing techniques for secondary materials recovery. These have included silica, chromite and zircon foundry sands, fly ash, plastics and secondary metals. Pilot-scale test work has focused specifically on metal recovery from chopped wire waste material. As a result of the wire chopping process, a waste by product is generated which contains various types of plastic (PVC, PE, etc). aluminum flake and copper wire. The latter two components can consist of up to 10-20% (by weight) of the bulk material. Carpco has developed a gravity concentration technique for the recovery of both the plastic and metal by products. This paper will present results from pilot-scale design tests as well as operation data from a recently installed full-scale recovery system. Applications of other separation techniques on waste material will also be presented. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Upgrading Products with Rising Current Classifiers:</B><BR>
<I>S. O'Brien, Linatex, Inc., Gallatin, TN and M. Paganon, Linatex Canada, Inc., Montreal, PQ, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
Rising current classifiers have long been utilized in the industrial minerals and sands industry to provide very sharp classifications in somewhat difficult to classify size ranges. Although they have also been used to a affect gravity separations in the past, recent case studies in iron ore processing and environmental remediation are given. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Resource Recovery an Option for the Treatment of Industrial Wastes:</B><BR>
<I>S. K. Mishra, TETRA Technologies, Inc., The Woodlands, TX</I></FONT><BR>
With the increasing regulatory pressure from the environmental authorities, waste management has become a focal point of industrial operation. To offset the waste management cost, industry has made conscious effort to recover usable resources from the waste streams. This paper reviews technological developments and current practices in the processing of waste materials. Method for recovering metallic, non-metallic and organic species from solid wastes and effluents generated by operating plants are discussed. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>SUPAFLO High Compression Thickener Optimizes Autoclaving at Barrick Goldstrike:</B><BR>
<I>L. Enloe, P. Wilmont, and M. Gordon, Outokumpu Mintec USA, Englewood, CO</I></FONT><BR>
A higher density feed than was currently being produced was required to de-bottleneck the operation of the refractory ore treating autoclaves at Barrick Gold's Goldstrike mill. This was to ensure efficient oxidation conditions and to maximize throughput for a proposed upgrade. To achieve the ultra-high density feed material, a Supaflo "High Compression" thickener was installed, following pilot plant testwork at site. The pilot plant data is compared to the full scale results. Commissioning and operation of the 30 m High Compression Thickener is reviewed. In particular methods for detecting and prevention of "donut" formation in the thickener bed are presented.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Laboratory Baffled-column Flotaton of Mixed Campbell Creek/Eagle Seam Bituminious Coal:</B><BR>
<I>J. T. Donnett, S. K. Kawatra, and T. C. Rao, Michigan Technological University, Houghton, MI</I></FONT><BR>
This study investigates the use of horizontally-baffled column (7.6 cm inside diameter by 344.2 cm high) to reduce the ash content of a low sulfur bituminious coal. The feed coal contained 43.1% ash, 0.80% total sulfur was 80% bassine 80 nm, and had a heating value of 8379 BTU/lb. The column had 11 horizontal baffles installed above the feed inlet and 15 below. In this paper, the results of this investigation will be reviwed and discussed. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

