<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Mineral Processing Fundamentals-Flotation
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:30 AM , A108/110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. S. Laskowski, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada
<DD>D. Nagaraj, Cytec Industries, Stamford, CT
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Interaction Between Physical and Chemical Variables in Flotation in Low Rank Coals: </B><BR>
<I>S. Chander and H. Polat, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Relatively large amounts of such hydrocarbons as fuel oils are often needed in flotation of low rank coals. The amount of oil can be decreased considerably by using surfactants as promoters. The reagents which are good candidates as surfactants to promote hydrophobicity can also act as emulsifying and wetting agents. Since the physical and chemical variables influence various sub-processes in different ways, their influence on the performance variables in complex. The results of laboratory tests are presented to show that the duel role of reagents can be judiciously exploited to increase both the recovery and grade of clean coal. The mode and order of reagent addition is critical in enhancing their efficacy as flotation promoters. The results demonstrate the benefits of proper conditioning of the pulp prior to flotation.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Sphalerite Activation: Flotation and Electrokinetic Studies:</B><BR>
<I>J. S. Laskowski, Q. Liu and Y. Zhan, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
Sphalerite is commonly floated in alkaline environment, and under such conditions the overall activation mechanism is obscured by the hydrolysis of Cu2+ and precipitation of Cu (OH)2. The electrokinetic and kinetic flotation tests showed that the activation of sphalerite is a two-stage process; the activation products formed on the surface of sphalerite in a near neutral and in alkaline solutions in the first rapid activation stage are "flotation-inactive." These layers, when formed in an alkaline solution, are unstable and are transformed into the "flotation-active" form in the second stage. However, the surface layers formed during activation in alkaline environment by copper in the presence of lead ions are very stable and even after a long conditioning time the flotation rate is not improved. Consequently, while both Cu2+ and Pb2+ activate sphalerite flotation, quite unpredictable effects may result when both are present in the solution. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>First-order Flotation Rate Equation Incorporating Hydrodynamic and Surface Forces: </B><BR>
<I>R. H. Yoon, and L. Mao, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
A first flotation rate equation was derived by incorporating both hydrodynamic and surface forces. The hydrodynamic forces were calculated using an appropriate stream function, while the surface forces were calculated using the extended DLVO Theory which considers long-range interactions due to electrostatic force, retarded van der Waals force and hydrophobic force. The model was verified in flotation experiments conducted using well-defined methylated glass spheres. The experimental work was conducted using a single-bubble flotation apparatus, so that contributions from hydrodynamic forces can be calculated. Effects of pH and particle hydrophobicity were investigated. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Measurement and Application of Zeta Potential in Kaolin Processing:</B><BR>
<I>J. Yuan and R. J. Pruett, ECC Intl. Sandersville, GA</I></FONT><BR>
In kaolin processing, separation of impurity minerals such as anatase is often difficult and complicated due largely to the extremely fine particle size of clay. Separation mechanism has been explained using surface properties such as zeta potential. This study focused on determining zeta potential of different types of Georgia kaolin clays and understanding the relationship between zeta potential and the behavior of clays in mineral separation processes. Surface phenomena which reflect conditions at the solid-liquid interface will be discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Anionic Flotation of Apatite, Dolomite and Phosphate Rock Modified by the Presence of a Bacterium: </B><BR>
<I>X. Zheng, R. W. Smith, R. K. Mehta, A. M. Raichur and M. Misra, University of Nevada, Reno, NV</I></FONT><BR>
Experimentation was performed on the flotation of apatite and dolomite separately using anionic collectors in the presence of Mycobacterium phlei. Also, the flotation of mixtures of dolomite and apatite in the presence of anionic collectors and in the absence and presence of the bacterium, was studied. It was found that M. phlei functioned as a depressant for both minerals. However, it functioned as a better depressant for dolomite than for apatite. Experimentation was extended to two different Florida dolomitic phosphate rocks. In this investigation a concentrate grade of less than 1.0% MgO could be achieved. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Wetting Francolite and Quartz by Fuel Oil and Its Significance in the Flotation of Phosphate Rock: </B><BR>
<I>Y. Lu, J. Drelich and J. D. Miller, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
Water contact angles in the fuel oil/water/fracolite and the fuel oil/water/quartz systems were measured to describe the wetting characteristics of these minerals. It was found that fracolite is readily wetted by fuel oil, as indicated by a large receding water contact angle of 100 to 120 degrees. In contrast, the fuel oil droplet did not attach at clean quartz surfaces. More interestingly, thin films of fuel oil formed at the fracolite surface are fairly stable, but such films are completely unstable at the quartz surface. Fatty acid dissolved in the aqueous phase helps the fuel oil drops spread at the francolite surface but has negligible effect on the wetting properties of clean quartz surfaces. Based on these experimental results, the significance of high solids conditioning for effective phosphate flotation in the presence of collector and fuel oil is discussed. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

