<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Plant Design and Practice I - Plant Modifications
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 9:30 AM, A105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>M. LeVier, Newmont Gold Co., Denver, CO
<DD>R. Nendick, Fluor Daniel Wright Ltd., Vancouver, BC Canada
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Developments at Southern Peru Copper Corporation's (SPL) Concentrator: </B><BR>
<I>J. Enriquez, R. Llerena, S. Meik, T. Olsen, M. Paco and F. Villasante, Southern Peru Copper Corp., Tacna, Peru</I></FONT><BR>
SPL operates two mine and concentrator facilities at Toquepala and Cuajone, 24 km apart on the western side of the Andes mountains in Southern Peru. Toquepala commenced operations in 1959 at a design production rate of 33,500 tpd and Cuajone in 1976 at 45,000 tpd. Throughput levels have steadily increased to offset decreasing ore head grades to the current levels of 50,000 and 64,000 tpd respectively. This has been achieved with the original installed equipment, an equipment modernization program, together with improved utilization of availability and changes in operating philosophy. The evolution of these, the retrofitting program, and current operating performance will be described in the paper. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mining Equipment Reliability Improvement at Barrick Goldstrike:</B><BR>
<I>D. Bleazard, D. Hepler, and  L. Dearman, Barrick Goldstrike, Elko, NV</I></FONT><BR>
The maintenance organizations at the Barrick Goldstrike Mine are actively involved in increasing the reliability of mining and processing equipment, resulting in improved equipment availability and an overall reduction in operating costs. Equipment failures are investigated to determine what can be done to reduce or eliminate the failures by either making changes in management practices, equipment design, and/or utilizing Predictive Maintenance (PdM) Technologies. When the appropriate PdM Technology has been identified application procedures and inspection frequencies are determined to monitor the condition of the equipment. The information that is obtained from the PdM inspection is then used to optimize maintenance activities. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Process Improvements at SAMITRI (Brazil) using Derrick Screens:</B><BR>
<I>S. B. Valine, Derrick Corp., Buffalo, NY and J. R. V. Furtado, G. Martins, D. L. V. Policarpo and F. C. da S. Quintao, SA Mineracao da Trindade, SAMITRI MG, Brazil</I></FONT><BR>
Major Brazilian iron ore producer, S. A. Mineracao da Trindade (SAMITRI), has recently completed modifications at two operations which involve the use of Derrick high frequency vibrating screens. Details of these modifications are presented, together with a review of product quality improvements. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Zarafshan/Newmont Joint Venture Muruntau Heap Leach Operation-A Case History: </B><BR>
<I>T. B. Acton, Newmont Gold, Denver, CO and S. Acar, Newmont Metallurgical Services, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The Zarafshan/Newmont Joint Venture is currently operating in the Republic of Uzbekistan producing in excess of 400,000 oz. of gold per year from low grade oxide gold ore stockpiles from the adjacent Muruntau open pit gold mine. Four stage crushing and screening produces the final product for heap leaching. Merrill-Crowe processing and local refining for International market export. Much has been learned during start-up and subsequent operations. Early technical and other problems have been overcome by the combined efforts of both partners.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Review of the Amax Guanaco Gold Mine: </B><BR>
<I>K. Norris, Compania Mineral Amax Guanaco, Antofagasta, Chile and S. Busby, Amax Gold Inc., Englewood, CO </I></FONT><BR>
This paper is an overview of the Amax Guanaco gold/silver mine located in the Atacama Desert approximately 260 kilometers south-east of Antofagasta, Chile, South America. Amax Guanaco is a 6,500 ton/day gold and silver heap leach operation producing approximately 90,000 ounces of gold and 360,000 ounces of silver per year. The paper reviews the process flowsheet, operations during the last three years, and current efforts to enhance profitability.

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

