<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Gravity Concentration of Gold, Modern Milling Practices
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, A108/110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>E. H. Bentzen III, Mineral Technologies, Golden, CO
<DD>D. E. Spiller, Newmont Metallurgical Services, Salt Lake City, UT
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Resurgence of Gravity Concentration at the Golden Giant Mine:</B><BR>
<I>J. A. Cormier and S. G. Honan, Battle Mountain Canada Golden Giant Mine, Marathon, ON, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
In July 1992 a gravity circuit was installed in the grinding circuit at Battle Mountain's Golden Giant Mine. Today, the gravity circuit produces over 25% of the total gold produced. A review of the reasons for the installation will be discussed as well as problems encountered and the solutions employed during the operation of the gravity circuit. The cost savings will be presented along with the history of metallurgical improvements. Future circuit modifications and the expected ramifications on the performance of the gravity circuit will be examined. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recovery of Gold by Gravity Separation a the Greens Creek Mine Alaska: </B><BR>
<I>R. J. Sawyer, Kennecott Corp. Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The Greens Creek underground polymetallic mine located on Admiralty Island in south east Alaska commenced operations in 1989 and was shut-down due to low metal prices in April 1993. Production restarted in 1996 from a newly discovered higher grade ore zone. The mill produces lead, zinc and bulk lead-zinc flotation concentrates containing high values of gold and silver. The ore mineralology is quite variable depending on the particular stope being mined. Gold is present as electrum and also as finely disseminated inclusions within the the sulfide matrix. Efforts to improve overall payable gold recovery have focused on the application of gravity separation. This paper describes the testwork leading up to the installation of a new gravity circuit and compress testwork and plant operating results. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Gravity Concentration at the Campbell Mine: </B><BR>
<I>J. A. Folinsbee, Placer Dome Canada, Balmertown, ON, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
Placer Dome Canada operates the Campbell Mine at Balmertown, in the north western corner of the province of Ontario. The mine operates at 1500 stpd and produces in excess of 300,000 ounces of gold annually. Recent changes to the gravity concentration circuit have resulted in a 10-15% increase in gravity recovery. The focus of this presentation will be on the changes that have contributed to this improvement. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Knelson Concentrator Aids in Processing Shift from Silver to Gold Production: </B><BR>
<I>C. L. McKenzie, Kinross Delamar Mining Co., Jordan Valley, OR</I></FONT><BR>
The Kincross DeLamar Mine has been operated for more than 17 years producing precious metals dore' from ores, principally silver bearing with associated gold coproducts. In late 1995 a new orebody was commissioned, the Stone Cabin orebody, and the site began a phased shift from silver dominance to gold dominance in terms of precious metals revenue. The Knelson Concentrator was selected to remove gold from a portion of the cyclone underflow stream in the grinding circuit. This paper describes the development of the flow sheet, specific mineralogical impacts on Knelson product and downstream materials, and impact on mine/mill grade reconciliation. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

