<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Metallurgical Processing Fundamentals I - Precious Metals
</I></FONT><BR>

Tuesday, February 25, 2:00 PM, A112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chairs:</B>
<DD>B. Pesic, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID
<DD>C. A. Young, Montana Tech of the University of Montana, Butte, MT
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Leaching Behavior of Rhenium in Ammonium Iodide/Iodine Solutions: </B><BR>
<I>D. Hong, X. Meng and K. N. Han, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
The leaching behavior of rhenium in ammonium iodide solutions with iodine as oxidant has been studied. Experiments were carried out in an autoclave. The effect of stirring speed, temperature, pH of the solution, iodine and iodide concentrations on the dissolution of rhenium was investigated. It was found that high temperature and high pH of the solution was essential for the efficient leaching of rhenium. The dissolution rate was found to be dependent upon the concentration of iodine and iodide. It was concluded that the dissolution of rhenium under the conditions studied was controlled by mass transfer with the apparent activation energy of 6.6 kJ/mole. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Leaching Behavior of Palladium in Ammoniacal Solution with Oxygen: </B><BR>
<I>X. Meng and K. N. Han, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
The leaching behavior of palladium in ammoniacal solutions has been investigated using the rotating disk technique in an autoclave. The study included the effect of rotating speed, temperature, oxygen pressure, composition of ammoniacal solutions and catalyst on the overall leaching rate. The dissolution of palladium in ammoniacal solutions was discussed in view of the thermodynamics and a kinetic model. Even though the potential-pH diagram suggested that palladium metal can dissolve in ammoniacal solutions at room temperature, it was found that the dissolution was too slow at temperatures below 100C but was significantly improved at higher temperatures. It was also found that the rotating speed of palladium disk had no effect on the leaching rate. The apparent activation energy was found to be 69.7 kJ/mole. Based on the results obtained, it is concluded that the dissolution of palladium is controlled by a chemical reaction. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Microbilogical Oxidation of CdS Concentrate: </B><BR>
<I>R. G. Reddy, University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL and A. E. Torma, AMROT Intl., Rio Rancho, NM</I></FONT><BR>
The microbilogical oxidation of cadmium sulfide concentrate was investigated using Thiobacillus ferrooxidans. The oxidation rates of CdS concentrate (particle size -200 mesh) were determined as a function of pulp density (2 to 20%) and temperature (20 to 40C). The experimental results showed that the rate of oxidation of CdS increased with increase in temperature and also increased with increase in pulp density. The solubilization of CdS was found to be about 20 times faster with T. ferrooxidan relative to the sterile controls. A possible mechanism was proposed for the T. ferrooxidan bacterium oxidation of CdS. It was concluded that the biooxidation of cadmium sulfide is an effective and practical method for cadmium extraction. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Bioleaching of Chalcopyrite Ores and Concentrates: </B><BR>
<I>R. Winby, BacTech Ltd., Belmont, WA, Australia and C. L. Brierley, VistaTech Partnership, Ltd., Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
This paper will report the results of bioleaching various chalcopyrite ores and concentrates to solubilize copper. The bioleaching results of different ores will be compared and estimated capital and operating costs of commercial-scale operations will be given. This paper will also report results of arsenic removal by selective precipitation. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Air Sweep Efficiency During Sulfide Mineral Biooxidation in Forced-air Ventilated Ore Heaps: </B><BR>
<I>K. A. Prisbrey and R. W. Bartlett, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID</I></FONT><BR>
When the rate of biooxidation of sulfide minerals in an ore heap is limited by oxygen availability, the process can be accelerated by ventilating the heap with air, blown through pipes from fans. Air flow streamlines and stream functions were computed for a heap, having homogeneous and isotropic intrinsic permeability, with air injected at equal rates from equally spaced injectors located at the bottom of the heap. Air sweep efficiency includes both oxygen utilization and the extent of mineral oxidation over time. Results are presented as a function of injector spacing, heap height, air blowing rate and the time-dependent oxygen demand rate. The oxygen demand rate depends on the sulfide mineral concentration and grain size in the ore and its intrinsic oxidation kinetics. Typical values for fine grained pyritic ores, such as refractory gold ores, are used for example calculations.  

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Adsorption of Gold-Thiourea Complex onto a Strong Cation Exchange Resin: </B><BR>
<I>R. K. Mensah-Biney, North Carolina State University, Asheville, NC</I></FONT><BR>
Adsorption of gold-thiourea complex onto a cation exchange resin, Amberlite 252, was evaluated in a batch stirred reactor. The data were modeled after the Freundlich isotherm and the observed saturation absorption capacity was about 3.20 meg Au/g dry resin (620 kg/t). Adsorption of the gold-complex decreased with increasing temperature and increasing thiourea concentration. The correlation between initial gold concentration and adsorption capacity was not conclusive. Scanning electron microscopy revealed evidence of deposition of elemental gold on the loaded resin. The proposed mechanism for "adsorption" of gold-thiourea complex consists of an ion exchange followed by a reduction of the gold complex to elemental gold. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Pilot Testing of DuPont Activator Technology at the Homestake Mine, South Dakota: </B><BR>
<I>J. S. Thompson, DuPont, Wilmington, DE, H. Hinds, D. Donelon, Homestake Mining Co., Lead, SD, S. D. Procaccini, DuPont Specialty Chemicals, Wilmington, DE, G. P. Marshall, DuPont, Wilmington, DE and R. E. Jenkins, DuPont Specialty Chemicals, Wilmington, DE</I></FONT><BR>
Increased gold leaching rates and higher gold recovery were demonstrated with DuPont's activator technology in a plant test at the Homestake mine in Lead, South Dakota. Activators are nitrogen and sulfur aromatic heteroacrylic compounds which catalyze the gold dissolution reaction in cyanide and other lixiviants. The test was run in the west sand plant alternating control and activated vats. Activated vats had gold in the preg solutions earlier, higher gold recovery, and lower residues. Optimization of the technology continues.

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

