<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Metallurgical Processing Fundamentals II - Environmental Remediation
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:30 AM, A112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chairs:</B>
<DD>B. Yarar, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO
<DD>R. G. Reddy, University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>High Concentration Soluble Manganese Removal by Adsorption/Oxidation on Manganese Oxide Ore: </B><BR>
<I>F. F. Peng and Y. Xu, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
High concentration manganese removal by adsorption and oxidation in aqueous solution was studied using manganese oxide ore. The operating parameters including pH, flow rate, Mn2+ concentration and oxidant dosage, affect the performance of Mn2+ removal were evaluated in the laboratory packed columns. In multi-column adsorption tests, no further decreasing in pH was observed on pH was lowered to 4.5-5. Adsorption was found the predominated mechanism involved with manganese removal. Extremely low H+/Mn2+ stoichiometry was measured, suggesting that the different adsorption mechanism other than H+/Mn2+ ion exchange might play an important role at low pH. This paper presents the explanation of the results obtained for high concentration manganese removal. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Removal of Lead from Water by the Natural Polymer-Chitosan:</B><BR>
<I>W. N. Harold and B. Pesic, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID</I></FONT><BR>
Chitosan is a derivative of chitin in which some portion of the acetyl group in the 2 position has been removed. Chitin is b(1r4)-2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucan. Both chitina and chitosan have high affinities for transition metals. Pb, and U. In this paper, the adsorption of lead as a function of pH, temperature, Pb and other metals concentration , and chitosan particle size was examined. It was found that chitosan was an excellent natural polymer for removal of lead from aqueous solutions. The kinetics of adsorption was fast, and the loading capacity for lead was relatively high. Rate of adsorption was controlled by intraparticle diffusion mechanisms. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Biological Sulfate Removal and Metal Recovery from Mine Waters:</B><BR>
<I>A. L. de Vegt, Paques, Inc., Exton, PA; H. G. Bayer, Kennecott Utah Copper Corp., Bingham Canyon, UT and C. J. Buisman, Tiopaq Sulfur Systems, B. V. Balk, The Netherlands</I></FONT><BR>
Paques has developed and installed treatment systems to remove metals and sulfate from mine waters as insoluble metal sulfides and elemental sulfur using two biological steps. A Paques groundwater treatment system for the Budelco zinc refinery has been in operation since May 1992 treating a flow of 1.3 MGD. Sulfate is reduced to below 200 mg/l, while metal removals exceed 99%. A demonstration plant started in November 1995 at Kennecott's Bingham Canyon Utah copper mine to remediate groundwater and selectively recover copper from the leach water. The principle of the biotechnological methods, full scale experience, and an overview of the test program at the copper mine will be presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Sorption of Heavy Metal Ions onto Non-livintg Aquatic Plant Biomass:</B><BR>
<I>G. Wang, M. C. Fuerstenau and R. W. Smith, University of Nevada, Reno, NV</I></FONT><BR>
Contamination of surface waters by heavy metals from mining and industrial sources has become a serous problem throughout the world. Biosorption onto living plants and dead plant biomass holds promise of being able to remove very low concentrations of heavy metal ions from solution, even in the presence of high concentrations of Ca (II) and Mg (II). Further, low-cost schemes are possible. An attractive possibility is the potential of dead biomass derived from higher aquatic plants. Such plant biomaterials are excellent sorbents for heavy metal ions. For example, dried water hyacinth (Eichhornia crassipes) roots, when suspended in water, strongly sorb cadmium, lead, and mercury ions. The sorption is dependent on factors such as reaction time, pH, concentration of metal ions, temperature, the presence of other metal ions and biomass concentration. The metal ions can be readily desorbed and roots regenerated. It also appears that roots can be recycled through a large number of loading-elution cycles without significant loss of sorption properties. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Calcination of Radioactive-waste Simulant in a Thermal Plasma Flow Reactor:</B><BR>
<I>P. R. Taylor and M. Manrique, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID and S. A. Pirzada, Nanomaterials Research Corp., Tuscson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
This investigation studied the inflight calcination kinetics of nuclear waste simulant using a thermal plasma reactor. A series of experiments were performed to determine the conversion of insoluble aluminum compounds to the soluble compounds and the decomposition of complex organic and nitrite compounds present in the simulant waste. Thermodynamic calculations based on free energy minimization were performed to establish a theoretical basis for this investigation. A kinetic model to describe the conversion of gibsite to sodium aluminate has been proposed. The products of the calcination were characterized using XRD, Gas Chromatography, and chemical analysis by ICP. The results of this investigation indicated 85% gibsite conversion to sodium aluminate, 90% of nitrate decomposition, 52% TOC decomposition and 90% conversion of chromium to soluble compounds. A process is identified for inflight calcination of wastes. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Comparison of Cyclones and Underflow-regulated Cyclones for Dewatering of Mineral Slurries: </B><BR>
<I>S. O'Brien, R. Spears and B. Lott, Linatex Inc., Gallatin, TN</I></FONT><BR>
The limited ability to control the water split out of conventional cyclones under varying feed conditions can be of concern when dealing with the removal of fines from waste streams. Underflow regulated cyclones normally have a restriction device located at the apex. Conventional wisdom dictates that a restriction at the apex normally causes other difficulties. However, by adding a siphon leg to the overflow, the water flow from the cyclone can be controlled without roping the unit. A Linatex developed underflow regulator was compared with a conventional cyclone for its ability to dewater a fine sand slurry.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>UV-Photolysis for the Destruction of Metal-complexed Cyanide:</B><BR>
<I>C. Young, M. Pruss, K. Slaybaugh, and B. Mikelson, Montana Tech of the University of Montana</I></FONT><BR>
Cyanide is a strong lixiviant for metals and is, therefore, favored for finishing and treatment, flotation control, and leaching, particularly gold. Industrial effluents consequently contain various metal-complex cyanides but no proven method exists for their complete destruction (until now?). In this study, photolytic techniques are described and experimentally compared for remediating a suite of metal-complexed cyanides including weak-acid dissociables (WADs) and strong-acid dissociables (SADs). Reaction mechanisms are proposed in accordance with Eh-pH diagrams and analytical results.

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

