<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Mineral Processing Fundamentals - Physical Separation
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:30 AM, A108/110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>C. E. Jordan, Salt Lake City, UT
<DD>M. Akser, E. I. DuPont de Nemours & Co., Starke, FL
</DL>


<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Upgrading Schemes for Boron Minerals-through Calcination:</B><BR>
<I>M. S. Celik, Instanbul Technical University, Instanbul, Turkey; T. Batar, Dokuz Eylul University, Izmir, Turkey; and Y. Akin, Instanbul Technical Univerity, Istanbul Turkey</I></FONT><BR>
Boron minerals are primarily upgraded by wet processing methods. However, severe environmental constraints have accelerated the development of dry processing techniques such as calcination. Boron minerals of commercial importance, i.e. colemanite, ulexite, and borax respectively undergo decrepitation, shrinkage and expansion upon heat treatment. Each mineral then requires a different beneficiation scheme for final product. In this study, laboratory and pilot plant studies on calcination of boron minerals conducted in our laboratories are reviewed along with their implications in commercial operations. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Fundamentals of Triboelectrostatic Separation: </B><BR>
<I>A Discussion on Particle Charge, Particle Size and Separation: H. Ban, T. Li, J. L. Schaefer, J. K. Neathery and J. M. Stencel, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY</I></FONT><BR>
Triboelectrostatic separation tests were performed on a bench-scale, analytical separator. Coal, coal combustion fly ash and mineral samples were used in the experiments. Fractions of separated samples were collected and analyzed to characterize the performance of the separation. Particle size distribution and morphological characteristics for these samples were analyzed by a laser diffraction particle size analysis, optical microscopy, and scanning electron microscopy (SEM). Theoretical analyzes were also performed in an effort to understand the behavior of the particles under different processing conditions. The presentation will discuss the particle separation data relevant to charge distribution and size distribution of the particles. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Classification Spirals for Iron Ore: A New Concept of Silica Grade Control and Its Benefits: </B><BR>
<I>F. Gheorghiu and C. Cot, Quebec Cartier Mining Co., Fermont, PQ, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
The silica grade of iron concentrate is a basic quality condition and its automat control permits to obtain the increase of spiral efficiency, therefore supplementary benefits of  the concentrating plant. The paper presents the bases and development of the control system model, its facilities and application results. The benefits of the automat control of the silica grade, on the basis of the model described, consist in: i) the observance of the target value of the silica grade, therefore the increase of the control process accuracy (standard deviation 0.15 - 0.17); ii) the stable operation of the spirals; iii) the increase of spiral efficiency, consisting in the increase of the weight/iron recovery yield. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Yield Index: A New Method for the Analysis of Flotation Results:</B><BR>
<I>M. T. Ityokumbul and M. P. Trubelja, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA and B. J. Arnold, CQ Inc., Homer City, PA</I></FONT><BR>
A review of commonly employed methods for the analysis of separation results is presented. The yield index, which is the product of the yield and the rejection of undesirable product (s), is presented and contrasted with the other indices. It is shown mathematically that optimization of flotation results using this index is superior since it concurrently maximizes both the recovery of the valuable constituent and the rejection of the undesirable components. The characteristics of the yield-gangue rejection plot from which the index is determined and its limitations are presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Modified Procedure to Measure the True Flotation Response of Coal: </B><BR>
<I>M. K. Mohanty and R. Q. Honaker, Southern Illinois University, Carbondale, IL and K. Ho, Illinois Clean Coal Institute, Carterville, IL</I></FONT><BR>
Recent studies indicate that the separation performance achieved by multiple-stage cleaning and, in some cases, single stage cleaning using column flotation is superior to the performance achieved by the traditional flotation characterization procedures. This superior performance is believed to be the result of the advanced flotation mechanisms provided by column flotation technologies. The results from a study which re-investigated the traditional release and tree procedures both experimentally and theoretically will be presented in this publication. As a result, a modified coal flotation characterization procedure has been developed which provides superior separation performance on the basis of both ash and total sulfur rejection. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Procedures for the Flotation of Low Rank Coals: </B><BR>
<I>T. Onlin, Industrial Technology Research Institute, Hsin Chu, Taiwan and D. D. Xu and F. F. Aplan The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Conventional wisdom indicates that as the rank of coal decreases, the amount of oil required for its flotation increases. In reality, it has been found that as the rank of the coal decreases linearly from low or medium volatile bituminous to lignite, the amount of oil required for flotation increases logarithmically. Very low rank coals such as lignite and sub-bituminous (and also sometimes high volatile C bituminous) may, in some cases, require upwards of 50 kg/t of oil for their flotation. Oxidation of the coal surface makes the coal particle respond as would one of lower rank, depending on the extent of oxidation. The authors have evaluated a large number of potential collectors for the flotation of low rank coals, and they have identified several attractive collectors for their flotation. In addition, the effect of high solids conditioning, reagent emulsification and pH is promoting low rank coal flotation has been evaluated. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

