<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Plant Design and Practice II - Refractory Gold Processing
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:30 AM, A105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>H. Pieterse, Barrick Goldstrike Mines Inc., Elko, NV
<DD>G. Simmons, Santa Fe Pacific Gold Corp., Albuquerque, NM
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Newmont Gold Roaster-Materials of Construction: </B><BR>
<I>T. Tempel Newmont Gold Co., Carlin, NV and A. Thabit, Garfield Steel and Machine, Inc., Glenwood Springs, CO
In 1994 Newmont Gold Co commissioned a 2.5 Mt/a refractory gold ore roasting  plant near Carlin, Nevada. Many unique characteristics of this facility required use of specialized materials of construction in the areas of dry grinding, roasting, gas cleaning, and sulfuric acid production. Process conditions and design criteria that necessitated the use of special materials include; siliceous and abrasive ore, low roasting temperatures, gas streams with high concentrations of oxygen and sulfur, and stringent environmental regulations. Materials selected for use were ceramics, corrosion-resistant steels, high temperature steels and polymers, lead, polypropylene and low flammability PVC.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Pressure Oxidation Problems and Solutions: Treating Carbonaceous Gold Ores Containing Trace Amounts of Chlorine (Halogens):</B><BR>
<I>G. L. Simmons, Sante Fe Pacific Gold Corp., Albuquerque, NM and D. R. Baughman, J. C. Gathje and K. C. Oberg, Hazen Research, Inc., Golden, CO
Santa Fe Pacific Gold Corp conducted pressure oxidation pilot plant studies at Hazen Research, Inc. on the Twin Creeks refractory carbonaceous gold ores during 1993 and 1994. Previous laboratory investigation resulted in very good gold recoveries of 90-95%, using CIL cyanidation after batch pressure oxidation. However, results from the pilot plant showed several ore types responded very poorly, with gold extractions of only 45-75%. Since these poor recoveries were unexpected, pilot plant testing was suspended for approximately four months while extensive basic research activities were conducted to determine the cause(s) and identify potential solutions. This paper describes the batch and pilot plant test results, the research activities that eventually identified the cause of the gold recovery problem, and the final semicontinuous and continuous pilot plant operations that confirmed possible solutions. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Flotation of Auriferous Pyrite Using Sante Fe Pacific Gold's N2TEC Flotation Technology: </B><BR>
<I>G. L. Simmons, Sante Fe Pacific Gold Corp., Albuquerque, NM
Many large low grade (refractory) sulfide gold resources exist, in Nevada and other parts of the world, that are not amenable to conventional flotation practice. Over the past few years, Sante Fe Pacific Gold Corp. have investigated non-conventional flotation process options to economically treat low grade resources of this type at it's Lone Tree and Twin Creeks mines. Initial testing using conventional flotation technology applied to the low grade gold resources at Lone Tree and Twin Creeks was unsuccessful. Review and analysis of gold bearing sulfide mineralogical characteristics and flotation chemistry provided a basic understanding that led to the development of SFPG's N2TEC flotation technology. This paper discusses the development of this technology and compares the results with conventional flotation practice. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Novel Method for Heap Biooxidation of Sulfide Concentrates:</B><BR>
<I>J. W. Shield, R. M. Crowell, C. E. Johansson and W. J. Kohr, GeoBiotics, Hayward, CA
Refractory sulfide flotation or gravity gold concentrates are coated onto support rocks and heap biooxidized. The coating is typically less than 0.05 in. thick and the support rock is 0.25 to 0.75 in. diameter. The exposed coating of sulfides reduces biooxidation rate limitations due to oxygen mass transfer. The large spaces between coated rocks reduces resistance to fluid percolation and aeration in the heap. The costs are significantly less than for concentrate biooxidation in stirred tanks. Subsequent gold recoveries exceed those seen in whole ore heap biooxidation and are comparable to stirred tank biooxidation processes. Laboratory and pilot test results indicate this is a viable technology for pretreating sulfide refractory gold ores. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Testing of Lining Materials in Barrick Goldstrike Pressure Oxidation Autoclaves: </B><BR>
<I>C. E. Semler, Semler Materials Services, Columbus, OH and H. J. H. Pieterse and R. A. Williams, Barrick Goldstrike Mines, Inc., Elko, NV
This paper reviews the knowledge and experience gained at Barrick Goldstrike Mines, Inc., regarding brickwork linings for pressure oxidation autoclaves. A 5-year test program, involving on-line, in-vessel sample exposure, has provided valuable information about the relative performance of a variety of brick and mortar products, for actual processing conditions. Brick and mortar properties, before and after autoclave exposure, will be presented and discussed. The program has resulted in multiple benefits, including development of a new mortar, improved understanding of brick property requirements, and an increase in the autoclave operating time between maintenance shutdowns. Further lining improvements are expected in the future, as the test program continues. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

