1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Hydrometallurgy I
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 27, 2:00 PM, A112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. S. Hu, Allco Chemical Corp., Gilbert, AZ
<DD>S. Nordwick, Montana Tech of the University of Montana, Butte, MT
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Transfer Rate of Cu (II) by b-Diketones from Ammoniacal Solution in Liquid Membrane Process: </B><BR>
<I>J. Drelich, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT and A. Kwiatkowski, J. Kapczynski, J. F. Biernat and J. Hupka, Technical University of Gdansk, Gdansk, Poland</I></FONT><BR>
The Cu(II) ions transfer rate was studied in a bulk liquid membrane system of an ammoniacal solution of Cu(II) as the feed, aromatic solvent as the membrane with dissolved  1-phenylo-1, 3-tetradekadione as the carrier, and a hydrochloric acid solution as the stripping phase. It was found that at the steady state the Cu(II) ions transport occurs at a constant rate. The transport phenomenon is stimulated by Cu(II) complex formation with b-diketones and ammonia molecules. The principal resistance to the transport of the Cu (II) ions remains at the membrane/stripping solution interface. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Bioleaching of Refractory Gold Concentrates at High Pulp Densities in a Non-conventional Rotating Drum Reactor: </B><BR>
<I>T. J. Vargas, M. N. Herrera, B. N. Escobar, N. Parra and C. Gonzalez, University of Chile, Santiago, Chile</I></FONT><BR>
The bioleaching of mineral sulfide pulps in a bench-scale rotating drum reactor has been studied. The reactor includes horizontal paddles in the inner wall for lifting of the mineral pulp. The performance of the reactor was tested in the bioleaching of a -400 mesh refractory pyritic gold concentrate in the presence of a pure Thiobacillus ferrooxidans strain (ATCC 19859). The concentrate was efficiently bioleached at 50% pulp density with the drum operating at a rotating speed of 0.5 rpm. Attempts of bioleaching the concentrate at  the same pulp density in conventional stirred reactor showed severe inhibition of bacterial activity. The results show that the drum reactor allows to operate at much higher pulp densities than the conventional stirred tank reactor. This behavior is explained in terms of an improvement of the bacterial activity due to a better control of the attrition of the mineral particles. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Reductive Acid Dissolution of Iron-bearing Zinc Concentrates-A First Step Towards Residue free Zinc Refining?: </B><BR>
<I>E. Molleman and T. van Sandwijk, Delft University of Technology, Delft, The Netherlands and G. Van Weert, ORETOME, Ltd., Caledon East, ON, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
This paper reports on testwork exploring the dissolution/reprecipitation reactions: ZnS + 2HCl+ , ZnCl2 + H2S, as part of a process for the production of pure ZnS. In spheroidal form, this would constitute a premium form of zinc refinery roaster feed enabling the production of pure ZnO. The research focused on the influence of proton activity on dissolution of zinc concentrates from Brunswick M&S, Red Dog and Tara. The results and thermodynamic data suggest that the three concentrates contained significant amounts of the more reactive mineral wurtzite, although XRD analysis showed mainly the presence of the mineral sphalerite. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Laboratory Electrorefining-Design and Testing Considerations:</B><BR>
<I>M. G. Ascher and K. L. Purdy, BHP Copper Inc., San Manuel, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Laboratory electrorefining testing requires a number of factors to be taken into consideration. A few types of laboratory electrorefining tests are described and compared. The design and operation of a full length laboratory electrorefining test setup at BHP San Manuel Metallurgical Laboratories is discussed. Typical problems encountered are presented with a  discussion of solutions used to overcome them. Typical lab results are compared to commercial scale results to show the usefulness of this technique. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Leaching Kinetics of Chalcopyrite in Ammonium Iodide Solutions with Iodine: </B><BR>
<I>Y. C. Guan and K. N. Han, South Dakota School of MInes and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
The leaching kinetics of chalcopyrite in ammonium iodide solutions with iodine has been studied using rotating disc. The variables studied include the concentration of lixiviants, rotating speed, pH of the solution, and reaction temperature. The leaching rate was found to be independent with the disc rotating speed, and a half order with respect to the iodine concentration. The apparent activation energy was measured to be about 5 kJ/mole under the conditions studied. Experimental findings were described by a kinetic model.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Diagonestic Leach Procedure for Low Grade Copper Ores: </B><BR>
<I>J. B. Hiskey, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ and C. E. James, Phelps Dodge Corp. Morenci, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Diagnostic leaching tests have proved to be an invaluable analytical procedure for gold ores. The success of these techniques is remarkable in that gold ores are typically extremely dilute. This paper presents a diagnostic leaching protocol developed for low-grade copper bearing materials. The procedure employs the application of increasingly stronger lixiviants and can either be applied individually or in a sequential fashion. A benefit of this procedure is that it provides considerable information regarding sample mineralogy. Results are presented for different samples of copper mill tailings containing between 0.168 and 0.225% copper. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

