<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Mineral Processing Fundamentals-General
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, A108/110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>S. K. Mishra, Tetra Technologies, Inc.,The Woodlands, TX
<DD>B. Yarar, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Direct Force Measurements for Amine Flotation System: </B><BR>
<I>D. H. Flinn and R. H. Yoon, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
In the absence of a reliable technique to directly measure forces between an air bubble and a solid in water, it was believed that force measurements in which a hydrophobic solid is substituted for an air bubble may provide valuable information. An atomic force microscope (AFM) was used to measure forces between a bare silica surface and a hydrophobized glass sphere in the presence of dodecylamine hydrochloride (DAHCl) at several pH's. The results show general agreement between that appearance of long-range, non-DLVO forces and an increase in floatability, which further suggests that long-range hydrophobic forces are necessary to achieve good flotation. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Interaction Forces at High Ionic Strengths-The Interfacial Polar Interaction Theory: </B><BR>
<I>S. Veeramasuneni and Y. Hu, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT, M. R. Yalamanchili, MEMC Electronic Materials Inc., St. Peters, MO and J. D. Miller, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The interaction of soluble salt particles in their saturated brines is of interest from both a fundamental and practical perspective. The state of particle dispersion/aggregation can now be described based on non-equilibrium electrokinetic measurements for alkaline halides. Based on these surface charge results, the extent of interaction of alkali halide particles in their saturated solutions was examined by optical microscopy. These microscopic observations indicate that the sign of the surface charge has significant effect on the extent of particle dispersion/aggregation. Atomic force microscopy (AFM) is now begin used to directly measure the interaction forces responsible for the stability of these alkali halide aggregates observed in optical microscopy studies. Finally, these experimental results are described based on the interfacial polar interaction theory. In this regard the nature and the type of interaction forces are examined to improve our understanding of interparticle forces prevailing at high ionic strengths. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>SIMS Study of Adsorption of Collectors on Pyrite: </B><BR>
<I>D. R. Nagaraj and J. S. Brinen, Cytec Industries, Stamford, CT</I></FONT><BR>
Adsorption of sulfide collectors such as xanthate on pyrite has been the subject of extensive studies over several decades using a wide variety of techniques. In spite of this, there are are many unanswered questions as to the identity of adsorbed species on pyrite surfaces. For example, though there is general agreement for the formation of dixanthogen, there is no agreement with regard to the formation of an iron xanthate complex. Far less known in non-xanthate collector systems. We have used Secondary Ion Mass Spectroscopy (SIMS) successfully in the past to obtain direct evidence for the identity of the adsorbed collector species on copper sulfides, galena and Cu-activated quartz. The present study is an extension of the SIMS analysis to investigate the adsorption of sulfide collectors on pyrite.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Effect of Hydrophobic Agglomerant on the Flotation of Fine Molybdenite: </B><BR>
<I>R. Stocker and S. Catro, Universidad de Concepcion, Concepcion, Chile and J. S. Laskowski, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
Flotation recovery of molybdenite particles finer than 15 microns sharply decrease with decreasing size. A totally hydrophobic latex agglomerant (UBC-1), which was previously reported to be very efficient in agglomerating hydrophobic coal particles, has been found to agglomerate such fine molybdenite particles. The agglomeration takes place only in the presence of MIBC which is commonly used as a frother in molybdenite flotation. Adsorption tests confirmed that MIBC is adsorbed onto molybdenite. The use of both UBC-1 agglomerant and MIBC resulted in much improved flotation recoveries of fine molybdenite. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Slime Coating Mechanism in the Flotation of Colemanite/Clay System: </B><BR>
<I>Y. Akin, I. Gulgonul, and M. S. Celik, Instanbul Technical University, Instanbul, Turkey</I></FONT><BR>
The floatability of a typical boron mineral, colemanite (Ca2B6O11.5H2O), is shown to be hindered by the presence of montmorillonite type clay minerals. The clay is found to act in the form of slime coating. The mechanism of slime coating is investigated using pure colemanite and clay and their mixtures with an anionic reagent in a microflotation cell. Adsorption, flotation, solubility, zeta potential and scanning electron microscope studies reveal that slime coating occurs through electrostatic attraction. It is possible to minimize the effect of slime coating either at high surfactant concentration or at high pH values. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Carrying Capacity in a Pilot Flotation Column: </B><BR>
<I>M. T. Ityokumbul and M. P. Trubelja, The Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA</I></FONT><BR>
Concentrate flow rates have been measured for the flotation of -100 mesh Lower Kittaning coal in a computer-controlled 0.076 m x 3.5 m pilot flotation column. The variables studied were recovery zone height (0.43 m - 2.36 m), air flow rate (1 - 6 1pm), and solid feed concentration (2.5% - 10% solids). The size distribution of concentrate and tailings samples were determined. The results obtained show that the concentrate flow rate was independent of collection zone height, but dependent on the gas flow rate, solid loading and particle size. The results obtained are compared with correlations currently available for predicting carrying capacity in column flotation. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>An Investigation of a Novel Concept for Mineral Liberation Analysis: </B><BR>
<I>K. V. S. Sastry, University of California, Berkeley, CA</I></FONT><BR>
Quantitative information concerning the state mineral liberation is extremely helpful for the design, development and control of mineral processing operations. Currently available methods include microscopy techniques followed by image analysis and physical methods of size and heavy liquid separation. Both methods tend to be slow and are limited to off-line. This paper will describe a novel concept for mineral liberation analysis which can be performed in a few minutes and has potential for on-line application. The technique is based on classifying the particles based on their size and a discriminating property, like stokes diameter, and mathematically transforming such information to yield weight-size-composition information. The paper will discuss the relevant mathematical details and will present results from preliminary experimental investigations that demonstrate the successful application of the concept. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development of a Detection Method for Measuring Scale Growth Rates in Real Time: </B><BR>
<I>J. P. Chamberlain and P. R. Kraus, Nalco Chemical Co., Naperville, IL</I></FONT><BR>
A new technology for measuring scale growth rates in real time has been developed. This technology is useful for 1) determining the scaling tendency of mineral processing waters, especially when changes in the process affect previously stable process solution, and 2) determining antiscalant performance quantitatively in real plant conditions. This new method can be used in place of the existing technique of monitoring scale growth on metal coupons placed in the plant process water. This paper describes the development of this technology with emphasis on results from field trials at US and Chilean copper concentrators. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

