1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Process Control and Computer Applications I - Plant Practices
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 2:00 PM, A105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>G. H. Luttrell, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA
<DD>E. C. Gutierrez, PCS Phosphates, Aurora, NC
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Development of a Video-based Coal Slurry Ash Analyzer:</B><BR>
<I>P. L. Dunn, E. B. Cruz, G. H. Luttrell and G. T. Adel, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg, VA</I></FONT><BR>
Automatic control of fine coal cleaning circuits has traditionally been limited by the lack of sensors for on-line ash analysis. Although several nuclear-based analyzers are available, none have seen widespread acceptance. In this investigation, image analysis technology is used for on-line determination of ash content in fine coal slurries. The ash content of a flotation tailings stream is correlated to the mean gray level of the slurry. Calibration data obtained from in-plant testing indicate that the sensor is accurate to within 62% ash over a range from 65-85% ash. Sensor development and in-plant testing are discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The New WEMCO SmartCell-Flotation with an Attitude:</B><BR>
<I>D. G. Foot Jr., L. B. Hales and L. D. Redden, EIMCO Process Equipment Co., Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
EIMCO Process Equipment Co has introduced the new SmartCell series of conventional flotation cells. The flagship of this new development is the 4500 ft3 cell that is the largest operating cell available in the industry. This new series of cells includes a cylindrical tank design, a conical draft tube and froth crowder. Optional air control, wash water addition and embedded expert control are available. A discussion of design parameters, energy efficiency, testing results of features and commercial plant results are presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Use of Taguchi Methods and Computer Techniques for Research and Process Improvement: </B><BR>
<I>C. Flores and K. L. Purdy, BHP Copper Inc., San Manuel, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The most common experimental approach of study one variable at a time while holding all others constant is extremely inefficient. Use of statistical methods enables engineers and scientists to obtain meaningful information with the fewest experiments, reducing cost and waste effort. In particular, Taguchi methods can be more efficient than traditional full factorial experiment designs, as they can study more variables with fewer runs, and they are more robust against process "noise". Taguchi designs are also simple to formulate and the results can be analyzed by simple PC spreadsheets. The role and benefits of using Taguchi methods in experiments for development and process optimization are discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Process Control System Utilization and Equipment Reliability Maintenance: </B><BR>
<I>O. A. Bascur, OSI Software, Inc., The Woodlands, TX and D. R. Potts, Meridium, Roanoke, VA</I></FONT><BR>
Most mining and metallurgical plants have developed predictive maintenance policies based on statistical analysis and specialized techniques, like vibration analysis, oil and lube analysis for critical equipment. Process control strategies have also been installed in several metallurgical sites. These control strategies require instrumentation maintenance from local personnel. The availability of real time and process history to identify the most critical part of the processing system from mechanical integrity is a must for global plant optimization. Specialized performance control monitoring algorithms are required to justify their existence and contribution to the bottom line. Emerging technologies are allowing to combine these techniques into a single total plant system. Tools are required to assist in troubleshooting and adapting these process control instruments and strategies. The key is both plant equipment and process control availability and utuilziation rather than just maintenance. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

