<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Hydrometallurgy II
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, A112

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>R. J. Roman, Leach, Inc., Tucson, AZ
<DD>K. L. Purdy, BHP Copper, San Manuel, AZ
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Treatment of the Tintaya Skarn Copper Oxide: </B><BR>
<I>L. R. Chirinos and K. N. Batallanos, BHP Tintaya SA, Arequipa, Peru and M. P. Neira and M. A. Eamon, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
The Tintaya mine of BHP Copper, located in Southern Peru, includes a copper oxide deposit hosted in a mineralized skarn zone. The ore contains high clays and high acid consuming species resulting in low heap leaching performance. A treatment scheme was adopted that included a wet screening separation. The coarse fraction would be treated in heaps and the fines by agitation leaching, the dissolved copper would then be recovered through SXEW. Testwork determined the optimum heap leaching conditions to treat the oxide in on/off pads of 3 meters height with an initial acid cure followed by a variable acid strength during irrigation. The method resulted in a reduced acid consumption and good copper recoveries. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A New Process to Remove Fluorine from Copper Concentrates: </B><BR>
<I>. V. M. Torres, A. Viana Jr., P. R. M. Andrade and N. J. Duarte, Cia Vale Do Rio Doce, Santa Luzia-MG, Brazil</I></FONT><BR>
The presence of high fluorine levels in copper concentrates affects the conventional sulfuric acid units usually integrated with copper smelters. Consequently, penalties are applied to high fluorine concentrates prices. Several process alternatives to this problem were studied at CVRD Technology Center, in Brazil. A hydrometallurgical process of removing fluorine and upgrading copper concentrates was developed and is presented in this paper. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Non-cyanide Industrial Recovery of Silver Utilizing Nitrous-Sulfuric Acid Catalyzed Pressure Oxidation: </B><BR>
<I>C. G. Anderson, H. A. Simons Ltd., Vancouver, BC, Canada</I></FONT><BR>
In the majority of operations recovering gold and silver by hydrometallurgical means cyanide is the predominant lixiviant. However, production of massive quantities of silver chloride as an important intermediate processing compound was done on an industrial scale in the nitrous-sulfuric acid pressure leaching of a refractory precious metals concentrate. This proven process required no cyanide. Thus, because of the large volumes encountered during day-to-day operation, the need for efficient and low cost methods of silver chloride precipitation, reduction and materials handling was mandatory. This presentation will cover the evolution of plant scale precipitation, filtration, washing, reduction and control  of silver chloride processing. As well, an in-depth description of the unique leaching system will also be included. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Column Leach Tests for the "El Arco" Copper Ore Deposit: </B><BR>
<I>R. Balderrama, Mexicana de Cananea SA de CV, Cananea, Sonora, Mexico</I></FONT><BR>
A study consist in 20 column leach tests were performed for the "El Arco" copper ore deposit, located on Baja California, Mexico. The main purpose was to define the basic criteria like recovery and sulfuric acid consumption, for a commercial heap leach system designed to process the oxide copper (Chrysocola) of the deposit. Leach parameters such as, amount of sulfuric acid in the cure solution, cure technique, particle size of the material, leach solution's flowrate application, leach solution's acid strength and height of the lifts, were evaluated to choose those parameters in which the results were the best ones for that particular design.

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Construction of a One Million Pound Cu per Year Solution Mining Pilot Plant at the White Pine MIne: </B><BR>
<I>J. E. Tilk  and W. T. Williams, Copper Range Co., White Pine, MI</I></FONT><BR>
Copper Range Company, White Pine, Michigan, is constructing a solution mining pilot plant at its Southeast No. 1 facilities. The plant will produce one million pounds of cathode copper per year at a designed flow rate of 150 gpm. Challenges in the underground construction of the plant comprise of drilling and blasting of the existing pillars, building concrete walls to contain the solution within designated areas, and installing an infrastructure including more than 50,000 ft of pipes, six pump stations and various controls to maintain a constant flow rate. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Bio-reactor Development for Ferrous to Ferric Conversion: </B><BR>
<I>M. P. Neira, BHP Copper, Tucson, AZ, T. D. McWaters, BHP Copper N.A., Miami, AZ and  C. Flores and R. Patel, BHP Copper N. A., San Manuel, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
In situ leaching of copper from chalcocite relies on ferric iron concentration in the lixiviant being reduced to ferrous. To re-establish the ferric concentration in solution, ferrous  must be re-oxidized to ferric. This reaction is slow under normal chemical conditions but it is catalyzed by Thiobacillus ferrooxidans bacteria. BHP Copper's Miami In situ unit developed a bio-reactor as a method of oxidizing ferrous to ferric. Testwork defined the effects on oxidation of temperature. CO2, oxygen, and air injection flow rate. This paper summarizes the results of ferrous bio-oxidation using plastic column packing and oxide ores as bio-reactors and the leaching results of the bio-reacted lixiviant on chalcocite ores. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

