<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Mineral Processing Fundamentals - Surface Chemistry of Mineral Fillers
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 8:30 AM, A108/110

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>J. J. Kellar, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD
<DD>S. Behl, Engelhard Corp., Gordon, GA
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Recent Advances in Kaolin Particle Aspect Ratio Determinations utilizing Automated Microscopy and Electron Energy Loss Spectroscopy: </B><BR>
<I>W. R. Boltin, T. B. Vander Wood, J. P. Bradley and L. P. Keller, MVA Inc., Norcross, GA and R. J. Pruett, ECC Int'l., Sandersville, GA</I></FONT><BR>
Aspect ratio (diameter thickness) measurements on clay minerals have typically involved manual electron microscopy analyses of shadowed particles in order to measure both platelet thickness and diameter. Recent advances in automated microanalysis technology and in applications of parallel electron energy loss spectroscopy (PEELS) have led to the development of new techniques that allow for more economical aspect ratio determinations. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Surface Treatments of Mineral Fillers as Viewed from a Flotation Chemist's Perspective: </B><BR>
<I>J. J. Kellar, South Dakota School of Mines and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
A tremendous amount of minerals are used as filler materials in a wide variety of industries including pulp/paper, automobile, computer and electronic industries. Oftentimes these fillers are given treatments which modify the surface properties of the filler. Many of these surface treatments are similar to those used during froth flotation. In this presentation the surface treatments given to fillers for the polymer industry will be reviewed. This review will compare the analysis of surface treatments traditionally performed by the flotation chemist with that required for surface treated fillers for polymeric materials. Particular attention will be given to spectroscopic, wetting and adhesive characteristics of the fillers after surface treatment. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The Surface Chemistry of Mineral Fillers in De-inking Flotation of Wastepaper Pulp: </B><BR>
<I>M. A. D. Azevedo, J. Drelich, M. R. Yalamanchili and J. D. Miller, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The major non-fiber material present in paper is starch, which is added to improve the inert-fiber bonding and also helps to increase the retention of mineral fillers in the cellulose fibers. In order to develop an efficient de-inking flotation process for the separation of ink particles from wastepaper pulp, it is important to understand the surface chemistry of filler materials and their interactions with cellulose fibers. In this regard, diffuse reflectance (DRIFT) is being used to study adsorption phenomena and particle interactions involved in these systems. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Synthesis and Preparation of Magnesium Hydroxide Surfaces as a Model for Flame-Retardant Fillers: </B><BR>
<I>F. J. Johnson, A. G. Pommer, W. M. Cross, R. M. Winter, and J. J. Kellar, South Dakota School of MInes and Technology, Rapid City, SD</I></FONT><BR>
Magnesium hydroxide (Mg(OH)2) is important industrially for its flame-retardant properties as a filler in high-temperature polymers. Surfactants are often applied to increase dispersion and improve adhesion between filler and polymer. The study of surface modified Mg (OH)2 interfaces has been limited by the availability of substrates suitable for many analytical techniques. To help alleviate this problem, three approaches to Mg(OH)2 substrate synthesis have been developed: hydration of MgO crystals; Mg(OH)2 sol-gel thin film dip-coating; and hydration of a magnesium metal disk. The synthesized Mg(OH)2 layers were characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM). Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR), and Raman spectroscopy before and after adsorption of the surfactants. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Adsorption Behavior of Polyacrylic Acid on Alumina and Silicon Carbide: </B><BR>
<I>B. Markovic, T. Chen and P. Somasundaran, Columbia University, New York, NY</I></FONT><BR>
Performance of mineral filler particles in ceramic applications can be modified drastically by adsorbing polymers of optimum molecular structure and dosage. In this work, a novel scheme of controlled polymer adsorption is used to produce nanocomposite of unique core-shell designs. Towards this purpose, adsorption and desorption behavior of selected polyacrylic acids on three minerals (alumina, titania, and silicon carbide) was examined as a function of relevant parameters. Adsorption of PAA was found to depend markedly on polymer molecular weight, pH, as well as solid loading. Specifically, the adsorption density was found to increase with increase in polymer molecular weight for non-porous alumina while it was found to decrease systematically in the case of porous alumina. This was attributed to the inaccessibility of the pores to the higher molecular polymers. Interestingly, the adsorption density of PAA was found to change when the solid loading was increased. PAA adsorbs on silicon carbide only at low pH values when the particles have very low surface charge suggesting that the adsorption in this case is controlled by electrostatic forces. Using polyacrylic acid as bridging agent between the alumina fillers (core) and nanosize alumina or titania particles (shells), controlled layer by layer deposition of nanoparticle on the core particle surface could be obtained. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mechanism(s) of Non-ionic Polymer Adsorption on Oxide/Silicate Surfaces: </B><BR>
<I>S. Mathur and B. M. Moudgil, University of Florida, Gainesville, FL</I></FONT><BR>
Development of robust reagent schemes for processes such as flotation and selective flocculation require that the adsorption mechanisms of surfactants, polymers and other additives which comprise the reagent suite, are well understood. Specifically, adsorption of polymeric additives is attributed to a combination of chemical and electrostatic interactions, hydrogen bonding, and van der Waals forces. Hydrogen bonding, however, is suspected to be a cause of most of the non-selectivity observed in polymer adsorption on fine particles. Since there is evidence in the literature to the contrary, a systematic study was undertaken to investigate the adsorption of a non-ionic polymer - polyethylene oxide (PEO) on several oxides and silicates. It was determined that strong Bronsted acid sites on the surface interact with the ether oxygen, a Lewis base, of PEO to cause adsorption and subsequently flocculation of the substrate particles. The other possible mechanisms such as complexation with adsorbed ions and electrostatic interactions were found not to play a major role in the PEO adsorption process. In this presentation, the adsorption and flocculation studies of oxides and silicates with PEO will be discussed. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Adsorption of Oleic Acid at the Surface of a TiO2 Thin Film as Revealed by FT-IR Internal Reflection Spectroscopy: </B><BR>
<I>J. Drelich, L. Chen, J. D. Miller, and S. Guruswamy, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
The adsorption of oleic acid at the surface of titanium dioxide from aqueous solutions was examined by Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectroscopy using an internal reflection element coated with a thin film of TiO2. Thin film with a thickness of 100-200A was deposited on the surface of a germanium single crystal by RF magnetron reactive sputtering. It was found that adsorption of oleic acid on the surface of TiO2 thin film occurs at neutral pH, from about pH=5.5 to pH=8.0. The electrostatic interaction between carboxylic group of oleic acid and the hydroxylated surface of titanium dioxide appears to be the dominant driving force stimulating the adsorption mechanism in this system. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

