<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Process Control and Computer Applications II - Artificial Intelligence and Simulation
</I></FONT><BR>

Thursday, February 27, 9:00 AM, A105/107

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>C. Karr, University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL
<DD>O. Bascur, Oil Systems, Inc., The Woodlands, TX
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Embedded Smart Control Thickeners: </B><BR>
<I>L. B. Hales, R. P. Klepper, and M. G. Nelson, EIMCO Process Equipment, Salt Lake City, UT</I></FONT><BR>
Large thickener sizing and control traditionally have been independent activities and lack automated controls. Developments in flocculation optimization, instrumentation to detect solids and computer process control technologies have lead to the acceptance of high rate and high density thickeners for tailings disposal as a paste. These thickeners are smaller than conventional thickeners and require automated continuous process control This paper describes the "Embedded Smart Control" system used by EIMCO to optimzie thickener performance. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Component and Object Technologies to Build the Industrial Desktop: </B><BR>
<I>O. A. Bascur, OSI Software, Inc., The Woodlands, TX</I></FONT><BR>
Intelligent systems (IS) technologies have received much attention in a wide range of process engineering applications including process operations. With the revolutionary progress in information and computer technologies applying the latest technologies in metallurgical complexes has become a serious challenge to both management and technical teams. Objects and components are changing the way everyone relates to their computer and networks. Goals of real time performance monitoring includes maximizing the profitability by maximizing production, improving efficiency, attending product quality, costs, maintenance, environmental and safety regulations. Designers must consider the greatly expanded desktop computing, Microsoft object technology, Internet and how to build these systems. This paper discusses some opportunities and challenges using objects, components in designing applications and integrating intelligent systems tools. Two examples using performance equations and IS technologies applied to mineral processing are presented. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Fuzzy Logic Control Applications in Coal Preparation Plants: </B><BR>
<I>M. J. Laurila, Quality Control, Inc., Lake Zurich, IL</I></FONT><BR>
On-line analyzers have made possible the use of Fuzzy Logic Control (FLC) for local control applications in coal preparation plants. This includes FLC control of complete circuits such as heavy media vessels, cyclones and froth flotation. This paper outlines the control strategies employed and presents examples of automatic vs. manual control. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>A Comparison of Fuzzy and Neural Network Modeling of Mineral Processing Equipment: </B><BR>
<I>C. L. Karr, B. Weck and K. Nishita, University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL</I></FONT><BR>
Researchers at the University of Alabama are investigating artificial intelligence based computer models of mineral processing systems. Two approaches have been found to be particularly effective in the development of data-driven computer models. The first approach employs neural networks which are computational paradigms based on the mechanics of the human brain. The second approach combines fuzzy mathematics with genetic algorrithms to produce an adaptive modeling system. In this paper, the two approaches to modeling are compared and contrasted with respect to accuracy, computational time, and the man hours required to model three mineral processing systems: 1) a grinding circuit, 2) a hydrocyclone separator, and 3) a flotation circuit. 

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Analysis and Comparison of Fuzzy Logic Control and PID Control Strategies: </B><BR>
<I>F. F. Peng and J. Zhang, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
Using a fuzzy logic controller, a signal applied on the processes may be generated through a linguistic protocol expressing an operators intuitive control strategies. In this paper, fuzzy logic controller and PID controller imposed upon the feedback liquid level control systems for a stirred tank are studied and compared. The construction factors including shape of membership functions, number of fuzzy variables, number of inputs, number of rules, and different defuzzification methods are considered in design and formulating the fuzzy logic control strategies and algorithms. From the analysis of the strategies and control performances, an optimum controller may be generated by making use of the best combinations of these fuzzy construction factors. 

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

