<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Capital Budgeting and Project Evaluation
</I></FONT><BR>

Monday, February 24, 9:00 AM, A109/111

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>


<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>D. K. Dysinger, Montana Tech of the University of Montana, Butte, MT
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Capital Budgeting: Forecasting the Future:</B><BR>
<I>D. K. Dysinger, Montana Tech of the University of Montana, Butte, MT</I></FONT><BR>
Capital budgeting is an investment making process to quantify, evaluate, and compare competing investment alternatives for maximizing the value of shareholder wealth. The absolute and relative values of the components of cash flow, revenue, operating costs, taxes, general and administrative costs, and the costs of capital, are uncertain across time. The degree of uncertainty is the basis of investment risk. Mineral investment is both long term and capital intensive and techniques for reducing uncertainty can have a particularly beneficial effect on the present value of shareholder wealth. The paper discusses and compares a number of tools for quantifying and reducing uncertainty in the decision making process.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Does the Capital Budgeting Process Inhibit Corporate Competitiveness?:</B><BR>
<I>B. W. Cavender, BHP Copper Inc., San Manuel, AZ</I></FONT><BR>
Capital investments are made for a variety of purposes, from providing incremental capacity at existing operations to developing and implementing new technologies intended to radically improve a company's capabilities. These projects generate very different business opportunities and create value in distinctive ways. For incremental improvements, the capital budgeting process assures at least a loose fit between short-term goals and readily available resources. However, the criteria used to evaluate capital projects often prevent a company from committing to more aggressive goals that lie beyond the firm's current abilities or resources. Such projects may not have clearly identifiable future cash flows, and the degree of interaction with other projects and the nature of the risk incurred may be very difficult to estimate. Additionally, by focusing only on quantifiable benefits, the budgeting process often fails to recognize "soft" improvements such as increased operating flexibility or new knowledge generated by such projects. By rejecting these projects, the capital budgeting process may actually harm the company's future competitive position.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Mining Financial Project Evaluation and Global Community:</B><BR>
<I>A. N. T. Lopes, SOMINCOR, Lisboa, Portugal</I></FONT><BR>
Financial Project Evaluation methods, which objectives are sufficient for strict corporate purposes, attempt to provide some measures of the financial attractiveness of a project to the company. Now, mining industry is more and more involved in fighting for its place and image to the society, which implies the assumption not only of its projects environmental costs internalization, but also of the consequences of the way society continues to see mining, with the risks involved to the project. It still supervenes that the mining industry has accepted a re-intensified mission to show clearly in a political and social way to serve the community. This paper intends to address the financial project evaluation methods complementary work in order to obtain the overall evaluation of projects taking in account the global community. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>NPV or IRR? Why Not Both?:</B><BR>
<I>T. F. Torries, West Virginia University, Morgantown, WV</I></FONT><BR>
The primary merit criteria used by the mining industry is IRR rather than NPV, although NPV is favored by academicians. While IRR does provide a measure of capital efficiency, which NPV does not, IRR cannot measure additions to wealth, may yield multiple solutions, and may result in non-NPV consistent project ranking. This paper discusses the goals of managers, compares NPV and IRR, and makes conclusions about the preferred measure. Conclusions are that managers require both measures, NPV suffers the same multiple root problem as does IRR, and the employment of incremental IRR to reach NPV consistent project ranking is unnecessary. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>One Project, Two Discount Rates:</B><BR>
<I>G. A. Davis, Colorado School of Mines, Golden, CO</I></FONT><BR>
The development timing of a mineral project often depends on its value, where positive NPV projects are developed immediately. Option pricing theory finds that it is better to wait until the NPV of the property is significantly greater than zero before developing it. This paper converts this vague development timing advice into a more concrete decision rule: develop the project when its "development timing NPV" is positive. In calculating the development timing NPV, we use a development timing discount rate that is about twice the normal valuation discount rate. Hence, for one project we need two discount rates, one for the valuation calculation, and one for the development timing decision.</P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

<P><CITE>capBudget.stml</CITE><BR>Version 1.0</P>
<P>You are visitor number
25.</P>
</P>

