<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
1997 SME Annual Meeting Technical Program
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR="#000000">
<TR><TH>
<IMG SRC="../art/meetlogo.GIF" ALT =" " ALIGN=left>

<FONT COLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><FONT SIZE=7>
1997 SME Annual Meeting & Exhibit
</FONT></H1>
<FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial">
<H3><I><BR CLEAR=left>
Downstream Markets for Mineral Products
</I></FONT><BR>

Wednesday, February 26, 9:00 AM, A109/111

</H3></FONT>
</TH></TR></FONT></TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT><B>Chair:</B>
<DD>N. Edmonson, Industrial Commodities Economics, Dunwoody, GA
<CHAIRS>
</DL>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Changing Trends in Aluminum End Markets:</B><BR>
<I>P. A. Dodd, Alumax, Inc., Norcross, GA</I></FONT><BR>
Aluminum end markets have undergone a significant shift since 1991. While the three major categories - building and construction, transportation, and containers and packaging - remain the dominant markets, transportation supplanted packaging as the largest market in 1994. Tremendous growth rates in transportation are due not only to healthy automobile production rates from 1992 to 1994, but also to the ongoing substitution of aluminum for steel in manufacturing autos. Meanwhile, growth in packaging slowed as aluminum captured nearly the entire beverage can market by 1990. These recent trends are likely to continue, making transportation even more dominant in the years to come. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Kaolin and Calcium Carbonate, - Markets, Supply and the Future:</B><BR>
<I>R. A. Burns, Strategic Business Development, Inc. Atlanta, GA</I></FONT><BR>
The production and sales of kaolin and calcium carbonate in North America exceeds 14 million tons in higher value market segments. With a few exceptions, the markets supplied exhibit mature growth rates. In some market sectors, technology changes have and continue to occur shifting pigment-type consumption and growth. New sources of supply will impact current businesses. New product and process developments for kaolin and calcium carbonates are continuing. Each of these issues is examined in developing a view of the future for kaolin and calcium carbonate in North America.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Rail Renaissance - New Opportunities:</B><BR>
<I>D. Bourquard, Norfolk Southern Corp., Norfolk, VA</I></FONT><BR>
In the last decade there have been great changes in the rail cost function driven by innovation and technology. Some of these are obvious and evolutionary - like better materials, larger cars, and more efficient locomotives. Others are unexpected and revolutionary like the use of satellites, the Internet, total supply chain analysis and deregulation. The result is a revised portfolio of situations where rail is the optimum transport choice versus truck, water, or other substitutes. New patterns of mineral production, processing and consumption result. Today's Engineers need to be aware of the new rail possibilities as they locate facilities and design terminals. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>Copper's Evolving Role in End-use Markets:</B><BR>
<I>W. T. Black, Copper Development Assoc. Inc., New York, NY</I></FONT><BR>
Although serving downstream applications for over 10,000 years - 4,000 years longer than man's second oldest metal, gold - copper continues to adapt to the modern world. In fact, despite its long history of use and re-use as our most recycled engineering metal, more than 80% of the copper ever used has been mined and placed in service since World War II. The paper will delineate the most important end-use applications for copper, and discuss the important trends in each, including relationships with competing materials and technologies. </P>

<P><FONT FACE="Helvetica,Arial"><B>The United States Fertilizer Manufacturer - An Endangered Species:</B><BR>
<I>K. F. Nyiri, Mississippi Chemical Corp., Yazoo City, MS</I></FONT><BR>
The United States is the world's largest fertilizer manufacturer and the second largest consumer. Access to relatively cheap, locally produced raw materials and a large backyard marketplace have allowed the US fertilizer manufacturers to supply the bulk of their domestic fertilizer requirements, as well as become a dominant player in world trade. But changes in transportation economics are eroding these advantages. Imports of fertilizer raw materials and finished products are increasing. As the worldwide mineral industry expands to satisfy existing and future demand, the position of the US as the leader in world fertilizer production and trade is being challenged. </P>

<P><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=left> Please feel free to <A HREF="mailto:pubs@rmii.com">report any problems</A> encountered on this page.</P>

<P>If you have specific questions about any items here, please contact <A HREF="mailto:smenet@aol.com">SME</A>. <STRONG>Please be certain to address correspondence to the Meetings Department</STRONG>.

