<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h2><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h2></center>
<center><B>BULLETIN #356</B></CENTER>
<hr size=3>
Comprehensive advertising compliance information emphasizing the practical <br>
analysis of government, industry and media restrictions on advertising <br>
<hr size=3>
<p><U><B>FROM THE EDITOR IN CHIEF</B></U> </p>
<p>In its largest law enforcement action against fraud on the Internet, FTC obtained a 
federal court order temporarily halting an alleged pyramid scheme advertised on 
the Internet. Our lead article, &quot;FTC Halts Alleged Internet Advertising Scheme,&quot; 
reports on this recent FTC action. </p>
<p>Political speech goes to the very heart of what the Constitution's framers intended 
to protect by the First Amendment. When that speech is political speech by 
candidates for public office, the freedom to speak also goes to the very essence 
of free elections. So governmental restrictions on such speech are indeed a rarity. 
That didn't stop Minnesota, however, from adopting a statute that actually 
criminalizes certain types of political speech, specifically, paid political advertising. 
And one politician found himself facing possible criminal penalties for the things 
that were said in his campaign ads. Our next article, &quot;Minn. Statute that 
Criminalizes Campaign Ads Found Unconstitutional,&quot; looks at the highlights of this 
disturbing case. </p>
<p>Our next article, &quot;Your Guide to Current Key Advertising Law Issues (Part 
Two),&quot; examines many of the key issues confronting advertisers, advertising 
agencies and their counsel as we approach the millennium. </p>
<p>Our next article, &quot;What's Marketing's Speed Limit on the Information 
Superhighway?,&quot; looks at some of the speed limits and speed traps for marketers 
as they enter the Brave New World of Internet and World Wide Web 
advertising. </p>
<p>Our final article, &quot;CDA Lawsuit: An Update,&quot; is an update of recent legal 
developments in the landmark challenge to the &quot;Communications Decency Act.&quot; </p>
<p>Volume XVI<br> Issue 12<br> June 17, 1996<br> Page 1 <br>
<hr size=3>
<B>Advertising Compliance Service</B> is a REFERENCE COMPENDIUM of 
JLCom <br>Publishing Co., L.L.C. <br>
