<html>

<head>
<title>Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue: News Items</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue of 
Advertising Compliance Service: Brief News of Note">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, internet, internet, internet, Internet, Internet, Internet, Internet, 
FTC, CSPI, CDA, Jenny Craig, FTC, CSPI, CDA, Jenny Craig, FTC, CSPI, CDA, Jenny Craig, 
FTC, CSPI, CDA, Jenny Craig, FTC, CSPI, CDA, Jenny Craig, FTC, CSPI, CDA, Jenny Craig,  
Communications Decency Act, Communications Decency Act, Communications Decency Act, 
Communications Decency Act, Communications Decency Act, Communications Decency Act, 
Sensible Advertising and Family Education Act, Sensible Advertising and Family Education Act, 
ad agency, ad agency, ad agencies, ad law, lawyer, attorney, advertisement law, legal, compliance, 
advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, 
campaign ads, advertise">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h3><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h3></center>
<center><B>BULLETIN #356</B></CENTER>
<hr size=3>
<p><U><B>BRIEF NEWS OF NOTE</B></U> </p>
<p><U><B>FTC FINAL ORDER INVOLVES CAUSE-RELATED MARKETING 
CLAIMS</B></U>--FTC gave its final OK to a consent agreement with Benckiser 
Consumer Products, Inc., of Danbury, Connecticut, settling charges that it made 
false and misleading &quot;cause-related marketing&quot; claims for its &quot;EarthRite&quot; line of 
household cleaning products. The order bars Benckiser from misrepresenting that 
a portion of the revenue from the sale of any household cleaning product is 
donated to any organization. If Benckiser chooses to claim that it donates some 
portion of revenue to an organization, the order requires Benckiser to clearly and 
prominently disclose the method of determining the amount of the donation. </p>
<p>(<I>Benckiser Consumer Products, Inc</I>., FTC Dkt. No. C-3659, May 24, 1996; 
materials relating to this FTC matter are available on the Internet at FTC's World 
Wide Web site at: <a href="http://www.ftc.gov"> http://www.ftc.gov</a>.) </p>
<p><B>NOTE:</B> A consent agreement is for settlement purposes only and does not 
constitute an admission of a law violation. When the Commission issues a consent 
order on a final basis, it carries the force of law with respect to future actions. 
Each violation of such an order may result in a civil penalty of $10,000. </p>
<p><U><B>CSPI ASKS FTC TO STEP UP REGULATION OF WEIGHT-LOSS 
FIRMS</B></U>--Some of the largest commercial weight-loss programs in the U.S. don't 
tell potential customers about the full costs of their services, and fail to provide 
information about how well--or how poorly--they work, according to the Center 
for Science in the Public Interest (CSPI). CSPI examined the largest weight-loss 
programs in the nation and found that some require clients to purchase 
exorbitantly priced foods, others distort the cost of mandatory fees, and none 
routinely disclose data on how much weight their clients actually lose and keep 
off. </p>
<p>CSPI and nine other health organizations, weight-loss experts, and consumer 
advocates petitioned FTC on May 29, 1996 to step up its regulation of the 
industry. </p>
<p>In visits to Washington, D.C.-area weight-loss centers, CSPI found that: </p>
<p>&quot;Jenny Craig advertises the cost of its program as `20 pounds for $20,' but 
additional food purchases of $70-$80 each week are required. Losing 20 pounds 
at 1 pounds per week (a typical rate recommended by health experts) would cost 
more than $1,000. </p>
<p>Nutri/System advertisements tell consumers that they must buy $49 worth of food 
per week, but don't reveal that signing up for the program can cost up to $299. 
The total cost for losing 20 pounds at 1 pounds per week can amount to over 
$900. </p>
<p>Physicians Weight Loss Center implies in its name that the program is supervised 
by physicians. In fact, two of the company's diet programs are not 
physician-supervised.&quot; </p>
<p>CSPI's petition urged FTC to require weight-loss firms to provide consumers with 
standardized information about cost, program duration, effectiveness, staff 
credentials, and possible health risks. The petition charged that the failure to 
disclose such information is an &quot;unfair and deceptive practice.&quot; </p>
<p>(<I>CSPI Release</I>, May 29, 1996.) </p>
<p><U><B>COURT ORDERS JUSTICE DEPARTMENT TO STOP &quot;REVIEWS&quot; 
UNDER THE CDA</B></U>--Responding to a complaint filed by the Citizens Internet 
Empowerment Coalition (CIEC) and ACLU, a federal judge ordered the Justice 
Department to halt all &quot;reviews&quot; of complaints under the Communications 
Decency Act (CDA) until the three-judge panel has a chance to rule on the law's 
constitutionality. In issuing the order, Judge Stewart Dalzell said that &quot;the 
government's conduct in subjecting a content provider to private and public 
scrutiny for displaying material that is neither obscene nor child pornography 
clearly runs afoul of both this Court's orders and the government's promises.&quot; </p>
<p>CIEC and ACLU attorneys filed the compliant after several national newspapers 
reported that the FBI had started an investigation of Compuserve for alleged 
CDA violations. The FBI denies that any investigation is underway. But 
Compuserve faced a potentially damaging public relations problem because of the 
reports. </p>
<p>According to CIEC, the American Family Association (AFA) filed a complaint 
with the Justice Department &quot;accusing Compuserve of violating the CDA for 
material in a forum called MacGlamour, despite the fact that the site was labeled 
for adults only and Compuserve provides its users free software to block access 
to unwanted material.&quot; </p>
<p>(<I>CIEC Trial Update No. 12: Special Update</I>, May 16 1996; more information 
about this matter is available at CIEC's web page at http://www.cdt.org/ciec; see 
also: Advertising Compliance Service, &quot;CDA Lawsuit: An Update,&quot; Tab #15, 
New Media, Article #21.) </p>
<p><U><B>SWEEPING LEGISLATIVE RESTRICTIONS PROPOSED FOR 
ALCOHOL ADS</B></U>--Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II (D-MA) has 
introduced six bills designed to have a major impact on alcoholic beverage 
advertising. Rep. Kennedy's &quot;Children's Protection from Alcohol Advertising Act&quot; 
would exclude many advertising and marketing practices that have an impact on 
children. Kennedy's &quot;Sensible Advertising and Family Education Act&quot; (SAFE) 
would mandate that any remaining ads carry a rotating series of health and safety 
warnings. His proposed legislation would mandate that alcoholic beverage labels 
must reveal such information as ingredients, calories and alcohol content. </p>
<p>(<I>CSPI</I>, May 16, 1996.) </p>
<p>Volume XVI<br> Issue 12<br> June 17, 1996<br> Page 2-4 <br>
<hr size=3>
<B>Advertising Compliance Service</B> is a REFERENCE COMPENDIUM of 
JLCom <br>Publishing Co., L.L.C. <br>
