<html>

<head>
<title>Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue: Internet Advertising Law Article</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue of 
Advertising Compliance Service:  Internet Advertising Law Article">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, internet, internet, internet, Internet, Internet, Internet, Internet, 
World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, 
World Wide Web, World Wide Web, FTC, Federal trade Commission, pyramid scheme,  
FTC, Federal Trade Commission, pyramid scheme, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, pyramid scheme, 
FTC, Federal Trade Commission, pyramid scheme, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, pyramid scheme, 
FTC, Federal Trade Commission, pyramid scheme, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, pyramid scheme, 
ad law, lawyer, attorney, advertisement law, legal, compliance, FTC, 
advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, 
campaign ads, advertise">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h3><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h3></center>

<hr size=3>
<center><B>FILE: TAB #15, NEW MEDIA, ARTICLE #19</B> </center>
<hr size=3>
<center><p><h3><B>FTC HALTS ALLEGED INTERNET ADVERTISING SCHEME</B> </h3></p></center>
<p><U><B>FTC's LARGEST INTERNET FRAUD ACTION</B></U> </p>
<p>In its 12th and largest law enforcement action against fraud on the Internet, FTC 
obtained a federal court order temporarily halting an alleged pyramid scheme 
advertised on the Internet. FTC estimates that the alleged scheme has already 
taken in over $6 million. The court's temporary restraining order freezes the 
defendants' assets and appoints a receiver to manage the company, called 
Fortuna Alliance. FTC wants the court to issue a permanent injunction that will 
provide redress for consumers who FTC says were victims of the alleged scam. </p>
<p><U><B>OLD AS METHUSELAH</B></U> </p>
<p>&quot;This brand new, high-tech scam is as old as Methuselah.&quot; So said Jodie 
Bernstein, Director of FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection. She added: </p>
<p>&quot;Behind all the techno-jargon and the mathematical mumbo jumbo, this is just an 
elaborate, electronic version of a chain letter. People are told that if they sign up 
and send money, they'll eventually end up at the top of the pyramid, collecting 
from those at the bottom. But most people never make it to the top. Early entrants 
may make some money, but eventually, the pyramids collapse and most of the 
`members' are left holding the bag.&quot; </p>
<p><U><B>HOME PAGE ON THE WORLD WIDE WEB</B></U> </p>
<p>FTC charged that Fortuna Alliance, L.L.C., and five officers marketed the alleged 
pyramid scheme through a home page on the World Wide Web. FTC said the 
defendants used claims such as &quot;What if you paid...$250 a month which produced 
a minimum of $5,250 income each month for you, While you simply watched?,&quot; 
and &quot;Would you want to continue this arrangement while you kept earning $5,000 
a month,&quot; to induce thousands of consumers to pay between $250 and $1750 to 
join their alleged pyramid scheme by claiming that members would receive over 
$5,000 per month in &quot;profits&quot; as others were induced to &quot;enroll.&quot; In addition, 
Fortuna and its officers provided advice and promotional materials for members 
to set up their own web sites to recruit others to join the pyramid, FTC said. </p>
<p><U><B>FTC'S COMPLAINT</B></U> </p>
<p>According to FTC's complaint, most participants in a pyramid scheme lose 
money, so the claims that consumers who pay Fortuna $250 will receive high 
income or profits of over $5,000 per month are false and misleading. Also, 
providing others with promotional material that contains similar false claims for use 
in recruiting new participants, is deceptive or unfair, in violation of the law, FTC 
noted. FTC's complaint asks the court to order a permanent halt to the alleged 
deceptive practices and to order redress for the people that signed up. </p>
<p>In papers filed with the court, FTC argued that Fortuna already has taken over $6 
million from consumers, and transferred at least $3.55 million of that money to a 
bank in Antigua, W.I. The temporary restraining order directs defendants 
immediately to see that the money is returned to the U.S. </p>
<p>(<I>Fortuna Alliance, L.L.C., et al.</I>, FTC File No. 962-3158, May 29, 1996; FTC 
v. Fortuna Alliance, L.L.C., et al., United States District Court, Western District 
of Washington, Complaint, May 29, 1996; materials relating to this FTC matter 
are available on the Internet at FTC's World Wide Web site at: 
<a href="http://www.ftc.gov"> http://www.ftc.gov</a>.) </p>
<p>Volume XVI<br> Issue 12<br> June 17, 1996<br> Page 5-6 <br>
<hr size=3>
<B>Advertising Compliance Service</B> is a REFERENCE COMPENDIUM of 
JLCom <br>Publishing Co., L.L.C. <br>
<HR SIZE=3>

<B>NOTE:</B> Subscription inquiries should be e-mailed to <a href="mailto:lawpublish@aol.com">lawpublish@aol.com</a> or Call TOLL FREE: 
1-888-ADLAW97. (An <a href="order.htm">order form </a>can be found at this Site and can be printed out.)
<p><B>NOTICE:</B> This publication is not intended to provide legal advice. Persons who 
need legal services should contact a duly licensed professional. </p>
