<head>
<title>Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue: Campaign Ad Compliance Article</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue of 
Advertising Compliance Service: Minnesota Statute That Criminalizes Campaign Ads Found 
Unconstitutional">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, Minnesota, Minnesota, Minnesota, Minnesota, Minnesota, Minnesota, Minnesota, 
First Amendment, political speech, First Amendment, political speech, 
First Amendment, political speech, First Amendment, political speech, 
First Amendment, political speech, First Amendment, political speech, 
campaign ads, campaign ads, campaign ads, campaign ads, campaign ads, 
ad law, lawyer, attorney, advertisement law, legal, compliance, FTC, 
advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, 
campaign ads, advertise">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h3><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h3></center>

<hr size=3>
<center><B>FILE: TAB #20, POLITICAL ADS, ARTICLE #6</B> </center>
<hr size=3>
<center><p><h3><B>MINN. STATUTE THAT CRIMINALIZES CAMPAIGN ADS FOUND 
UNCONSTITUTIONAL</B></h3></p></center>

<p><U><B>STATE STATUTE CRIMINALIZES CERTAIN CAMPAIGN ADS</B></U> </p>
<p>Political speech goes to the very heart of what the Constitution's framers intended 
to protect by the First Amendment. When that speech is political speech by 
candidates for public office, the freedom to speak also goes to the very essence 
of free elections. So governmental restrictions on such speech are indeed a rarity. 
That didn't stop Minnesota, however, from adopting a statute that actually 
criminalizes certain types of political speech, specifically, paid political advertising. 
And one politician found himself facing possible criminal penalties for the things 
that were said in his campaign ads. Here are the highlights of this disturbing case: </p>
<p><U><B>MINNESOTA LAW IN QUESTION</B></U> </p>
<p>The Minnesota statute at issue in this recent case is M.S. 211B.06, &quot;False 
Political and Campaign Material.&quot; Subdivision 1 of that statute makes it a gross 
misdemeanor to prepare, disseminate or broadcast certain types of paid political 
advertising. Specifically, that statute says: </p>
<p>&quot;A person is guilty of a gross misdemeanor who intentionally participates in the 
preparation, dissemination, or broadcast of paid political advertising or campaign 
material with respect to the personal or political character or acts of a candidate, 
whether or not defamatory, or with respect to the effect of a ballot questions, that 
the person knows or has reason to believe is false and that is designed or tends to 
elect, injure, or defeat a candidate for nomination or election to a public office or 
to promote or defeat a ballot questions.&quot; </p>
<p><U><B>1994 CONGRESSIONAL CAMPAIG</B></U>N </p>
<p>During the 1994 campaign for the Sixth District congressional seat, Tad Jude's 
campaign broadcast a television ad that showed a Minneapolis police 
officer--appearing in a generic police uniform--reading the ad's script. The 
disputed ad's text focused on a crime that had occurred and claimed &quot;Patten may 
never have been released and this crime never committed had legislation authored 
by Tad Jude been enacted.&quot; The ad went on to claim that this legislation was 
stopped by his Congressional opponent for the Sixth District congressional seat, 
Bill Luther, and &quot;his liberal friends in the Minnesota Senate.&quot; </p>
<p><U><B>WHAT HAPPENED NEXT</B></U> </p>
<p>On November 7, 1994, Luther &quot;formally asked the Anoka County prosecutor to 
determine whether [Jude] had committed a crime.&quot; On May 2, 1995, Jude 
received a letter from Hennepin County Attorney's office telling him that they 
would now pursue Luther's complaint. On June 21, 1995, Jude interviewed with 
the Hennepin County Attorney's office. On November 28, 1995, Jude testified to 
the Hennepin County grand jury and was indicted. </p>
<p><U><B>MCLU'S AMICUS BRIEF: STATE FALSE CAMPAIGN MATERIAL LAW 
IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL</B></U> </p>
<p>On January 31, 1996, the Minnesota Civil Liberties Union announced that it 
would file an amicus brief in the criminal case against former congressional 
candidate Tad Jude in Hennepin County District Court. MCLU argued in its brief 
that even false campaign statements are entitled to constitutional protection. </p>
<p>&quot;False or controversial statements are inevitable in the heat of political discussions 
and debate,&quot; said MCLU Executive Director Michael Moore. &quot;Imposing criminal 
sanctions on candidates who make false statements in political ads has a chilling 
effect on free speech that ultimately hinders the political process far more than the 
false statements would.&quot; </p>
<p>MCLU argued that any criminal sanction for political speech is unconstitutional. 
Alternatively, MCLU argued that if the court finds that the state may 
constitutionally sanction political speech, it must apply a more restrictive standard 
than that contained in Minnesota's False Political and Campaign material statute. </p>
<p>MCLU noted that the indictment here was based on two sentences from the ad: 
(1) &quot;Patten may never have been released and this crime never committed had 
legislation authored by Tad Jude been enacted&quot;; and (2) &quot;But Jude's bill was 
stopped by Bill Luther and his liberal friends in the Minnesota Senate.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;In 1990,&quot; MCLU said, &quot;Patten was on a pre-release furlough when he 
committed the offenses described in Jude's ad. However, the offense for which 
Daniel Patten was incarcerated was committed in 1983. Therefore, the legislation 
that Jude introduced in 1988 would not have had any effect on Patten's sentence 
or release date.&quot; </p>
<p>However, MCLU pointed out, &quot;the Jude campaign's media consultant testified 
before the grand jury that he believed that the ad was true and that he had no 
reason to think that Jude knew that the ad was not true. Jude also testified that he 
`took every reasonable step under the circumstances to make sure it was true.'&quot; </p>
<p><U><B>STATUTE OVERLY BROAD AND UNCONSTITUTIONAL</B></U> </p>
<p>On March 1, 1996, Hennepin County Judge Robert Lynn dismissed the 
indictment against Tad Jude. He called the law (M.S. 211B.06) &quot;overly broad&quot; 
and unconstitutional. In response to the ruling Tad Jude said, &quot;I'm not the only 
winner today with Judge Lynn's ruling. The property taxpayers and voters of 
Anoka, Washington, and Dakota Counties are the winners.&quot; </p>
<p><U><B>NOT THE END</B></U> </p>
<p>However, the dismissal of the indictment is not the end of the story. On March 7, 
1996, the State Attorney General's office took the case from Hennepin County 
and seeks to appeal it. </p>
<p>Chris Georgacas, State Republican Chairman, said this decision to appeal the 
indictment has &quot;little to do with the law, everything to do with preserving DFL 
incumbents.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;Skip Humphrey [Minnesota's Attorney General] is perpetuating the DFL party's 
current campaign against free speech,&quot; said Georgacas in harshly criticizing 
Attorney General Hubert Humphrey's decision to appeal the ruling by Hennepin 
County District Judge Robert Lynn that a Minnesota law regulating political 
speech is unconstitutional. &quot;Whether through Leland Lynch's ill-considered 
Campaign Advertising Code or now by this appeal, Democrat Party chieftains are 
attempting an all-out effort to restrict challenger candidates from engaging in 
vigorous, yet responsible free speech in this election-year,&quot; said Georgacas. He 
noted that, &quot;No other state in the country has such an over-reaching law.&quot; </p>
<p>Minnesota Attorney General Humphrey has already taken an extremely expansive 
view of his state's jurisdiction over the Internet, including advertising. (See 
Advertising Compliance Service, &quot;Advertising on the Internet: Who Has 
Jurisdiction?,&quot; Tab #15, New Media, Article #13.) </p>
<p><U><B>LAWYER'S REFERENCE SERVICE</B></U> </p>
<p>Minnesota statute: M.S. 211B.06, &quot;False Political and Campaign Material.&quot; </p>
<p>See also: </p>
<p><B>Advertising Compliance Service</B>, &quot;Advertising on the Internet: Who Has 
Jurisdiction?,&quot; Tab #15, New Media, Article #13.) </p>
<p>Volume XVI<br> Issue 12<br> June 17, 1996<br> Page 7-11 <br>
<hr size=3>
<B>Advertising Compliance Service</B> is a REFERENCE COMPENDIUM of 
JLCom <br>Publishing Co., L.L.C. <br>
