<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue: Your Guide to Current Key Advertising Law Issues</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue of 
Advertising Compliance Service: Your Guide to Current Key Advertising Law Issues">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, CDA, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, CDA, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, CDA, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, CDA, World Wide Web, CIEC, ACLU, World Wide Web, CIEC, ACLU, World Wide Web, CIEC, ACLU, 
World Wide Web, CIEC, ACLU, World Wide Web, CIEC, ACLU, World Wide Web, CIEC, ACLU, 
puffery, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, puffery, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, 
puffery, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, puffery, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, 
puffery, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, puffery, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, 
advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h3><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h3></center>

<hr size=3>
<center><B>FILE: TAB #2, GENERAL ARTICLES, ARTICLE #274</B> </center>
<hr size=3>
<center><p><h3><B>YOUR GUIDE TO CURRENT KEY ADVERTISING LAW ISSUES (Part Two.)</B></h3></p></center>

<p>(Ed.'s Note: Part One of this two-part article appears in <B>Advertising Compliance Service</B> at Tab 
#2, General Articles, Article #272.) </p>
<p><U><B>IMPACT OF NEW TELECOMMUNICATIONS ACT</B></U> </p>
<p>On February 8, 1996, President Clinton signed into law the Telecommunications Act of 1996. 
The measure sailed through the House on February 1, 1996, 414-16, and then through the 
Senate, by an equally lopsided vote of 91-5. The new telecommunication law is 280 pages in 
length and requires 80 different proceedings by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC). 
So complex is this measure that another telecommunications Act may be needed in 1997 to 
correct problems in this labyrinthine act. </p>
<p>The world of advertising is sure to change as a result of this law as cable companies hasten 
delivery of high-speed modems connecting customers to the Internet, enabling new computer 
services and the availability of vast amounts of data cheaply. Telephone companies may offer 
movies on demand and interactive TV. Broadcasters may ultimately offer multiple channels of 
programming, bringing change not only to programming but to advertising as well. </p>
<p>One portion of the new law has nothing to do with deregulation: the Communications Decency 
Act (CDA). The CDA criminalizes the expression of information and ideas over computer 
communications systems. Under the CDA, people may be fined up to $250,000 fine and/or face 
up to two years in prison if they transmit indecent materials over computer networks. </p>
<p>You can expect fierce legal battles over this new measure. The first legal challenge to the Act was 
filed on the very day the measure was signed into law: February 8, 1996! On that date, the 
Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), an Internet civil-liberties group, American Civil Liberties 
Union (ACLU), and 18 other civil-liberties groups challenged the Act's censorship provisions on 
First Amendment and other Constitutional grounds. </p>
<p>In a separate action, a coalition representing a broad spectrum of Internet users, access providers, 
content providers and publishers filed a lawsuit on February 26, 1996 in a federal court in 
Philadelphia seeking to overturn the CDA. The challenge argues that the Internet is a unique 
communications technology deserving of First Amendment protections at least as broad as those 
enjoyed as by the print medium. The group--called the Citizens Internet Empowerment Coalition 
(CIEC)--has 35 members, including advertisers, book publishers, newspaper publishers, editors, 
commercial online service providers, ISP's, non-profit groups, libraries, and civil liberties 
advocates. </p>
<p>Named Plaintiffs in the CIEC suit include such heavyweights as Microsoft Corporation, Microsoft 
Network, Apple Computer, Inc., America Online, Inc., Compuserve, Inc., Prodigy, Inc., 
Recording Industry Association of America, and Newspaper Association of America. </p>
<p>CIEC called its suit &quot;a landmark effort that will determine the fate of the Internet and the future of 
free expression in the Information Age.&quot; CIEC noted that-- </p>
<p>&quot;Every user of the Internet is a content provider under the Communications Decency Act (CDA) 
and could be subject to fines and prison sentences under the new law. If you post messages to an 
open listserv, Usenet newsgroups, participate in IRC or chat sessions, or maintain your own 
personal Web Page, ftp or gopher archive, you may be subject to fines up to $250,000 or 2 
years in prison under the CDA if someone, somewhere, finds the material you post to be 
`indecent' or `patently offensive'&quot;. </p>
<p>These groups are outraged that the measure criminalizes information on the Internet that's now 
legal in the print medium. They believe this Act will make the federal government far bigger and 
more intrusive than ever. </p>
<p>Advertisers and advertising agencies both have a large and rapidly growing presence on the 
Internet, particularly on the World Wide Web. The signing into law of this bill means that if you 
have something on your Web site that might be considered &quot;indecent&quot; in some community 
somewhere in the U.S., you may face a $250,000 fine and/or two years in prison. </p>
<p>You can also expect a growing &quot;chilling effect&quot; that this new law will have on the growing legion of 
advertisers and advertising agencies who have web sites on the Internet's World Wide Web. 
What will the advertising community do while it awaits the outcome of the barrage of lawsuits 
based on this new law? Some Internet observers contend that there will be &quot;a tidal wave&quot; of 
self-censorship on the Internet that will go far beyond what the new law ultimately will mean. After 
all, the prospect of two years in prison and a huge fine certainly raises the stakes for anyone 
considering using this new medium for marketing purposes. </p>
<p>The problem now is the uncertainty caused by the new Act. Until courts have had a chance to 
review the new law--a time-consuming process--advertisers and ad agencies are without clear 
guidance as to what they can and can't do in this new medium. The stakes for content providers 
for Web Sites has gone up enormously. Advertising, after all, is intimately involved with creativity. 
Do advertising creatives now have to &quot;dumb down&quot; their web page offerings in light of what the 
worst judge in the least enlightened jurisdiction might think of their creative efforts? </p>
<p>Also, your Internet Service Provider may have to screen your web pages for anything that one of 
your users somewhere in the U.S. could find &quot;indecent.&quot; Some observers believe the inevitable 
result will be an overblown government bureaucracy that will compel many small advertisers and 
ad agencies to get off the World Wide Web and restrict the remaining advertisers and ad agencies 
to severely restrict their offerings on the Web. </p>
<p>On February 15, 1996, a federal judge did issue a partial temporary restraining order barring 
enforcement of the Communications Decency Act's (CDA) &quot;indecency&quot; provision. However, 
Judge Ronald Buckwalter refused to enjoin those provisions of the Act dealing with &quot;patently 
offensive&quot; communications. </p>
<p>Judge Buckwalter agreed with plaintiffs' claim that the CDA will have a chilling effect on free 
speech on the Internet and concluded that the CDA raises &quot;serious, substantial, difficult and 
doubtful questions.&quot; Moreover, Judge Buckwalter agreed that the CDA is &quot;unconstitutionally 
vague&quot; as to the prosecution for indecency. However, the court left open the possibility that the 
government could prosecute under the &quot;patently offensive&quot; or &quot;obscene&quot; provisions. Many First 
Amendment experts have called these provisions redundant since obscenity is already illegal both 
in Cyberspace and outside of it. These experts say that obscenity laws aren't dependent on a 
particular medium as are indecency laws and have in fact already been enforced against online 
services. </p>
<p><U><B>STREAMLINING OF FTC: ADVERTISING'S CHIEF REGULATOR</B></U> </p>
<p>You can expect the continuing streamlining of FTC in the months and years ahead. Already in 
1996, that agency has taken steps resulting in the elimination of thousands of old FTC orders. 
Under a new &quot;sunset&quot; policy, FTC is clearing the decks of old FTC orders that have long since 
served their purpose. FTC has also eliminating many outdated trade regulation rules and industry 
guides as part of its ongoing program to streamline its oversight of industry activities. Accordingly, 
you can expect a leaner, meaner FTC in the years ahead. </p>
<p><U><B>WILL PUFFERY COME TO AN END?</B></U> </p>
<p>It seems far less likely today than a year ago. Such advertising slogans as &quot;Nobody doesn't Like 
Sara Lee?&quot; have long been considered &quot;puffery&quot; and so immune from substantiation requirements. 
However, a proposed revision to Article 2 of the U.S. Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) by the 
National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws committee would have changed 
all that. </p>
<p>Drafted in the 1950's, the Code recommended that state legislatures adopt a uniform body of 
laws governing key commercial transactions. The Code was later adopted with slight variations by 
every state except Louisiana plus the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico. </p>
<p>American law has always recognized the difference between puffery and factual ad claims. The 
law does not require substantiation for the former, but does for the latter. The committee was 
thinking about requiring it of both. </p>
<p>This clearly would have had a devastating potential impact on the advertising industry if it were 
adopted. The committee's first draft actually would have eliminated the distinction between puffery 
and affirmations of fact altogether. But the advertising industry quickly responded and a later draft 
reinstated the puffery/factual claims distinction. However, some observers contend that this draft 
still amounts to a de facto ban of puffery. So look for swift industry reaction to any proposal that 
would change the centuries-old legal rules involving puffery. </p>
<p><U><B>BROADER ALLOWANCE OF CERTAIN CLAIMS</B></U> </p>
<p>You should look for the broader allowance of certain types of claims in the future by regulators. 
One example: direct-to-consumer advertising of prescription drugs. You can expect at least some 
changes in the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) current rules involving the advertising of 
prescription drugs. Pressure has been building at FDA to loosen certain restrictions on these rules. 
Activity in this area is sure to occur in the months and years ahead. </p>
<p>Another area where you can expect to see a greater allowance of claims is in the health claims 
area. Already, one recent proposal would allow manufacturers of foods containing oatmeal or oat 
bran to claim on the labels that diets high in these grain products and low in saturated fat and 
cholesterol may reduce the risk of coronary heart disease. Other proposals are sure to follow in 
the future. </p>
<p><U><B>LONG-STANDING PRINCIPLES OF AD REGULATION WILL CONTINUE</B></U> </p>
<p>Finally, with all the changes, there should be a recognition that the many long-standing principles 
that guide advertising law will continue. A strong working knowledge of the myriad federal and 
state cases, decisions, orders, rules, regulations and rulings involving advertising law is vital for any 
serious advertising professional. This vast body of law will continue to grow and evolve. Your 
goal is to stay current with this important area of law. </p>
<p><U><B>LAWYER'S REFERENCE SERVICE</B></U> </p>
