<title>Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue: WHAT'S MARKETING'S SPEED LIMIT ON THE INFORMATION 
SUPERHIGHWAY?</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue of 
Advertising Compliance Service: WHAT'S MARKETING'S SPEED LIMIT ON THE INFORMATION 
SUPERHIGHWAY?">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, Internet, Telecommunications, globalization, Communications Decency 
Act, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web,  World Wide Web, 
Telecommunications Act of 1996, advertisers, ad agencies, Telecommunications Act of 1996, advertisers, ad agencies, 
Telecommunications Act of 1996, advertisers, ad agencies, Telecommunications Act of 1996, advertisers, ad agencies, 
information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, 
information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, 
domain names, trademark, copyright, domain names, trademark, copyright, 
domain names, trademark, copyright, domain names, trademark, copyright, 
advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h3><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h3></center>

<hr size=3>
<center><B>FILE: TAB #15, NEW MEDIA, ARTICLE #20</B> </center>
<hr size=3>
<center><p><h3><B>WHAT'S MARKETING'S SPEED LIMIT ON THE INFORMATION 
SUPERHIGHWAY?</B></h3></p></center>

<p>By <br>
<p>Stephen R. Bergerson* <br>
<p><U><B>LEGAL RAMIFICATIONS OF CYBERSPACE MARKETING</B></U> </p>
<p>More and more of today's marketing managers are driving sleeker and faster 
technological innovations down the information highway. They've recognized the 
Internet's ability to get them from Marketing Central to the consumer--and back 
again--faster than the speed of light. </p>
<p>But in the excitement of putting their foot to the floor and fixing their focus on the 
finish line, many are turning a blind eye to the legal ramifications of racing into 
marketspace. </p>
<p><U><B>SPEED LIMITS AND SPEED TRAPS</B></U> </p>
<p>Contrary to popular belief, there are speed limits on the Superhighway. And 
speed traps. It's still a frontier, but it's anything but lawless. For over 20 years, the 
Internet was a &quot;free&quot; environment, but that was before it was commercialized. 
And where commerce goes, the law always follows. So today's cybermanagers 
need to keep their heads up and their eyes on the road, or they're sure to exceed 
marketspace speed limits. Here's a checklist of the kinds of traps that lie ahead. </p>
<p><U><B>DOMAIN NAMES AND TRADEMARKS</B></U> </p>
<p>Internet domain names like TIDE.COM and CHEEZWHIZ.COM can be 
registered with Internic on a first-come, first-served basis. But if a domain name 
infringes on a pre-existing trademark, the domain name and its owner become 
legal lightening rods and tend to attract sharp, thunderous and very heated 
responses. To avoid being jolted, marketers need to do a trademark search 
before using or registering a domain name, and to give very careful thought to 
registering it with the Federal Trademark Office. </p>
<p><U><B>HOME PAGE COPYRIGHT ISSUES</B></U> </p>
<p>Copyright law creates at least three significant web site ownership issues. Since 
copyright law give a copyright owner nearly exclusive control over the right to 
use, distribute, display, perform and copy or make derivatives of the work, 
copyright ownership questions are important. And the answers are frequently 
surprising, because copyright in a creative work is generally owned by the person 
who created it (not the person who &quot;paid&quot; for it) unless (a) the creator is an actual 
employee who created the work within the scope of their employment or (b) it's 
created by an independent contractor who specifically agrees in writing that the 
commissioning party will own copyright in it. </p>
<p>Since marketers usually hire independent contractors to create their web site 
content code and overall &quot;look and feel,&quot; and all are protected by copyright, they 
need to be aware of the rules of copyright ownership. </p>
<p><U><B>GLOBAL LEGAL EXPOSURE</B></U> </p>
<p>The Internet's global capability has significant legal implications. Both large and 
small &quot;cyvertisers&quot; immediately become global advertisers. Since Internet 
advertising and promotions are seen around the world, and laws vary widely from 
place to place, &quot;cyvertising&quot; creates unprecedented legal exposure. Who has legal 
jurisdiction at every point along the Highway? Is it the state or country where the 
advertising and promotions are uploaded? Downloaded? All? The question hasn't 
been answered yet, but regulators are looking long and hard at where they can set 
their traps. </p>
<p>Some, including Minnesota Attorney General Humphrey, are doing more than 
looking at or talking about it. Humphrey's office has already charged several 
cyvertisers with violating Minnesota's consumer fraud, false advertising and 
deceptive trade practice statues. </p>
<p>FTC is now actively monitoring the Internet and recently announced settlements 
with eight different cyvertisers, and litigation against a ninth. One FTC 
commissioner said &quot;If it's deceptive on earth, it's deceptive in cyberspace.&quot; </p>
<p>So much for the lawless frontier. </p>
<p><U><B>PRIVACY ISSUES</B></U> </p>
<p>There are several ways to get caught in the privacy trap. One is to use a living 
person's name or likeness for commercial purposes. That is recognized as an 
invasion of privacy in nearly every state in this country, not to mention foreign 
laws. </p>
<p>Ignoring the public's growing obsession about the commercial use of personal 
information also raises significant privacy issues. The U.S. Commerce Department 
recently issued a report calling on telephone, on-line, cable and satellite TV 
industries to tell their users exactly what personal information they are gathering, 
how it is to be used and threatening formal regulations if companies don't start 
obtaining explicit approval from consumers before using or sharing &quot;sensitive&quot; 
data. </p>
<p><U><B>CRACKERS AND FLAMERS</B></U> </p>
<p>Since the Internet has its share of crackers who like to infect programs with 
viruses, and flamers, who send insulting or even nasty messages to individuals or 
companies, marketers need to draft sweepstakes and other sales promotion rules 
to provide for contingencies created by these kinds of meddlers. They also need 
to be more careful than ever with eligibility, deadlines, &quot;void in . . .,&quot; and other 
traditional rules issues which take on a whole new hue on the Net. </p>
<p><U><B>CONTENT LIABILITY</B></U> </p>
<p>Content liability creates very real issues for online marketers. As they collaborate 
with online providers, who is responsible for the content, including libel and 
copyright infringement? The service provider? The sponsor? Both? And since all 
Internet users can now alter any advertising message, content liability raises more 
questions than there are answers for. </p>
<p><U><B>INDUSTRY LIABILITY</B></U> </p>
<p>The recently enacted Telecommunications Act of 1996 makes using the Net to 
distribute &quot;indecent&quot; or &quot;patently offensive&quot; material to minors a crime. A federal 
judge has temporarily enjoined enforcement of the former, but allowed it for the 
latter. Since the law doesn't define &quot;patently offensive&quot; and many find lots of ads 
to be just that the time bomb is ticking. </p>
<p><U><B>LICENSING AGREEMENTS</B></U> </p>
<p>Marketers who negotiate rights to use music, photographs, illustrations, 
trademarks, designs or people's names or likenesses on-line need to be sure that 
the licensing agreement specifically allows such use, or they will exceed the scope 
of the license and infringe on the owner's rights. They also need to know that the 
Screen Actors Guide (SAG) is claiming that additional residuals are due its 
members when they appeal in live-action video on the Net or CD-ROM. </p>
<p><U><B>TAXES</B></U> </p>
<p>Where there's revenue, there's revenuers. State, local governments are already 
discussing sales and service tax issues relating to on-line services. Since there are 
50 states plus D.C., and thousands of local governments with tax laws, this will 
get very complicated, so stay in touch with your tax advisor. </p>
<p>As marketers race into space, they need to watch where they're going. There are 
speed limits . . . and speed traps. And the costs of getting pulled over can be very 
high. </p>
<p><U><B>LAWYER'S REFERENCE SERVICE</B></U> </p>
<p>For recent ad compliance information involving the areas discussed in this article, 
see: </p>
<p><I>Globalization</I> </p>
<p><B>Advertising Compliance Service</B>, &quot;Ad Compliance and the Emerging Global 
Marketplace: Recent Speech,&quot; Tab #26, International Advertising, Article #29. </p>
<p><I>Internet</I> </p>
<p><B>Advertising Compliance Service</B>, &quot;FTC Launches Wholesale Crackdown On 
Deceptive Ads In Cyberspace,&quot; Tab #15, New Media, Article #17. </p>
<p><B>Advertising Compliance Service</B>, &quot;Telecommunications Act of 1996: Impact on 
