<head>
<title>Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue: Communications Decency Act Lawsuit: An Update</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising Law: Free Online Sample Issue of 
Advertising Compliance Service: Communications Decency Act Lawsuit: An Update">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, advertising law, 
Internet, Telecommunications, Communications Decency 
Act, Internet, Telecommunications, Communications Decency Act, Internet, Telecommunications, Communications Decency 
Act, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web, World Wide Web,  World Wide Web, 
Telecommunications Act of 1996, Telecommunications Act of 1996, 
Telecommunications Act of 1996, Telecommunications Act of 1996, 
information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, 
information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace, information superhighway, cyberspace">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p><h3><B>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</B> </h3></center>

<hr size=3>
<center><B>FILE: TAB #15, NEW MEDIA, ARTICLE #21</B> </center>
<hr size=3>
<center><p><h3><B>CDA LAWSUIT: AN UPDATE</B></h3></p></center>

<p><U><B>CLOSING ARGUMENTS HEARD</B></U> </p>
<p>On May 10, 1996, a three-judge panel heard closing arguments in the case of 
ACLU v. Reno concerning the so-called &quot;Communications Decency Act&quot; (CDA). 
(Those portions of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 that criminalize 
expression of information and ideas over computer communications systems are 
known as the CDA.) Ever since the law became effective--February 8, 
1996--people have faced fines of up to $250,000 and/or up to two years in 
prison if they transmitted &quot;indecent&quot; materials over computer networks. </p>
<p><U><B>BACKGROUND</B></U> </p>
<p>On February 15, 1996, however, a federal judge issued a partial temporary 
restraining order barring enforcement of the CDA's &quot;indecency&quot; provision. Judge 
Ronald Buckwalter refused to enjoin those provisions of the Act dealing with 
&quot;patently offensive&quot; communications. </p>
<p>Judge Buckwalter agreed with plaintiffs' claim that the CDA will have a chilling 
effect on free speech on the Internet and concluded that the CDA raises &quot;serious, 
substantial, difficult and doubtful questions.&quot; Moreover, Judge Buckwalter agreed 
that the CDA is &quot;unconstitutionally vague&quot; as to the prosecution for indecency. 
However, the court left open the possibility that the government could prosecute 
under the &quot;patently offensive&quot; or &quot;obscene&quot; provisions. Many First Amendment 
experts have called these provisions redundant since obscenity is already illegal 
both in Cyberspace and outside of it. These experts say that obscenity laws aren't 
dependent on a particular medium as are indecency laws and have in fact already 
been enforced against online services. </p>
<p><U><B>GOVERNMENT'S CLOSING ARGUMENT</B></U> </p>
<p>In its closing argument on May 10, 1996, the government proposed forcing 
Internet users to label indecent or patently offensive words or images with an 
electronic &quot;tag.&quot; After questioning from the judges, the government acknowledged 
the impossibility of implementing this scheme with current technology. </p>
<p>That concession alone, ACLU said, could justify granting plaintiff's motion for a 
preliminary injunction against the CDA's censorship provisions. &quot;It's about time 
that the government conceded what the cyberspace community has known all 
along--that this is an unworkable law,&quot; said Christopher Hansen, who presented 
oral arguments for the ACLU. &quot;And even if it were feasible, it is constitutionally 
unthinkable to give the government the power to restrict valuable speech, or to 
compel people to pejoratively label their speech.&quot; </p>
<p>The government also admitted that the CDA criminalizes speech that does have 
value (e.g., artistic, literary or even medical information) and not just 
&quot;pornography&quot; or other prurient words or images not covered under existing 
obscenity laws. As Hansen told the Court, Congress made sure that the CDA 
applied specifically to libraries and educational institutions, and rejected several 
opportunities to make any exceptions for valuable speech. </p>
<p>&quot;The government is basically saying `trust me' when it comes to determining what 
kind of online words and images will be considered `indecent' or `patently 
offensive,'&quot; said Marjorie Heins, an ACLU lawyer. &quot;But they were not able to 
offer a coherent explanation as to what those terms mean.&quot; </p>
<p><U><B>THREE ESSENTIAL POINTS</B></U> </p>
<p>Overall, ACLU said, plaintiffs succeeded in making three essential points to the 
court: </p>
<UL><LI><p>The CDA is a criminal statute with criminal penalties.
<LI><p>The CDA is aimed specifically at constitutionally protected speech. 
<LI><p>The government's tagging scheme would force everyone to censor himself/herself 
to avoid risk of criminal prosecution.</UL>
<p><U><B>BROAD APPLICABILITY</B></U> </p>
<p>Plaintiffs also reminded the Court that the CDA censorship law applies not only to 
Web Sites, but to newsgroups, chat rooms, and other vital Internet areas. ACLU 
argued in its brief--and the government largely conceded--that various schemes 
for self-censorship would be unworkable in these environments as well. </p>
<p>At the end of the May 10 proceedings, Chief Judge Dolores K. Sloviter said the 
Court would issue a ruling &quot;in due course.&quot; Under expedited provisions, any 
appeal on rulings on the CDA will be made directly to the U.S. Supreme Court. </p>
<p><U><B>LAWYER'S REFERENCE SERVICE</B></U> </p>
<p><I>ACLU Press Release: ACLU v. Reno Trial Update</I>, May 10, 1996. </p>
<p>See also: </p>
<p><B>Advertising Compliance Service</B>, &quot;Telecommunications Act of 1996: Impact on 
Advertisers, Ad Agencies,&quot; (Parts One-Two) Tab #15, New Media, Articles #14 
and 16.) </p>
<p>Volume XVI<br> Issue 12<br> June 17, 1996<br> Page 21-22 <br>
