<title>Advertising Law - Valuable Information in Advertising Compliance 
Service</title>

<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="description" content="Describes how advertisers, advertising 
agencies and their attorneys can use the valuable information found in 
Advertising Compliance Service">
<meta name="keywords" content="law, advertising, advertising law, advertising 
law, FTC, FDA, NAD, NARB, BBB, Federal Trade Commission, ad agency, ad agency, 
ad agencies, ad law, lawyer, attorney, advertisement law, legal, compliance, 
FTC, FTC, FTC, FTC, FTC, NAD NAD, advertising self-regulation, substantiation, 
false advertising, unfair advertising, deceptive advertising, false, unfair, 
deceptive ads, deception, advertise">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<body>

<h2><p align=center><strong>Your Online Guide to Advertising Compliance 
Service</strong></center></p></h2>

<p>From traditional print and broadcast media to the <i>cutting edge of 
Cyberspace</i>, <strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</strong> is a 
twice-monthly <b>REFERENCE COMPENDIUM</b> that has provided its subscribers 
in-depth, timely and insightful coverage of the <a href="adlaw.htm">vast 
advertising law area </a>for 15 years! U.S. advertising is a $170 billion 
industry. Television accounts for some $60 billion. Radio takes in about $10 
billion. The print, and other, media account for nearly all of the rest. 
<strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</strong> covers all of the important 
cases, decisions, rulings, rules, regulations, consent decrees and orders 
flowing from the federal and state courts and regulatory bodies affecting 
the advertisers, advertising agencies and marketers--large and small--that 
make up this immense industry.</p>

<p> <strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</strong> provides in-depth, 
timely and insightful coverage of legal developments in <i>the burgeoning 
Internet and Web advertising market </i>as well. While relatively tiny compared to 
the traditional media (under $100 million in ad revenues), this market is poised 
to take off <i>like a rocket</i>! And our legal and regulatory system 
is racing to keep up. If you're involved with advertising, it's essential 
to know the latest legal developments. The <strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE 
SERVICE</strong> ensures that you do. </p> Subscribe now and you will receive: </p>

<ul>
<li><b>24 ISSUES</b>, annually, packed with crucial advertising compliance 
information. These Issues are designed to give you <b>DOUBLE VALUE</b>: <I>Immediate 
and Long-Term</i>! Read each Issue as it arrives to stay current with all key 
advertising legal developments. Then, file each information-packed article 
in one of our 26 "tabs." (This step takes no more than a minute or two.) 
This lets you refer back to the valuable information in these articles again and 
again in the future. Use the comprehensive <a href="suppleme.htm">INDEX</a> (Main 
<i>and</i> Supplementary) and numerous <a href="table.htm">TABLES</a> (Main 
<i>and</i> Supplementary) to help you find the topic or case or decision you're 
looking for. (Click "<a href="suppleme.htm">INDEX</a>" to see an online copy of the 
Supplementary Index or "<a href="table.htm">TABLES</a>" to see an example of just 
one Supplementary Table anywhere on this page.)<br>

<li><b>6 SPECIAL REPORTS</b>, annually, with full texts of landmark decisions, 
legislation, rules, regulations, cases and analyses. <br>

<li><b>THE TWO-VOLUME BASIC REFERENCE SET</b> containing Volumes XV and XVI already filed to date in two quality 3-ring binders with the <i>46 most recent issues</i>! (Future 3-ring binders are sent to subscribers periodically to 
house the future growth--<i>and enhance the value</i>--of <b>Advertising 
Compliance Service</b>.) That's <i>over 175 articles and nearly 1,000 information-filled pages</i>! It's a $900 value and it's yours as part of your initial subscription price!<br>

<li>Brand-new <b><a href="suppleme.htm">INDEX</a></b> with over 2,000 entries to <i>speed</i> your research <i>and</i> 
<b><a href="table.htm">TABLES</a></b> of court decisions, Federal Trade Commission cases, and 
National Advertising Division/National Advertising Review Board decisions 
help you make sure your advertising is in compliance with all federal rules and 
self-regulatory guidelines.<br>
</ul>

<p>If you read each <strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</strong> Issue 
and Special Report, you would know: </p>

<ul>
<li>How the government is training its big guns at tobacco advertisers and 
what that portends for other advertisers. The next major target: Alcoholic 
beverage advertisers. (For a glimpse at some of the salvoes fired in the 
anti-tobacco advertising war, check out our "<a href="doc.htm">Important 
Advertising Law-Related Documents</a>" page now!)<br>

<li>How one Appeals Court recently came down in favor of a <i>very expansive 
definition</i> of just what is a "commercial advertisement" for purposes of 
Lanham Act false advertising lawsuits. This fairly common type of advertising 
lawsuit should become even more common now. Other federal courts have also 
ruled that the Lanham Act applies to a broad range of deceptive statements found 
in advertisements. Remedies have ranged from injunctive relief to <b>damage 
awards as high as $40 million</b> in one comparative advertising case.<br>

<li>How legislators, federal regulators and state attorneys general successfully 
made a massive push to gain jurisdictional control of advertising on the 
Internet. Many articles in <b>Advertising Compliance Service</b> examine this 
major trend, keeping our subscribers alert to these important developments. 
Many advertisers--large and small--hit with fines and penalties seem stunned and 
were clearly unaware of their advertising legal compliance duties on this new medium.<br>

<li>As you probably know, two lower federal courts knocked down the vague and 
overbroad Federal &quot;Communications Decency Act (CDA),&quot; as unconstitutional. 
So your Internet and World Wide Web ads (and other speech) are safe, right? 
<i>Wrong</i>! You could be prosecuted for those ads under the CDA <i> from 
February 8, 1996 onwards</i> if your Internet or Web ads fall within that Act! 
How? If the U.S. Supreme Court upholds the CDA when it decides the case next 
year! Under the CDA, information now legal in the print medium (including 
sections of the King James Bible or photographs of Michelangelo's Sistine 
Chapel paintings) may carry a <b>$250,000 fine or two years of prison</b> 
if carried on the Internet. Many experts <i>think</i> the Supreme Court will 
overturn the CDA. But there is definitely no guarantee that they will do so.<br>

<li>Why following traditional advertising guidelines may not be enough 
to ensure that your Internet, Web and online advertising complies with 
all federal, state, local and self-regulatory laws, rules, regulations 
and guidelines.<br>

<li>What &quot;Brave New World&quot; advertisers are facing in the 
wake of the newly passed Telecommunications Act of 1996. What happens to your 
advertising budget when the entire telecommunications industry ends up in 
the hands of a few companies, as some experts believe?<br>

<li>Why the rules on securing copyrights and consent forms on the 
Internet may differ from other traditional media.<br>
</ul>

<p>Recent issues of <strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE SERVICE</strong> have 
given subscribers crucial information on:</p>

<ul>
<li>Circumstances under which a customer letter can be considered 
an &quot;advertisement&quot; vulnerable to court challenges of &quot;false 
and misleading&quot; information.<br>

<li>The many avenues you can pursue when combating your competitors' 
false or misleading advertising claims as well as the many legally 
acceptable claims your ads can make when drawing comparisons to your 
competitors' product.<br>

<li>The courts' new-found and dangerous power to declare published 
articles--about your product or service--&quot;commercial advertising 
or promotion&quot; which can lead to costly litigation and damages. <br>

<li>Why something as simple as a camera angle or camera lens used in a 
television commercial could run afoul of federal rules, resulting in 
costly penalties. <br>

<li>With all advertising media receiving an increasing amount of scrutiny, 
you can't afford NOT to subscribe to <strong>ADVERTISING COMPLIANCE 
SERVICE</strong>. Print out and mail the order form below with a check, 
today, to receive your 24 ISSUES, annually, packed with crucial 
advertising compliance information; 6 SPECIAL REPORTS, annually, with 
full texts of landmark decisions, legislation, rules, regulations, cases 
and analyses; and TWO BASIC REFERENCE VOLUMES including two 3-ring binders filled with the 46 latest issues! <br>
</ul>
<p>Sincerely, </p>

<p>
<p>
John Lichtenberger, Esq.<br>
