<head>
<title>Advertising Agencies, Advertisers and their Attorneys Astonished by Size of Costly Fines and Penalties</title>
<meta name="description" content="Advertising agencies, advertisers and 

their attorneys are amazed by the size of the fines and penalties imposed 

for alleged false and/or deceptive advertising">
<meta name="keywords" content="advertising agencies, advertising agencies, 

advertising agencies, advertising agencies, advertising agencies, advertising 

agencies, ad agency, ad agency, ad agency, ad agency, ad agency, ad agency, 

advertising law, FTC, FTC, FTC, FTC, FTC, FTC, FTC, Federal Trade Commission, 

Federal Trade Commission, Federal Trade Commission, Federal Trade Commission, 

lawyer, attorney, advertisement law, legal, compliance, false, unfair, 

deceptive, false, unfair, deceptive ads, deception, advertise">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><font size=4><strong>Advertising Agencies, Advertisers and Their Attorneys 
Astonished<br>
By Size of Costly Fines and Penalties</strong></font></p>
<p>Advertising agencies, advertisers and their attorneys have been amazed by the 
size of costly fines and penalties assessed in Federal Trade Commission (FTC) 
and Court decisions recently. Recent <b>Advertising Compliance Service</b> issues 
have analyzed these decisions offering practical, compliance-oriented analysis and 
commentary. As these decisions illustrate, <i>ignorance of the fast-paced 
developments in advertising law can be a very costly proposition</i>. <u>Remember</u>: 
In each one of these cases, <i>someone</i> had to answer why their--or their 
client's--advertising copy failed to comply with advertising law's countless 
requirements. Here are just a few examples of such cases examined in recent 
<b>Advertising Compliance Service</b> articles:</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> A federal court recently upheld over $16 million in damages against an 
advertiser in a recent Federal Trade Commission case involving allegedly 
deceptive ads. Moreover, the Court held one of the company's officers 
<i>individually liable</i> for that amount! Defendants strenuously argued that the $16 
million exceeded their net worth . . . but to no avail! </p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> One large advertising agency is deemed culpable by a federal agency in a case 
costing the ad agency's advertiser-client $100,000.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Advertising agency execs and attorneys were aghast when a federal judge hit 
an ad agency with $1 million in damages for deceptive advertising.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Advertiser will pay $2.75 million civil penalty to settle charges over national ad 
campaign.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Product demonstrations: What <i>you must know</i> to avoid costly penalties and 
lengthy court and/or government proceedings. How one advertiser paid $150,000 
by not heeding this advice.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Diet firm agrees to $100,00 consumer refund over &quot;unsubstantiated&quot; ad claims.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Advertiser will pay $888,000 civil penalty to settle charges over ad campaign.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Advertiser to pay $150,000 penalty to settle charges over nutritional claims.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Federal ad regulator's finalized consent agreement contains $480,000 refund 
requirement.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Massive direct-mail, sweepstakes case ends with $1.25 million redress to 
consumers.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Government regulator cites misleading ads in investment 
newsletter-respondents ordered to pay civil money penalties totaling $300,000.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Internet advertisers of credit repair program to pay $17,500 in redress.</p>
<p><img src="blue-b~2.gif" align=bottom width=12 height=12> Deceptive advertising charges lead marketer to accept settlement with federal 
regulator and give refunds up to $195,000.</p>
<p>Court and regulatory history is littered with advertisers and ad agencies of every 
size and stripe who erroneously believed it could never happen to them. These 
decisions demonstrate that there is simply no substitute for keeping current with 
the myriad cases, decisions, rulings, rules, regulations, consent decrees and orders 
flowing from the federal and state courts and powerful regulatory bodies. And 
that's exactly what <b>Advertising Compliance Service</b> has been doing for its 
subscribers for 15 years: Helping them keep current with the most important 
advertising compliance information available. </p>
<p>So if you're in any way responsible for preparing or reviewing any advertising 
copy on any medium, you should ask yourself whether you've been keeping up 
with developments involving advertising law's many strictures. Don't wait until 
your ad is the subject of a competitor lawsuit, a federal administrative action, or a 
state attorney general action, with all the attendant fines, penalties, damages, 
attorneys fees, injunctions, recordkeeping requirements, corrective advertising 
expenditures, bad publicity, etc., etc., that this can entail. Otherwise, you may 
have to answer these questions:</p>
<ol>
<li>What went wrong?<br>
</li>
<li>Why did this happen?<br>
</li>
<li>Why wasn't this prevented?<br>
</li>
<li>Who is responsible?<br>
</li>
</ol>
<p>For subscription information, contact JLCom Publishing Co., L.L.C. by e-mail to:  
<a href="mailto:lawpublish@aol.com">lawpublish@aol.com</a> or CALL TOLL FREE: 1-888-ADLAW97. An <a href="order.htm">order 
form </a>is available at this Web Site.</p>
<p>&copy; Copyright 1996 JLCom Publishing Co., L.L.C. All rights reserved. This 
publication, in whole or in part, may not be reproduced, stored in a computerized, 
or other, retrieval system, or transmitted in any form or by any means whatsoever 
without the prior written permission of JLCom Publishing Co., L.L.C. </p>
