<BR><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>
Introducing... InterVU Network
</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><I>The video delivery network.</I></FONT></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="../images/bluebarsm.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><BR></P>
<BR>
<UL>
<H4>
<A HREF="#ANCHOR1511515">What is the InterVU Network?</A>
<BR><A HREF="#ANCHOR3001200">The InterVU Network Solution</A>
<BR><A HREF="#ANCHOR3001600">Technology Overview</A>
<BR><A HREF="#ANCHOR3001400">Performance</A>
<BR><A HREF="#ANCHOR3001300">Client Components of The InterVU Network</A>
<BR><A HREF="#ANCHOR3001500">Summary</A>
</H4>
</UL>
<HR>
<UL>
<A NAME="ANCHOR1511515"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
What is the InterVU Network?
</FONT>
</B>
</FONT>
<P>The InterVU Network is an economical way for Internet Content Providers to speed the delivery of high quality video files that are embedded in their Web sites.  The InterVU service also offloads these large files from the Content Provider's primary Web server, expediting Web site and video access to all viewers. </P>
<BR>
<A NAME="ANCHOR3001200"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
The InterVU Network Solution
</FONT>
</B>
</FONT>

<P>
The traditional approach to distributing video and other large data files is to replicate the Web site on one or more servers, each with its own communication line to the Internet.   These servers may be at the same facility or scattered across the Internet to provide multiple access points. To retrieve a file, the viewer must manually select a mirror server from a displayed list of mirror servers without any knowledge as to whether the server selected will provide the fastest download, or even whether the server is functional.  This approach is generally inefficient and does not result in a consistent improvement in delivery performance.
</P>
<P>
Using the InterVU Network, large audio-video files associated with Web presentations are duplicated on InterVU Network servers for access by viewers who use the intelligent InterVU Player. When a viewer requests a video, content on all of these servers is managed and monitored by an InterVU Control Center around the clock.
</P>
<P>
Content Providers participating in the InterVU service receive performance, usage and demographic statistics.  Content Providers also benefit from the increased exposure generated from the InterVU Video Guide.  The Video Guide consists of Web pages that catalog the audio-video files contained on the InterVU Network servers, so that a viewer can conveniently find videos (and their related Web sites) of interest.
</P>
<BR>
<A NAME="ANCHOR3001600"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
Technology Overview
</FONT>
</B>
</FONT>
<P>
The InterVU Network uses InterVU's Smart Mirror&#153; Technology to manage the process of selecting the proper server to be used for file downloads.  Smart Mirror Technology identifies the InterVU Network server that is electronically closest to a viewer from a group of mirrored servers which are various distances away (more hops, Internet connections or Internet congestion) from the viewer.  By following a pointer (URL) to the closest server, the data "virtually" crosses these extra hops rather than traveling through them.
</P>
<UL>
<LI TYPE=DISC>The InterVU Network servers only contain the audio-video files for a Web site.  The HTML pages including the text, static graphics and, when appropriate, back end databases, all reside on the Content Provider's primary server. The  cost of the primary Web site server and its communication lines is reduced because the site doesn't need the capacity to distribute huge audio-video files.
<BR><BR>
<LI>When a viewer is browsing the Web site using the InterVU Player for viewing videos, an InterVU Network server is automatically accessed based on a calibration which previously chose this server as offering the fastest download time.<BR>
<BR>  
<LI>The Smart Mirror Technology is scaleable.  Additional InterVU Network servers can be added at any time without notifying the viewers or requiring changes to the InterVU Player or the Content Provider's Web site.
</UL>
<P>
InterVU Network servers are connected to the Internet at different locations such that each server is closer (in a communication speed sense) to a set of viewers than any of the other servers.  Video files are duplicated on each of the mirror servers, so viewers can acquire the same file from different servers.
</P>
<A NAME="ANCHOR114995"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+1>SmartVU&#153; Network Optimizer</FONT>
<P>
The InterVU SmartVU Network Optimizer is a utility attached to the InterVU player which analyzes Internet video download performance by testing selected video servers located on  the global InterVU Network.  At the end of the test, an InterVU Network server is selected to provide the "best" overall video performance based on Internet access connections. Each time the viewer clicks on a video which is hosted on the InterVU Network, the viewer is seamlessly and automatically redirected to the optimal InterVU Network server to receive the highest performance from the Internet. 
</P>

<P>
Program Operation:  Pressing the "Start" button initiates  Stage 1 which identifies a list of mirrored video servers that are most likely to provide superior video delivery performance. These sites are listed in the dialog box and presented as numbered dots which are located geographically on the "radar screen".   Stage 2 calculates the number of Internet "electronic links" or hops from each of the mirrored sites being analyzed.  Each of the video sites are then relocated onto the radar screen based on these electronic link measurements.  The number of electronic links are indicated on the outside ring of the radar screen.  Stage 3 tests for optimal video delivery from each of the video sites to the viewer.  In the fourth and final stage, the SmartVU program determines the optimal mirrored site based on an analysis of the test results.   Clicking "OK" saves this site as the video source for the viewer whenever a video is viewed that is on the InterVU Network.  Final test results are automatically emailed to the InterVU Control Center for the continuous improvement of your video delivery performance.
</P> 


<BR>
<A NAME="ANCHOR3001400"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
Performance Comparison
</FONT>
</B>
</FONT>

<P>The following graph demonstrates the dramatic enhancement in video delivery speed which Content Providers can achieve through utilization of the InterVU Network.
</P>
<UL>
<UL>
<IMG SRC="../images/perform1.gif">
</UL>
</UL>
<P>The next graph shows the effects on performance when the video files are located on the Web site server compared to when the video files are located on the InterVU Network.
</P>
<UL>
<UL> 
<IMG SRC="../images/effect1.gif">
</UL>
</UL>
<BR>


<BR> 
<A NAME="ANCHOR3001300"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
Client Components of The InterVU Network 
</FONT>
</B>
</FONT>

<P>
To use the InterVU Network, a viewer needs both the SmartVU Network Optimizer and an InterVU Network Enabled Player.  InterVU has presently made available the SmartVU Network Optimizer and the InterVU Player to support the following environments:<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
      Movie Formats:	MPEG	

Operating Systems:	PC Windows NT and Windows 95	

  	  Browsers:	PC: All 32 bit forms of the Netscape Navigator, 2.0 and greater
			(Note: the current InterVU Player for the Macintosh is not yet "Network Enabled")
</PRE>
<BR>
 InterVU also has an effort underway to integrate Smart Mirror functionality into other players, enabling content developers who work in other formats to benefit from the InterVU Network service.  InterVU is planning on expanding the InterVU Network to support other browser environments, OSs, and video formats:<BR>
<BR> 
<PRE>
      Movie Formats:	AVI, Quicktime, & other cool third party low bit rate A/V formats

Operating Systems:	Windows 3.11

	Browsers:	MAC: 	Netscape Navigator, 2.0 and greater
				Cyberdog

			PC:	Explorer
</PRE>
<BR>
Content Providers can now offload the heavy bandwidth load associated with video from their
Web site and provide a compelling high speed, high quality interactive video experience for their Web
site visitors.
</P>


<BR>
<A NAME="ANCHOR3001500"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
Summary
</FONT>
</B>
</FONT>

<P>The InterVU Network is an easy, economical way for Web Content Providers to improve the delivery of video files embedded in Web pages.  The InterVU Network addresses Internet throughput problems by physically separating the video content from Web pages, and placing them on multiple dedicated video servers which are placed at strategic locations to provide the best redundant high-speed coverage.  The InterVU Network improves performance by seamlessly redirecting a Web video request to a InterVU Network server that can provide the most efficient delivery route and sustained delivery capability.  The InterVU Network accomplishes this using InterVU's proprietary technology.
</P>

<P>InterVU's concentrated effort on the development of the InterVU Network has enabled the company to gain extensive knowledge about Internet performance. We are developing a series of service solutions which will enable Content Providers to significantly improve the quality, speed and cost-effectiveness of video delivery to the viewer without burdening the performance of existing infrastructure.</P>


</UL>
<BR>
