<FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">
How Tos</FONT></B>
</FONT>
<H4>What software and hardware are needed to create MPEG video clips?</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
There are several cards available for MPEG encoding. Each
has certain benefits. For example, a company called <A HREF="http://vitechts.com">Vitec Multimedia</A>, in Sarasota, FL has one product that will give you considerable flexibility in encoding size--thus bandwidth--and costs approximately $700. Unfortunately, this card has no ability to encode sound. Their other product will encode both video and sound for around $1000.  Though we haven't seen it yet, <A HREF="http://www.b-way.com">Data Translation</A> offers their Broadway product for under $1000.
<BR>
<BR>A higher end option, is from <A HREF="http://www.realmagic.com">Sigma
Designs</A>. Their encoder card is called Real Magic Producer.
It comes with powerful video editing software by Adobe but its cost will
definitely make you wallet sting (~$5000). 
<BR>
<BR>There are also software-only video encoding systems, but they are very
slow. There are several available for free from various WEB sites, such
as <A HREF="http://www.visiblelight.com/mpeg.htp">The MPEG Plaza</A>.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="features">
<H4>How do I use the InterVU Player and its features in the Web pages I create?</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>To add the InterVU Player to your Web pages, you use the EMBED tag which allows documents of varying data types to be embedded into an HTML file. This command has three required attributes, SRC, WIDTH, and HEIGHT. The command will also support parameters designed to customize video playback; these parameters are listed below. On the other hand, if you wish to have the file play by itself in a Netscape window, you may also use a standard HTML reference such as: <P>&lt;A REF=&quot;http://www.yoursite.com/coolvideo.mpg&quot;&gt;Link
to MPEG&lt;/A&gt;.</P>
<H4>Required Parameters:</H4>
<P><B>SRC=&lt;URL&gt; </B></P>
<UL>
<P>The <B>EMBED</B> tag allows documents of varying data types to
be embedded into an HTML file. This command has three required
attributes, <B>SRC</B>, <B>WIDTH</B>, and <B>HEIGHT</B>. The command
will also support parameters designed to customize video playback.</P>
<B>SRC=&lt;URL&gt;</B>
<UL>
The URL, or Internet location, of the source MPEG document.
This file must have a MIME type of video/mpeg or video/x-mpeg.
This parameter is required. 
</UL>
<BR>
<B>WIDTH=&lt;size in pixels&gt;</B>
<UL>
The <B>WIDTH</B> attribute specifies the width of the displayed
image of the embedded MPEG document in pixels. You'll need to
add 10 pixels to the width of the video in order to show the frame
around the displayed image. If <B>DOUBLESIZE</B> or <B>HALFSIZE</B>
attributes are also used, you will have to use double or half
of the actual video size, respectively, in your calculation (details
below). If <B>WIDTH</B> is <I>greater</I> than the size of the
video plus the frame, then the excess will be displayed as a white
border surrounding the Player. If <B>WIDTH</B> is <I>less</I>
than the size of the video plus the frame, then the Player will
be cropped and centered within the remaining area. This parameter is required.</UL>
<BR>
<B>HEIGHT=&lt;size in pixels&gt;</B>
<UL>
The <B>HEIGHT</B> attribute specifies the height of the displayed
document in pixels. You'll need to add 29 pixels to the height
of the video frame in order to show the control bar of the InterVU Player. If the <B>CONBAR=NO</B> attribute is set, then only
10 pixels would be added (details below). If <B>DOUBLESIZE</B>
or <B>HALFSIZE</B> attributes are also used, you will have to
use double or half of the actual video size, respectively, in
your calculation (details below). If <B>HEIGHT</B> is <I>greater</I>
than the size of the video plus the frame, then the excess will
be displayed as a white border surrounding the Player. If <B>HEIGHT</B>
is <I>less</I> than the size of the video plus the frame, then
the Player will be cropped and centered within the remaining area.
This parameter is required.</UL>
<BR>
<B>AUTOPLAY=&lt;YES&gt;</B>
<UL>
The <B>AUTOPLAY</B> attribute is an optional parameter. If
set to YES, the video starts playing automatically when the &quot;Web page&quot;
is selected or viewed. The default is <B>NO</B>. Specifying <B>AUTOPLAY=NO</B>
(or by not including the <B>AUTOPLAY</B> parameter) will cause
the first frame of the video to be displayed when the page is
loaded. The user must then start the video manually.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>PLUGINSPAGE=&lt;URL&gt;</B>
<UL>
When a page is viewed that needs a plug-in not found on the
client, a special icon is displayed in place of the plug-in. The
first time the unknown plug-in type is invoked, a dialog box is
automatically opened. This dialog box contains two buttons: Plug-in
Info and Cancel. Clicking on Plug-in Info causes Navigator to
open a URL. The URL is either the location specified in the PLUGINSPAGE
attribute in the EMBED tag, or if the attribute is not used, the
Netscape page that lists current plug-ins. The URL generally contains
information on obtaining the plug-in or the ability to download
and save the plug-in in the correct location on the client. InterVU
encourages content providers to include the <B>PLUGINSPAGE</B>
attribute with a value of <B>&quot;http://www.intervu.com&quot;</B>
in their HTML pages to make it easier for users to access the
InterVU Player.
</UL>

<H4>Additional optional parameters:</H4>



<B>SM=&lt;video path&gt;</B><BR>
<I>This feature is not available for the Macintosh version at this time.</I>
<UL>  
This parameter directs the Player to obtain the video file from the InterVU Network server.  The video path is the directory tree in which the video file is placed.  InterVU assigns a unique video path  to each customer.
</UL> 
<BR>
<B>PG=&lt;XYZ&gt;</B><BR>
<I>This feature is not available for the Macintosh version at this time.</I>
<UL>
This parameter is used to communicate the rating of the video. The interpretation is:
<UL>
X = The "adult" rating of the video.<BR>
Y = the "profanity" rating of the video.<BR>
Z = the "violence" rating of the video.<BR>
</UL>
Each X, Y and Z is a value from 0 to 2, where
<UL>
2 = suitable for family viewing.<BR>
1 = parental guidance advised, mature audience, equivalent to broadcast TV.<BR>
0 = extreme content, potentially very offensive.<BR>
</UL>
To enable the end user to send a recommended rating of the video back to the Web site, use the parameter NOTIFY="email address", where the email address is the full email address of the recipient of the email.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>FRAMERATE=&lt;Number&gt;</B><BR>
<UL>
You may use this attribute to decrease the frame rate for
the MPEG file being displayed. Use positive integers from 1 to
25, representing how many frames (or separate video images) are
played per second. The smaller the number you enter, the slower
the video will play. It is best to adjust the number entered in
the parameter until you get the result you would like. Please
note that sound is dependent on the file playing at its normal
rate. So if the FRAMERATE option is used, the file will play without
sound.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>LOOP=&lt;Number&gt;</B>
<UL>
If you would like the video to loop, you may use this attribute
and enter the number of times you would like it to loop. Each
time the start button is pressed, the video will play the specified
number of times.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>DOUBLESIZE=&lt;YES&gt;</B><BR>
<UL>
This attribute configures the InterVU Player
to play the video at double the encoded size. The default value
is <B>NO</B>. The <B>DOUBLESIZE</B> attribute may not be used
with <B>HALFSIZE</B> in the same <B>EMBED</B> statement. The <B>HEIGHT</B>
and <B>WIDTH</B> attribute values must be changed when this attribute
is used.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>HALFSIZE=&lt;YES&gt;</B><BR>
<UL>
This attribute configures the InterVU Player to play the video at half the encoded size. The default value
is <B>NO</B>. The <B>HALFSIZE</B> attribute may not be used with
<B>DOUBLESIZE</B> in the same <B>EMBED</B> statement. The <B>HEIGHT</B>
and <B>WIDTH</B> attribute values must be changed when this attribute
is used.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>CONBAR=&lt;NO&gt;</B>
<UL>
You may disable the &quot;controls&quot; bar of the InterVU Player with this option. When the control bar is disabled, just click on the video to start/stop the video. You will need to recalculate
the number of pixels you add to the original video size so the display area will not show space for the control bar. The control bar's height is 19 pixels, so instead of adding 29 pixels, you
will only need to add 10 pixels. The default value is <B>YES</B>.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>FRAMES=&lt;YES&gt;</B>
<UL>
This attribute is required if you are creating a Web page
with Netscape FRAMES. For viewers using a Mac, the video will
autoplay. For all other viewers, the <B>FRAMES</B> attribute will
be ignored, and the video will play according to how you set the
<B>AUTOPLAY</B> attribute (where the default is <B>NO</B>.) </UL>
<BR>
<B>PALETTE=&lt;FOREGROUND&gt;</B><BR>
<UL>
The <B>PALETTE</B> option configures how colors are displayed
when the InterVU Player is viewed on machines that are running in 256-color mode. Leaving
this to default as <B>FOREGROUND</B> allows the InterVU Player to take control of all 256-colors and obtain the best possible
image quality for displayed movies; other images embedded within
the browser window may suffer slight degradation in quality. If
<B>PALETTE</B> is set to <B>BACKGROUND</B>, then Netscape is allowed
to retain control of all 256 colors. This will result in slight
degradation in the quality of the displayed movie, and may improve
surrounding images, however results vary widely depending on image
content. This setting is ignored when the client is running in
color modes greater than 256-color. In those modes, best color
fidelity is achieved at all times regardless the of <B>PALETTE</B>
setting. 
</UL>

<H4>HTML Example:</H4>

<UL>
<B>&lt;EMBED SRC=&quot;Sample.mpg&quot;, WIDTH=174, HEIGHT=134,
CONBAR=NO, LOOP=YES&gt;</B>
</UL>
<UL>
Note: When using the <B>EMBED</B> tag, a space is required
before each attribute. An optional comma may be added to improve
readability.</UL>
</UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="ANCHOR2401200"></A><FONT SIZE=+2><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C">Performance</FONT></B>
</FONT>
<H4>What have you found frame rates to be on Pentium 100's or PowerMacs using 28.8 kbps modem links, a robust server, optimized regularly, MPEG hardware, and 160 x 120 window size?</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The video stream bandwidth requirement is the pacing item. For MPEG-1, the
&quot;normal&quot; stream size should be around 1.5 megabits per second (mbps). A 28.8 kbps will
not play a &quot;normal&quot; MPEG video very fast (1 frame per 2 seconds.)
We reduce the size of the video frame to reduce the bandwidth requirements
by approximately a factor of four. Therefore, the frame rate increases to 2 fps on a 28.8 kbps modem for a 120 x 160 image. Often times the video is compressed more to increase throughput. This increase may improve throughput by 50% to approximately 8 fps. Some display artifacts may be introduced with this level of compression. 
<BR>
<BR>The server performance is dependent on the bandwidth requirements of the video
stream. The number of users supported is heavily dependent on the bandwidth requirements described above, the type and configuration of the server, the amount of disk activity, the connection to the network, and the type and quantity of other users on the server. Depending on the bandwidth of the video stream as defined above, you may expect to support anywhere
from 5 to 50 simultaneous users of the server. 
<BR>
<BR>MPEG hardware enables the personal computer to play larger videos without system performance degradation.  The Player does not currently make use of MPEG decoding hardware. 
<BR>
<BR>
Video size a very important factor for remote playback since using a smaller
video lowers the transmission bandwidth needs. During local cached playback,
the performance of the personal computer is the limiting factor for real time decoding.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="ANCHOR2401300"></A><B><FONT COLOR="#DC143C"><FONT SIZE=+2>Problems
</FONT></B></FONT>
<H4>I recently downloaded the InterVU Player for Netscape 2.0+.
I made an HTML file on my hard drive and embedded a small MPEG video in
it. It worked great! But when I uploaded this page to my Web site on my
local server and viewed it in Netscape online, it didn't work. Netscape
would ask me if I wanted to use naplayer.exe. Then a dummy picture would
appear where the video should be. So I made a link on the page to download
the video. And when I click on that, a new document loads up with the video
embedded in the page! I even went to your example page and the embedded
video did not work. Does my server need any configuration?</H4>

<BLOCKQUOTE>See if these comments regarding the installation help you
identify where the configuration problem lies. The server is probably not the problem. WEB servers only dish up files per the browsers request; however, your server does need to be configured such that the MIME type for MPEG files is either video/mpeg or video/x-mpeg. 
<BR>
<BR>To see if you have the InterVU Player installed correctly, here
are a few things to check. First, select &quot;Help&quot; on the Netscape
Menu Bar, then &quot;About Plug-ins&quot;. You should see &quot;video/mpeg&quot;
and &quot;video/x-mpeg&quot; listed. If these entries are not included,
then the Player was not installed correctly. 
<BR>
<BR>The InterVU Player is installed in two directories. The file Npivmpg.dll
is located in the plugin directory of Netscape and calls Ivplayer.dll and sndstrm.dll,
located in the InterVU directory, which is a subdirectory of the plugin
directory. If Npivmpg.dll can not find Ivplayer.dll or Sndstrm.dll, the program will abort.
Make sure all files are where they belong. 
<BR>
<BR>Finally, select &quot;Options&quot; from the Netscape menu bar, then
&quot;General Preferences&quot; and then the &quot;Helpers&quot; tab. If
&quot;video/mpeg&quot; is included in the list of file types, make sure
that nothing is listed under the action column for that entry. Netscape
may get &quot;confused&quot; if a helper application and a plug-in are simultaneously
installed for the same file/MIME type. 
<BR>
<BR>The way the InterVU Player, or more specifically, Netscape, &quot;knows&quot;
that a file is an MPEG video is if you name the file with either an MPG,
MPE, or MPEG extension. This extension type is what net folks call a MIME
extension. Not all extensions are &quot;approved&quot;, or official. Those
extensions which are pending MIME type approval have the prefix &quot;x-&quot;
... as in x-mpeg. Did you save your file with one of the above extensions?
<BR>
<BR>This information should help you figure out what is causing your specific
problem.
<BR>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</UL>
